    "system.aluminum.title": "Aluminum",
    "system.aluminum.desc": "The most abundant metal in the Earth's crust, lightweight and corrosion-resistant.",
    "system.aluminum.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Al<br>• Atomic Number — 13<br>• A post-transition metal from the 13th group<br>• Most abundant metal in the Earth's crust<br>• Lightweight, silvery-white, and durable metal<br>• Non-magnetic and non-sparking<br>• Highly resistant to corrosion due to its oxide layer<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 13 protons in the nucleus<br>• 13 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 14 neutrons (Aluminum-27)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ne] 3s² 3p¹<br>• Located in the 3rd period and 13th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Low density (approx. 2.70 g/cm³)<br>• Boiling point — 2470°C<br>• Melting point — 660.3°C<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Excellent malleability and ductility<br>• Reflects about 92% of visible light<br>• Remains strong at very low temperatures<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with oxygen to form a thin protective Al₂O₃ layer<br>• Amphoteric: reacts with both acids and strong bases<br>• Not easily flammable in solid form, but powder is explosive<br>• Forms trivalent compounds (oxidation state +3)<br>• Reacts with halogens to form halides<br><br><b>Aluminum Isotopes</b><br>• Aluminum-27 (²⁷Al) — the only stable natural isotope<br>• Aluminum-26 (²⁶Al) — radioactive, used in radiometric dating<br>• Artificial isotopes used in scientific tracing<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in minerals like Bauxite and Cryolite<br>• Present in gems like Rubies and Sapphires (as Al₂O₃)<br>• Never found in free elemental form in nature<br>• Found in almost all rocks and soils<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Hall-Héroult process (electrolysis of alumina)<br>• Bayer process (extraction from bauxite ore)<br>• Recyclable indefinitely with low energy cost<br><br><b>Applications of Aluminum</b><br>• Aerospace industry ('the winged metal')<br>• Packaging: foil, beverage cans, and containers<br>• Construction: window frames, roofs, and siding<br>• Transportation: car bodies and train components<br>• High-voltage power transmission lines<br><br><b>Significance in Science</b><br>• Fundamental for modern lightweight engineering<br>• Essential for the development of sustainable transport<br>• Key material for cryogenic technology<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Engineering — aircraft and vehicle design<br>• Food Industry — safe packaging and utensils<br>• Construction — modern skyscrapers and bridges<br>• Energy — efficient electrical grids",
    "system.aluminum.fact": "Aluminum has the atomic number 13 and is a member of the Post-Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.aluminum": "Wikipedia - Aluminum",
    "resource.pubchem.aluminum": "PubChem - Aluminum",
    "ai.aluminum.simple": "Aluminum is a chemical element with symbol Al and atomic number 13. It belongs to the Post-Transition Metal group.",
    "ai.aluminum.detailed": "Aluminum (Al) is element number 13 in the periodic table. As a post-transition metal, it exhibits unique chemical and physical properties that make it vital in various industrial and biological processes.",
