    "system.silicon.title": "Silicon",
    "system.silicon.desc": "The foundation of modern electronics and the second most abundant element in the Earth's crust.",
    "system.silicon.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Si<br>• Atomic Number — 14<br>• A metalloid from the 14th group<br>• Second most abundant element in Earth's crust (after oxygen)<br>• Hard, brittle crystalline solid with a blue-grey metallic luster<br>• Foundation of modern electronics and computing<br>• Never found free in nature; exists as silica or silicates<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 14 protons in the nucleus<br>• 14 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 14 neutrons (Silicon-28)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ne] 3s² 3p²<br>• Located in the 3rd period and 14th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Solid at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — 3265°C<br>• Melting point — 1414°C<br>• Semiconductor: conductivity increases with temperature<br>• Low thermal expansion and high hardness<br>• Transparent to infrared radiation<br>• Crystal structure like diamond<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Relatively unreactive at room temperature<br>• Forms silica (SiO₂) when heated with oxygen<br>• Reacts with halogens to form tetrahalides (e.g., SiCl₄)<br>• Forms silicides with many metals<br>• Oxidation states — +4 and -4<br>• Resistant to most acids except hydrofluoric acid<br><br><b>Silicon Isotopes</b><br>• Silicon-28 (²⁸Si) — most abundant stable isotope (92.2%)<br>• Silicon-29 (²⁹Si) — stable isotope (4.7%)<br>• Silicon-30 (³⁰Si) — stable isotope (3.1%)<br>• Used in NMR spectroscopy and semiconductor research<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in sand, quartz, and flint (as SiO₂)<br>• Major component of clay, granite, and many rocks<br>• Essential part of the Earth's mantle and crust<br>• Found in some biological structures like diatom shells<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Reduction of silica with carbon in electric arc furnaces<br>• Siemens process for ultra-pure electronic-grade silicon<br>• Czochralski method for growing single-crystal ingots<br><br><b>Applications of Silicon</b><br>• Microchips, transistors, and solar cells (semiconductors)<br>• Glass and ceramic manufacturing<br>• Silicones: lubricants, sealants, and medical implants<br>• Aluminum alloys for engine blocks<br>• Concrete and brick production<br><br><b>Significance in Science</b><br>• Enabling element for the Information Age<br>• Critical for renewable energy (photovoltaics)<br>• Vital for understanding geology and planetary science<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Electronics — CPU and memory manufacturing<br>• Energy — solar power technology<br>• Medicine — biocompatible silicone implants<br>• Construction — glass and building materials",
    "system.silicon.fact": "Silicon has the atomic number 14 and is a member of the Metalloid group.",
    "resource.wiki.silicon": "Wikipedia - Silicon",
    "resource.pubchem.silicon": "PubChem - Silicon",
    "ai.silicon.simple": "Silicon is a chemical element with symbol Si and atomic number 14. It belongs to the Metalloid group.",
    "ai.silicon.detailed": "Silicon (Si) is element number 14 in the periodic table. As a metalloid, it exhibits unique chemical and physical properties that make it vital in various industrial and biological processes.",
