    "system.phosphorus.title": "Phosphorus",
    "system.phosphorus.desc": "A vital element that is part of DNA, bones, and provides energy transfer in cells.",
    "system.phosphorus.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — P<br>• Atomic Number — 15<br>• A highly reactive nonmetal from the 15th group<br>• Essential for all living organisms (DNA, ATP)<br>• Exists in several allotropic forms (white, red, black)<br>• White phosphorus glows in the dark (chemiluminescence)<br>• Never found as a free element in nature<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 15 protons in the nucleus<br>• 15 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 16 neutrons (Phosphorus-31)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ne] 3s² 3p³<br>• Located in the 3rd period and 15th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• White phosphorus: waxy solid, poisonous, flammable<br>• Red phosphorus: amorphous solid, stable, non-toxic<br>• Boiling point — 280.5°C (white)<br>• Melting point — 44.1°C (white)<br>• Poor conductor of heat and electricity<br>• Insoluble in water, but white P dissolves in carbon disulfide<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Spontaneously ignites in air (white phosphorus)<br>• Reacts with halogens to form trihalides and pentahalides<br>• Forms phosphine (PH₃), a highly toxic gas<br>• Forms phosphoric acid (H₃PO₄) when oxides react with water<br>• Common oxidation states — +3, +5, and -3<br><br><b>Phosphorus Isotopes</b><br>• Phosphorus-31 (³¹P) — the only stable natural isotope<br>• Phosphorus-32 (³²P) — radioactive, used as a tracer in biology and medicine<br>• Phosphorus-33 (³³P) — radioactive, used in biochemical research<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in phosphate rocks (e.g., Apatite)<br>• Present in fertile soils and seawater<br>• Major component of bones and teeth in animals<br>• Crucial part of the DNA backbone and energy-carrying ATP<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced by heating phosphate rock with silica and coke in electric furnaces<br>• Red phosphorus is made by heating white phosphorus in an inert atmosphere<br>• Purified through sublimation and distillation<br><br><b>Applications of Phosphorus</b><br>• Agricultural fertilizers (superphosphates)<br>• Safety matches (red phosphorus on the striker)<br>• Steel manufacturing (deoxidizer)<br>• Detergents and water softeners<br>• Pyrotechnics and tracer bullets<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Fundamental for energy transfer in cells (ATP cycle)<br>• Essential for genetic information storage (DNA/RNA)<br>• Critical for bone structural integrity (calcium phosphate)<br>• Important in understanding mineral nutrition and ecology<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Biology — metabolic energy and genetics<br>• Agriculture — global food security via fertilizers<br>• Medicine — bone health and radiopharmaceuticals<br>• Industry — metallurgical and chemical manufacturing",
    "system.phosphorus.fact": "Phosphorus has the atomic number 15 and is a member of the Nonmetal group.",
    "resource.wiki.phosphorus": "Wikipedia - Phosphorus",
    "resource.pubchem.phosphorus": "PubChem - Phosphorus",
    "ai.phosphorus.simple": "Phosphorus is a chemical element with symbol P and atomic number 15. It belongs to the Nonmetal group.",
    "ai.phosphorus.detailed": "Phosphorus (P) is element number 15 in the periodic table. As a nonmetal, it exhibits unique chemical and physical properties that make it vital in various industrial and biological processes.",
