    "system.sulfur.title": "Sulfur",
    "system.sulfur.desc": "A lemon-yellow nonmetal essential for protein creation and sulfuric acid production.",
    "system.sulfur.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — S<br>• Atomic Number — 16<br>• A bright yellow nonmetal from the 16th group (Chalcogens)<br>• Brittle, odorless, and insoluble in water<br>• Essential for all life, found in amino acids and proteins<br>• Known since ancient times (brimstone)<br>• Forms a wide variety of compounds, including sulfuric acid<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 16 protons in the nucleus<br>• 16 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 16 neutrons (Sulfur-32)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ne] 3s² 3p⁴<br>• Located in the 3rd period and 16th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Solid at room temperature (cyclooctasulfur S₈)<br>• Boiling point — 444.6°C<br>• Melting point — 115.2°C<br>• Poor electrical and thermal conductor<br>• Exists in multiple allotropes (rhombic, monoclinic)<br>• Emits a blue flame when burned<br>• Dissolves in carbon disulfide and benzene<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with oxygen to form sulfur dioxide (SO₂)<br>• Reacts with most metals to form sulfides<br>• Forms sulfuric acid (H₂SO₄), the 'king of chemicals'<br>• Forms hydrogen sulfide (H₂S), which has a rotten egg smell<br>• Common oxidation states — -2, +4, and +6<br><br><b>Sulfur Isotopes</b><br>• Sulfur-32 (³²S) — most abundant stable isotope (95.02%)<br>• Sulfur-33 (³³S) — stable isotope (0.75%)<br>• Sulfur-34 (³⁴S) — stable isotope (4.21%)<br>• Sulfur-36 (³⁶S) — very rare stable isotope (0.02%)<br>• Isotope ratios used to track pollution and biological activity<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in its elemental state near volcanoes and hot springs<br>• Present in minerals like Pyrite (fool's gold) and Gypsum<br>• Found in fossil fuels (coal, oil, natural gas)<br>• Found in essential proteins and vitamins (B1, H)<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Frasch process (pumping superheated water into deposits)<br>• Claus process (recovering sulfur from natural gas and oil)<br>• Byproduct of copper and zinc smelting<br><br><b>Applications of Sulfur</b><br>• Production of sulfuric acid (fertilizers, batteries)<br>• Vulcanization of rubber (tires, elastic materials)<br>• Gunpowder and fireworks manufacturing<br>• Fungicides and pesticides for agriculture<br>• Bleaching agent for paper and textiles<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential component of amino acids (cysteine and methionine)<br>• Forms disulfide bridges that stabilize protein structures (hair, nails)<br>• Fundamental in the study of geochemical cycles<br>• Critical for heavy chemical industrial development<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Biology — protein structure and enzyme function<br>• Agriculture — crop protection and soil pH adjustment<br>• Industry — rubber, paper, and battery production<br>• Environment — study of acid rain and air quality",
    "system.sulfur.fact": "Sulfur has the atomic number 16 and is a member of the Nonmetal group.",
    "resource.wiki.sulfur": "Wikipedia - Sulfur",
    "resource.pubchem.sulfur": "PubChem - Sulfur",
