    "system.chlorine.title": "Chlorine",
    "system.chlorine.desc": "Chlorine is element #17, a versatile halogen essential for various scientific applications.",
    "system.chlorine.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Cl<br>• Atomic Number — 17<br>• A highly reactive pale green gas from the Halogens group<br>• Powerful oxidizing agent used for disinfection<br>• Essential for life, found in salt and stomach acid<br>• Second lightest halogen after fluorine<br>• Distinctive, suffocating odor even at low concentrations<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 17 protons in the nucleus<br>• 17 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 18 neutrons (Chlorine-35)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ne] 3s² 3p⁵<br>• Located in the 3rd period and 17th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Gas at standard temperature and pressure<br>• Boiling point — −34.04°C<br>• Melting point — −101.5°C<br>• 2.5 times denser than air<br>• Pale yellow-green color<br>• Soluble in water (forms chlorine water)<br>• Liquefies easily under pressure<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with nearly all elements<br>• Supports combustion of many substances<br>• Reacts with water to form hypochlorous acid (HClO)<br>• Strong bleaching and disinfecting properties<br>• Forms ionic chlorides with metals and covalent chlorides with non-metals<br>• Common oxidation states — -1, +1, +3, +5, and +7<br><br><b>Chlorine Isotopes</b><br>• Chlorine-35 (³⁵Cl) — stable isotope (75.77%)<br>• Chlorine-37 (³⁷Cl) — stable isotope (24.23%)<br>• Chlorine-36 (³⁶Cl) — radioactive tracer found in the environment<br>• Isotope ratios used for geological dating and tracking water sources<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Primarily found as Chloride ions (Cl⁻) in seawater<br>• Found in mineral deposits as Halite (NaCl) and Sylvite (KCl)<br>• Essential component of solar system's planetary crusts<br>• Never found as a free gas in nature due to high reactivity<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Chloralkali process (electrolysis of brine)<br>• Produced as a coproduct with sodium hydroxide and hydrogen<br>• Liquefied and transported in pressurized tanks<br><br><b>Applications of Chlorine</b><br>• Water purification and swimming pool sanitation<br>• Production of PVC (polyvinyl chloride) plastic<br>• Bleaching agent for paper and textiles<br>• Manufacture of pharmaceuticals and disinfectants<br>• Synthesis of agricultural chemicals (pesticides)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential electrolyte for maintaining fluid balance in humans<br>• Component of hydrochloric acid in the stomach for digestion<br>• Crucial for industrial organic chemistry and polymer science<br>• Fundamental in the study of oxidation-reduction reactions<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Biology — digestion and cellular electrolyte balance<br>• Medicine — disinfection and drug synthesis<br>• Industry — plastics, textiles, and paper production<br>• Ecology — monitoring water quality and ozone depletion",
    "system.chlorine.fact": "Chlorine has the atomic number 17 and is a member of the Halogen group.",
    "resource.wiki.chlorine": "Wikipedia - Chlorine",
    "resource.pubchem.chlorine": "PubChem - Chlorine",
    "ai.chlorine.simple": "Chlorine is a chemical element with symbol Cl and atomic number 17. It belongs to the Halogen group.",
    "ai.chlorine.detailed": "Chlorine (Cl) is element number 17 in the periodic table. As a halogen, it exhibits unique chemical and physical properties that make it vital in various industrial and biological processes.",
    "ai.chlorine.study.1": "Atomic number: 17",
