    "system.argon.title": "Argon",
    "system.argon.desc": "Argon is element #18, a versatile noble gas essential for various scientific applications.",
    "system.argon.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ar<br>• Atomic Number — 18<br>• A noble gas from the 18th group<br>• Third most abundant gas in Earth's atmosphere (0.93%)<br>• Completely colorless, odorless, and tasteless<br>• Chemically inert, providing a protective atmosphere<br>• Non-flammable and non-toxic<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 18 protons in the nucleus<br>• 18 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 22 neutrons (Argon-40)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ne] 3s² 3p⁶ (full octet)<br>• Located in the 3rd period and 18th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Gas at standard conditions<br>• Boiling point — −185.8°C<br>• Melting point — −189.3°C<br>• Slightly denser than air<br>• 2.5 times more soluble in water than nitrogen<br>• Forms a distinct violet-blue glow in an electric discharge<br>• Low thermal conductivity<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Extremely inert, forms no stable compounds at room temperature<br>• Only highly unstable compounds (like ArH⁺) exist in lab conditions<br>• Does not support combustion<br>• Used to shield reactive materials from air<br>• Exists as monatomic atoms (Ar)<br><br><b>Argon Isotopes</b><br>• Argon-40 (⁴⁰Ar) — most abundant stable isotope (99.6%)<br>• Argon-36 (³⁶Ar) — stable isotope (0.33%)<br>• Argon-38 (³⁸Ar) — stable isotope (0.06%)<br>• Argon-39 (³⁹Ar) — used for dating groundwater and ice cores<br>• Argon-40 is formed by the radioactive decay of potassium-40<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Makes up 0.934% of the Earth's atmosphere by volume<br>• Present in the Earth's crust as a result of radioactive decay<br>• Found in volcanic gases<br>• Present in space, formed during stellar nucleosynthesis<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Fractional distillation of liquid air<br>• Separated from nitrogen and oxygen in air separation units<br>• Stored and transported in gas cylinders or cryogenic tanks<br><br><b>Applications of Argon</b><br>• Shielding gas for arc welding (TIG welding)<br>• Fill gas for incandescent and fluorescent light bulbs<br>• Inert atmosphere for growing semiconductor crystals<br>• Double-pane window insulation (low thermal conductivity)<br>• Preservation of historical documents and food products<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Industry</b><br>• Vital for high-temperature industrial processes<br>• Essential for Potassium-Argon dating in geology<br>• Used in particle physics detectors (TPCs)<br>• Important for non-reactive storage in chemical labs<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Engineering — precision welding and manufacturing<br>• Electronics — semiconductor production<br>• Geology — dating Earth's historical events<br>• Physics — study of gas discharges and particle detection<br>• Conservation — protecting delicate artifacts from oxidation",
    "system.argon.fact": "Argon has the atomic number 18 and is a member of the Noble Gas group.",
    "resource.wiki.argon": "Wikipedia - Argon",
    "resource.pubchem.argon": "PubChem - Argon",
    "ai.argon.simple": "Argon is a chemical element with symbol Ar and atomic number 18. It belongs to the Noble Gas group.",
    "ai.argon.detailed": "Argon (Ar) is element number 18 in the periodic table. As a noble gas, it exhibits unique chemical and physical properties that make it vital in various industrial and biological processes.",
