    "system.potassium.title": "Potassium",
    "system.potassium.desc": "Potassium is element #19, a versatile alkali metal essential for various scientific applications.",
    "system.potassium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — K<br>• Atomic Number — 19<br>• A highly reactive alkali metal from the 1st group<br>• Soft, silvery-white metal that can be cut with a knife<br>• Essential mineral for all living cells and nerve function<br>• Reacts even more violently with water than sodium<br>• Must be stored in mineral oil to prevent oxidation<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 19 protons in the nucleus<br>• 19 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 20 neutrons (Potassium-39)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 4s¹<br>• Located in the 4th period and 1st group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Second least dense metal after lithium<br>• Boiling point — 759°C<br>• Melting point — 63.5°C<br>• Silvery luster that tarnishes to grey instantly in air<br>• Excellent electrical and thermal conductor<br>• Low electronegativity and high electropositivity<br>• Forms a lilac or light purple flame during a flame test<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts violently with water → forms potassium hydroxide and hydrogen<br>• The hydrogen gas often ignites spontaneously due to the heat of reaction<br>• Forms ionic bonds with non-metals (e.g., KCl)<br>• Powerful reducing agent used in chemical synthesis<br>• Rapidly forms peroxides and superoxides if exposed to air<br>• Common oxidation state — +1<br><br><b>Potassium Isotopes</b><br>• Potassium-39 (³⁹K) — most abundant stable isotope (93.3%)<br>• Potassium-41 (⁴¹K) — stable isotope (6.7%)<br>• Potassium-40 (⁴⁰K) — radioactive, used in geology (K-Ar dating)<br>• Natural potassium is slightly radioactive due to the presence of ⁴⁰K<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• 7th most abundant element in the Earth's crust<br>• Found in minerals like Sylvite (KCl) and Carnallite<br>• Present in seawater at concentrations of about 0.04%<br>• Never found free in nature due to high reactivity<br>• Abundant in land plants and fruits (e.g., bananas)<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Reduction of molten potassium chloride with sodium vapor<br>• Fractional distillation of liquid potassium-sodium alloys<br>• Produced from mineral deposits via mining and refining<br><br><b>Applications of Potassium</b><br>• Agricultural fertilizers (Potash) for plant growth<br>• Production of liquid soaps (potassium hydroxide)<br>• Component of gunpowder and pyrotechnics (potassium nitrate)<br>• Glass manufacturing and specialized optics<br>• Potassium-ion batteries (developing technology)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Major intracellular cation in the human body<br>• Essential for maintaining electrical potential in nerve cells<br>• Critical for muscle contraction and heart rhythm regulation<br>• Fundamental in the study of electrolyte balance and cellular pumps<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Biology — nerve signaling and cellular metabolism<br>• Agriculture — essential nutrient for global crop production<br>• Geology — determining the age of rocks via K-Ar dating<br>• Chemistry — synthesis of organic and inorganic compounds<br>• Medicine — treatment of hypokalemia and electrolyte solutions",
    "system.potassium.fact": "Potassium has the atomic number 19 and is a member of the Alkali Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.potassium": "Wikipedia - Potassium",
    "resource.pubchem.potassium": "PubChem - Potassium",
