    "system.calcium.title": "Calcium",
    "system.calcium.desc": "Calcium is element #20, a versatile alkaline earth essential for various scientific applications.",
    "system.calcium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ca<br>• Atomic Number — 20<br>• An alkaline earth metal from the 2nd group<br>• Essential mineral for all living organisms, especially for bones and teeth<br>• Silvery metal that tarnishes rapidly in air<br>• 5th most abundant element in the Earth's crust<br>• Key component in structural materials like cement and lime<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 20 protons in the nucleus<br>• 20 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 20 neutrons (Calcium-40)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 4s²<br>• Located in the 4th period and 2nd group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Soft metal (harder than lead, can be cut with difficulty)<br>• Boiling point — 1484°C<br>• Melting point — 842°C<br>• Relatively low density compared to other metals<br>• Silvery-white appearance when pure<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Forms an orange-red flame during a flame test<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with water to release hydrogen gas and form calcium hydroxide<br>• Less reactive than alkali metals but more reactive than magnesium<br>• Reacts with oxygen to form calcium oxide (CaO), also known as quicklime<br>• Forms ionic bonds with non-metals (e.g., CaCl₂, CaCO₃)<br>• Strong reducing agent used in metallurgical processes<br>• Common oxidation state — +2<br><br><b>Calcium Isotopes</b><br>• Calcium-40 (⁴⁰Ca) — most abundant stable isotope (96.9%)<br>• Calcium-44 (⁴⁴Ca) — stable isotope (2.1%)<br>• Calcium-48 (⁴⁸Ca) — very rare, nearly stable isotope<br>• Isotope analysis used to study nutritional cycles and medical diagnostics<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in massive deposits of Limestone, Chalk, and Marble (CaCO₃)<br>• Present in minerals like Gypsum, Fluorite, and Apatite<br>• Abundant in seawater as dissolved calcium salts<br>• Never found free in nature due to high reactivity<br>• Essential component of shells, skeletons, and corals<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Electrolysis of molten calcium chloride (CaCl₂)<br>• Thermal reduction of lime with aluminum in a vacuum<br>• Obtained from natural minerals via chemical processing and refining<br><br><b>Applications of Calcium</b><br>• Construction industry: cement, mortar, and concrete<br>• Steelmaking: removing impurities (deoxidizer and desulfurizer)<br>• Production of paper, glass, and plastics as a filler<br>• Food industry: calcium fortification and additives<br>• Agriculture: soil treatment (lime) to adjust pH<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Primary structural component of bones and teeth (hydroxyapatite)<br>• Essential for blood clotting and muscle contraction<br>• Acts as a secondary messenger in cellular signaling pathways<br>• Fundamental in the study of mineralization and skeletal health<br>• Critical for the carbon cycle (formation of marine carbonates)<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Biology — skeletal structure and cell signaling<br>• Medicine — bone health supplements and diagnostics<br>• Construction — foundational building materials<br>• Geology — formation of sedimentary rocks and fossils<br>• Industry — metallurgical and chemical processing",
    "system.calcium.fact": "Calcium has the atomic number 20 and is a member of the Alkaline Earth group.",
    "resource.wiki.calcium": "Wikipedia - Calcium",
    "resource.pubchem.calcium": "PubChem - Calcium",
