    "system.scandium.title": "Scandium",
    "system.scandium.desc": "Scandium is element #21, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.scandium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Sc<br>• Atomic Number — 21<br>• A silvery-white transition metal<br>• First of the transition elements in the periodic table<br>• Rare-earth element category due to similar properties<br>• Very lightweight and high melting point<br>• Discovered in 1879 in Scandinavia<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 21 protons in the nucleus<br>• 21 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 24 neutrons (Scandium-45)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d¹ 4s²<br>• Located in the 4th period and 3rd group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Low density (nearly as light as aluminum)<br>• Boiling point — 2836°C<br>• Melting point — 1541°C<br>• Silvery-white appearance that turns yellowish/pinkish in air<br>• Soft metal, but hardens when alloyed with others<br>• Good thermal and electrical conductivity<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with water to release hydrogen gas<br>• Dissolves readily in many acids<br>• Forms a protective oxide layer in air<br>• Resembles aluminum and rare-earth metals in reactivity<br>• Common oxidation state — +3<br><br><b>Scandium Isotopes</b><br>• Scandium-45 (⁴⁵Sc) — the only stable natural isotope<br>• Scandium-46 (⁴⁶Sc) — radioactive tracer used in oil refineries<br>• Scandium-47 (⁴⁷Sc) — used in medical research and imaging<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in trace amounts in over 800 minerals<br>• Primary source is the mineral Thortveitite<br>• Found in the Sun and other stars<br>• Difficult to isolate in pure form from its ores<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Byproduct of uranium and titanium processing<br>• Extracted via electrolysis of scandium chloride<br>• Produced in very small quantities globally (approx. 10-15 tons per year)<br><br><b>Applications of Scandium</b><br>• Scandium-aluminum alloys for aerospace and high-end bicycles<br>• High-intensity discharge (HID) lamps (stadium lighting)<br>• Solid oxide fuel cells (SOFCs) for efficient energy<br>• Additive in sports equipment (lacrosse sticks, baseball bats)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Vital for increasing strength of aluminum without increasing weight<br>• Key component in high-performance lighting technology<br>• Important in the study of early solar system materials<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Aerospace — building stronger, lighter aircraft<br>• Energy — advanced fuel cell development<br>• Sports — high-performance equipment manufacturing<br>• Astronomy — identifying stellar compositions",
    "system.scandium.fact": "Scandium has the atomic number 21 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.scandium": "Wikipedia - Scandium",
    "resource.pubchem.scandium": "PubChem - Scandium",
