    "system.titanium.title": "Titanium",
    "system.titanium.desc": "Titanium is element #22, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.titanium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ti<br>• Atomic Number — 22<br>• A strong, lightweight, and corrosion-resistant transition metal<br>• As strong as steel but 45% lighter<br>• Twice as strong as aluminum but only 60% heavier<br>• Resistant to corrosion in seawater, aqua regia, and chlorine<br>• Named after the Titans of Greek mythology<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 22 protons in the nucleus<br>• 22 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 26 neutrons (Titanium-48)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d² 4s²<br>• Located in the 4th period and 4th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-grey metallic color<br>• Boiling point — 3287°C<br>• Melting point — 1668°C<br>• Low thermal and electrical conductivity<br>• Paramagnetic (weakly attracted to magnetic fields)<br>• Highly biocompatible (not rejected by the human body)<br>• High strength-to-weight ratio<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Forms a passive oxide layer (TiO₂) that prevents corrosion<br>• Reacts with oxygen at high temperatures (1200°C in air)<br>• Resistant to most dilute sulfuric and hydrochloric acids<br>• Burns in pure nitrogen gas to form titanium nitride (TiN)<br>• Common oxidation states — +4, +3, and +2<br><br><b>Titanium Isotopes</b><br>• Titanium-46, 47, 48, 49, 50 — stable natural isotopes<br>• Titanium-48 (⁴⁸Ti) — most abundant (73.7%)<br>• Titanium-44 (⁴⁴Ti) — radioactive, used in astrophysics to study supernovae<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• 9th most abundant element in the Earth's crust<br>• Found in minerals like Rutile (TiO₂) and Ilmenite (FeTiO₃)<br>• Present in most igneous rocks and sediments<br>• Found in meteorites and on the Moon<br>• Never found in pure elemental form in nature<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Kroll process (reduction of TiCl₄ with molten magnesium)<br>• Hunter process (reduction with sodium — less common now)<br>• Complex and expensive production due to high reactivity with air<br><br><b>Applications of Titanium</b><br>• Aerospace: jet engines, airframes, and spacecraft<br>• Medicine: joint replacements, dental implants, and heart valves<br>• Industry: chemical processing pipes and heat exchangers<br>• Consumer: watches, jewelry, eyeglasses, and sports equipment<br>• Pigments: Titanium dioxide (white pigment for paint and sunscreens)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Revolutionized modern aircraft and space exploration<br>• Standard material for high-performance medical prosthetics<br>• Essential for chemical industries handling corrosive substances<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — bone integration and surgical safety<br>• Aerospace — engineering of supersonic vehicles<br>• Arts — vibrant white pigments in painting<br>• Industry — building long-lasting infrastructure in harsh environments",
    "system.titanium.fact": "Titanium has the atomic number 22 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.titanium": "Wikipedia - Titanium",
    "resource.pubchem.titanium": "PubChem - Titanium",
    "ai.titanium.simple": "Titanium is a chemical element with symbol Ti and atomic number 22. It is part of the Transition Metal group.",
    "ai.titanium.detailed": "Titanium (Ti) is the 22th element in the periodic table. As a transition metal, it possesses unique chemical and physical properties that make it vital in various industrial and biological processes.",
    "ai.titanium.study.1": "Atomic number: 22",
