    "system.vanadium.title": "Vanadium",
    "system.vanadium.desc": "Vanadium is element #23, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.vanadium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — V<br>• Atomic Number — 23<br>• A hard, silvery-grey, ductile transition metal<br>• Primarily used as a steel additive to increase strength and toughness<br>• Named after Vanadis, the Old Norse goddess of beauty<br>• Resistant to corrosion and stable against alkalis and acids<br>• Rarely found as a free element in nature<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 23 protons in the nucleus<br>• 23 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 28 neutrons (Vanadium-51)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d³ 4s²<br>• Located in the 4th period and 5th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white metallic appearance<br>• Boiling point — 3407°C<br>• Melting point — 1910°C<br>• High structural strength and durability<br>• Good corrosion resistance to sulfuric and hydrochloric acids<br>• Paramagnetic metallic element<br>• Maintains strength at high temperatures<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Forms a protective oxide layer that inhibits further oxidation<br>• Exhibits a wide range of colorful oxidation states in solution<br>• Forms vanadium pentoxide (V₂O₅), a key industrial catalyst<br>• Reacts with most non-metals at high temperatures<br>• Common oxidation states — +2, +3, +4, and +5<br><br><b>Vanadium Isotopes</b><br>• Vanadium-51 (⁵¹V) — only stable natural isotope (99.75%)<br>• Vanadium-50 (⁵⁰V) — extremely long-lived radioactive isotope (0.25%)<br>• Artificial isotopes used in nuclear physics research<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in about 65 different minerals like Vanadinite and Carnotite<br>• Present in fossil fuel deposits (oil and coal)<br>• Found in seawater in trace amounts<br>• Present in some biological organisms (e.g., sea squirts)<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered as a byproduct of iron slag processing<br>• Produced from flue dust of heavy oil combustion<br>• Refined via the reduction of vanadium pentoxide with calcium or aluminum<br><br><b>Applications of Vanadium</b><br>• Steel alloys (80% of production): tools, axles, and crankshafts<br>• High-speed tool steels for industrial cutting<br>• Vanadium redox batteries (VRB) for large-scale energy storage<br>• Catalyst in the production of sulfuric acid<br>• Aerospace titanium alloys (Ti-6Al-4V)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for heavy-duty structural engineering<br>• Enabling material for long-duration grid energy storage<br>• Essential catalyst for global chemical manufacturing<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Engineering — manufacturing of high-strength tools and parts<br>• Energy — large-scale battery storage solutions<br>• Chemistry — catalytic processes in industrial synthesis<br>• Aerospace — high-performance engine and structural components",
    "system.vanadium.fact": "Vanadium has the atomic number 23 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.vanadium": "Wikipedia - Vanadium",
    "resource.pubchem.vanadium": "PubChem - Vanadium",
    "ai.vanadium.simple": "Vanadium is a chemical element with symbol V and atomic number 23. It is part of the Transition Metal group.",
    "ai.vanadium.detailed": "Vanadium (V) is the 23th element in the periodic table. As a transition metal, it possesses unique chemical and physical properties that make it vital in various industrial and biological processes.",
