    "system.chromium.title": "Chromium",
    "system.chromium.desc": "Chromium is element #24, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.chromium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Cr<br>• Atomic Number — 24<br>• A steely-grey, lustrous, hard, and brittle transition metal<br>• High melting point and high corrosion resistance<br>• Main additive in stainless steel to provide anti-corrosive properties<br>• Named after the Greek word 'chroma' (color) due to its colorful compounds<br>• Does not tarnish in air, maintaining its shine<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 24 protons in the nucleus<br>• 24 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 28 neutrons (Chromium-52)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d⁵ 4s¹ (half-filled shell stability)<br>• Located in the 4th period and 6th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Extremely high luster and shine<br>• Boiling point — 2671°C<br>• Melting point — 1907°C<br>• Very hard material (9th on Mohs scale)<br>• Antiferromagnetic at room temperature<br>• High structural stability and durability<br>• Silvery-white appearance<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Forms a thin, dense oxide layer (Cr₂O₃) that prevents further oxidation<br>• Reacts with most non-metals at high temperatures<br>• Soluble in hydrochloric and sulfuric acids, but not nitric acid<br>• Displays a wide range of oxidation states with distinct colors<br>• Common oxidation states — +2, +3, and +6<br><br><b>Chromium Isotopes</b><br>• Chromium-52 (⁵²Cr) — most abundant stable isotope (83.79%)<br>• Chromium-53 (⁵³Cr) — stable isotope (9.50%)<br>• Chromium-54 (⁵⁴Cr) — stable isotope (2.37%)<br>• Chromium-50 (⁵⁰Cr) — stable isotope (4.35%)<br>• Used in radioactive tracing and industrial labeling<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• 21st most abundant element in the Earth's crust<br>• Found primarily in the mineral Chromite (FeCr₂O₄)<br>• Present in gems like Emeralds and Rubies (provides their color)<br>• Found in the Earth's mantle and some meteorites<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Obtained from chromite ore via smelting with coal/carbon<br>• Refined using the aluminothermic process or electrolysis<br>• Ferrochromium is produced for the steel industry<br><br><b>Applications of Chromium</b><br>• Stainless steel manufacturing (at least 10.5% Cr content)<br>• Chrome plating for decoration and corrosion protection<br>• Pigments and dyes for paints, glass, and ceramics<br>• Tanning of leather (chromium salts)<br>• Refractory materials for high-temperature furnaces<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Essential for modern materials science and metallurgy<br>• Key to developing heat-resistant and high-strength alloys<br>• Vital for industrial chemical synthesis (catalysts)<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Industry — metallurgical and plating processes<br>• Arts — colorful pigments and long-lasting finishes<br>• Fashion — leather processing and dyeing<br>• Chemistry — redox reactions and catalysis",
    "system.chromium.fact": "Chromium has the atomic number 24 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.chromium": "Wikipedia - Chromium",
