    "system.manganese.title": "Manganese",
    "system.manganese.desc": "Manganese is element #25, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.manganese.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Mn<br>• Atomic Number — 25<br>• A hard, brittle, silvery-grey transition metal<br>• Essential for the production of steel and iron alloys<br>• Vital mineral for human health and plant photosynthesis<br>• Resembles iron but is harder and more brittle<br>• Rapidly oxidizes in air to form various oxides<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 25 protons in the nucleus<br>• 25 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 30 neutrons (Manganese-55)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d⁵ 4s² (stable half-filled d-shell)<br>• Located in the 4th period and 7th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-grey color with a pinkish tint when oxidized<br>• Boiling point — 2061°C<br>• Melting point — 1246°C<br>• Paramagnetic (becomes ferromagnetic after special treatment)<br>• Hard material, brittle and difficult to fuse<br>• Good thermal and electrical conductivity<br>• Exists in four different allotropic forms<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with water slowly at room temperature, faster with steam<br>• Dissolves in dilute acids with the release of hydrogen gas<br>• Forms a wide range of oxidation states from -3 to +7<br>• Potassium permanganate (KMnO₄) is a powerful oxidizer<br>• Common oxidation states — +2, +3, +4, +6, and +7<br><br><b>Manganese Isotopes</b><br>• Manganese-55 (⁵⁵Mn) — the only stable natural isotope<br>• Manganese-54 (⁵⁴Mn) — radioactive, used in soil and plant studies<br>• Manganese-53 (⁵³Mn) — extremely long-lived, found in meteorites<br>• Artificial isotopes used in scientific tracing and industry<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• 12th most abundant element in the Earth's crust<br>• Found in minerals like Pyrolusite (MnO₂) and Rhodochrosite<br>• Abundant on the ocean floor as manganese nodules<br>• Essential part of the Oxygen-Evolving Complex in photosynthesis<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Obtained from ores via reduction with aluminum or in blast furnaces<br>• Electrolytic process used to produce pure manganese metal<br>• Ferro-manganese is produced for the steel industry<br><br><b>Applications of Manganese</b><br>• Steel alloys (removes oxygen and sulfur, increases hardness)<br>• Dry-cell batteries (alkaline and zinc-carbon)<br>• Pigments for glass, ceramics, and bricks (violet/brown colors)<br>• Nutritional supplements and animal feed additives<br>• Aluminum alloys for beverage cans (increases durability)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Critical cofactor for enzymes in human metabolism<br>• Essential for bone formation and blood clotting factors<br>• Fundamental for water-splitting in plant photosynthesis<br>• Key element for understanding transition metal chemistry<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Biology — enzymatic activity and plant growth<br>• Industry — metallurgical strength and battery technology<br>• Medicine — dietary supplements and nutritional science<br>• Geology — study of seafloor nodules and mineral deposits",
    "system.manganese.fact": "Manganese has the atomic number 25 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.manganese": "Wikipedia - Manganese",
    "resource.pubchem.manganese": "PubChem - Manganese",
