    "system.iron.title": "Iron",
    "system.iron.desc": "Iron is element #26, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.iron.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Fe<br>• Atomic Number — 26<br>• A lustrous, silvery-grey transition metal<br>• Most common element on Earth by mass (forming the core)<br>• Backbone of modern civilization and infrastructure<br>• Essential for oxygen transport in blood (hemoglobin)<br>• Ferromagnetic at room temperature<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 26 protons in the nucleus<br>• 26 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 30 neutrons (Iron-56)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d⁶ 4s²<br>• Located in the 4th period and 8th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Dense, strong, and malleable<br>• Boiling point — 2862°C<br>• Melting point — 1538°C<br>• High thermal and electrical conductivity<br>• Lustrous appearance that rusts (oxidizes) easily in moist air<br>• Forms alloys like steel with carbon and other metals<br>• Highest binding energy per nucleon (most stable nucleus)<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with oxygen and water to form iron oxides (rust)<br>• Dissolves easily in dilute acids<br>• Displays multiple oxidation states, primarily +2 and +3<br>• Acts as a catalyst in many industrial chemical reactions<br>• Forms stable complex compounds (e.g., ferrocene)<br>• Common oxidation states — +2, +3, +4, and +6<br><br><b>Iron Isotopes</b><br>• Iron-56 (⁵⁶Fe) — most abundant stable isotope (91.75%)<br>• Iron-54 (⁵⁴Fe) — stable isotope (5.85%)<br>• Iron-57 (⁵⁷Fe) — stable isotope (2.12%)<br>• Iron-58 (⁵⁸Fe) — stable isotope (0.28%)<br>• Isotope ratios used in studies of meteorite origins and planetary science<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in minerals like Hematite (Fe₂O₃) and Magnetite<br>• Makes up a large part of the Earth's inner and outer core<br>• Abundant in the Universe, formed in large stars before supernovae<br>• Essential component of many proteins and enzymes in life<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Reduction of iron ores with coke in blast furnaces<br>• Direct reduction processes for sponge iron<br>• Refined into various grades of steel via oxygen and electric arc furnaces<br><br><b>Applications of Iron</b><br>• Construction: bridges, skyscrapers, and reinforced concrete<br>• Transportation: ships, cars, trains, and heavy machinery<br>• Tools, cookware, and industrial equipment<br>• Magnetic materials and electromagnetic cores<br>• Steel manufacturing (iron-carbon alloys)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Critical for oxygen transport in mammals (hemoglobin/myoglobin)<br>• Vital for electron transfer in metabolic processes (cytochromes)<br>• Fundamental in understanding the Earth's magnetic field (geodynamo)<br>• Important in the study of nucleosynthesis in astrophysics<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Biology — respiration and metabolism<br>• Engineering — structural integrity and machinery design<br>• Geology — study of the Earth's interior and core<br>• Medicine — treatment of anemia and iron supplements",
    "system.iron.fact": "Iron has the atomic number 26 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.iron": "Wikipedia - Iron",
    "resource.pubchem.iron": "PubChem - Iron",
