    "system.cobalt.title": "Cobalt",
    "system.cobalt.desc": "Cobalt is element #27, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.cobalt.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Co<br>• Atomic Number — 27<br>• A hard, lustrous, silver-grey transition metal<br>• Named after 'kobold' (goblin/sprite in German folklore)<br>• Essential component of Lithium-ion batteries<br>• Vital part of Vitamin B12 (cobalamin) for humans<br>• Ferromagnetic, like iron and nickel<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 27 protons in the nucleus<br>• 27 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 32 neutrons (Cobalt-59)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d⁷ 4s²<br>• Located in the 4th period and 9th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-grey appearance with a bluish tint<br>• Boiling point — 2927°C<br>• Melting point — 1495°C<br>• High structural strength and wear resistance<br>• Maintains magnetic properties at high temperatures (high Curie point)<br>• Brittle and hard metallic element<br>• Good electrical and thermal conductivity<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Relatively stable in air, tarnishes slowly<br>• Reacts with most non-metals at high temperatures<br>• Dissolves slowly in dilute mineral acids<br>• Known for vibrant blue pigments (Cobalt blue)<br>• Forms a wide range of coordination complexes<br>• Common oxidation states — +2 and +3<br><br><b>Cobalt Isotopes</b><br>• Cobalt-59 (⁵⁹Co) — the only stable natural isotope<br>• Cobalt-60 (⁶⁰Co) — radioactive, used in medical radiotherapy<br>• Cobalt-57 (⁵⁷Co) — used as a tracer in medical diagnostics<br>• Artificial isotopes used in sterilization and industrial radiography<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in minerals like Cobaltite, Skutterudite, and Erythrite<br>• Primarily obtained as a byproduct of copper and nickel mining<br>• Found in the Earth's crust in trace amounts<br>• Present in meteorites and deep ocean crusts<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from ores via smelting and leaching processes<br>• Purified through solvent extraction and electrolysis<br>• Majority of global supply comes from the Democratic Republic of Congo<br><br><b>Applications of Cobalt</b><br>• Lithium-ion batteries (smartphones, electric vehicles)<br>• Superalloys for jet engines and gas turbines (high heat resistance)<br>• Hardened steels for cutting tools and drill bits<br>• Cobalt blue pigments for glass, ceramics, and paints<br>• Magnets: Alnico and Samarium-Cobalt alloys<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential trace element for human health (Vitamin B12)<br>• Critical for transition to green energy (EV battery supply chain)<br>• Key material for advanced aerospace engineering<br>• Vital in nuclear medicine (cancer treatment and sterilization)<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Energy — electric vehicle revolution and battery tech<br>• Medicine — Vitamin B12 deficiency and cancer therapy<br>• Aerospace — high-performance engine manufacturing<br>• Arts — historical blue dyes and pigments",
    "system.cobalt.fact": "Cobalt has the atomic number 27 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.cobalt": "Wikipedia - Cobalt",
    "resource.pubchem.cobalt": "PubChem - Cobalt",
