    "system.nickel.title": "Nickel",
    "system.nickel.desc": "Nickel is element #28, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.nickel.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ni<br>• Atomic Number — 28<br>• A silvery-white, lustrous transition metal with a slight golden tinge<br>• Hard and ductile, resistant to corrosion and oxidation<br>• One of the four elements that are ferromagnetic at room temperature<br>• Extensively used in alloys (stainless steel) and batteries<br>• Found in the Earth's core and in meteorites<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 28 protons in the nucleus<br>• 28 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 30 neutrons (Nickel-58)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d⁸ 4s²<br>• Located in the 4th period and 10th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• High metallic luster and polishable surface<br>• Boiling point — 2730°C<br>• Melting point — 1455°C<br>• High thermal and electrical conductivity<br>• Ferromagnetic (strongly attracted to magnets)<br>• Maintains structural strength at high temperatures<br>• Ductile: can be drawn into thin wires<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Dissolves slowly in dilute acids, but becomes passive in nitric acid<br>• Resistant to corrosion by air, water, and alkalis<br>• Forms colorful compounds (often green in solution)<br>• Acts as an effective catalyst in hydrogenation reactions<br>• Common oxidation states — +2 and +3<br><br><b>Nickel Isotopes</b><br>• Nickel-58 (⁵⁸Ni) — most abundant stable isotope (68.08%)<br>• Nickel-60 (⁶⁰Ni) — stable isotope (26.22%)<br>• Nickel-62 (⁶²Ni) — highest binding energy per nucleon of any nuclide<br>• Nickel-63 (⁶³Ni) — radioactive, used in electron capture detectors<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in minerals like Pentlandite and Garnierite<br>• Abundant in the Earth's core alongside iron<br>• Present in iron-nickel meteorites (Kamacite and Taenite)<br>• Found in trace amounts in plants and some microorganisms<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from sulfide and laterite ores via smelting and leaching<br>• Refined using the Mond process (gas-phase purification)<br>• Purified via electrolysis for high-grade applications<br><br><b>Applications of Nickel</b><br>• Stainless steel production (approx. 65% of global usage)<br>• Rechargeable batteries (NiMH and Li-ion chemistry)<br>• Coinage (nickel and cupronickel alloys)<br>• Superalloys for gas turbines and rocket engines<br>• Electroplating for corrosion protection and decoration<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Critical for high-temperature engineering materials<br>• Essential cofactor for some bacterial enzymes (e.g., Urease)<br>• Fundamental for understanding the formation of the Earth's core<br>• Key component in sustainable energy storage solutions<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Engineering — manufacturing of heat-resistant alloys<br>• Energy — advanced battery technology and storage<br>• Economics — historical and modern use in currency<br>• Geology — study of planetary formation and core composition",
    "system.nickel.fact": "Nickel has the atomic number 28 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.nickel": "Wikipedia - Nickel",
    "resource.pubchem.nickel": "PubChem - Nickel",
