    "system.copper.title": "Copper",
    "system.copper.desc": "Copper is element #29, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.copper.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Cu<br>• Atomic Number — 29<br>• A reddish-orange, soft, and ductile transition metal<br>• Exceptional electrical and thermal conductivity (second only to silver)<br>• One of the few metals to occur in nature in directly usable metallic form<br>• Essential trace mineral for all living organisms<br>• Base for major alloys like Bronze and Brass<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 29 protons in the nucleus<br>• 29 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 34 neutrons (Copper-63)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s¹ (stable full d-shell)<br>• Located in the 4th period and 11th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Unique reddish-metallic color<br>• Boiling point — 2562°C<br>• Melting point — 1085°C<br>• Extremely malleable and ductile (can be drawn into very fine wires)<br>• High electrical conductivity (100% IACS standard)<br>• Naturally antimicrobial (kills bacteria and viruses on surface)<br>• Non-magnetic metallic element<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts slowly with air to form a green patina (copper carbonate)<br>• Dissolves in oxidizing acids like nitric and concentrated sulfuric acid<br>• Forms colorful compounds (typically blue or green in solution)<br>• Catalyzes various organic chemical reactions<br>• Common oxidation states — +1 (cuprous) and +2 (cupric)<br><br><b>Copper Isotopes</b><br>• Copper-63 (⁶³Cu) — most abundant stable isotope (69.17%)<br>• Copper-65 (⁶⁵Cu) — stable isotope (30.83%)<br>• Copper-64 (⁶⁴Cu) — radioactive, used in medical PET imaging<br>• Isotope ratios used to track archaeological artifacts and pollution<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found as native copper in rare metallic deposits<br>• Found in minerals like Chalcopyrite (CuFeS₂), Malachite, and Azurite<br>• Present in the Earth's crust at about 50 ppm<br>• Essential component of respiratory proteins in some mollusks (hemocyanin)<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Smelting of sulfide ores followed by electrolytic refining<br>• Hydrometallurgy (leaching) for low-grade ores<br>• Highly recyclable without loss of quality (80% of copper ever mined is still in use)<br><br><b>Applications of Copper</b><br>• Electrical wiring and power cables (main usage)<br>• Plumbing: water pipes and fittings<br>• Electronics: PCBs, heat sinks, and electromagnetic motors<br>• Architecture: roofing, flashing, and decorative cladding<br>• Coinage, jewelry, and musical instruments (brass/bronze)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Vital for enzyme function and iron absorption in humans<br>• Critical for the global energy transition (EVs and renewables)<br>• Key material for superconducting research (cuprates)<br>• Essential for understanding ancient technological history (Copper Age)<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Energy — electrical grids and renewable technology<br>• Medicine — antimicrobial surfaces and diagnostic imaging<br>• History — study of the Bronze Age and ancient metallurgy<br>• Construction — durable piping and architectural finishes",
    "system.copper.fact": "Copper has the atomic number 29 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.copper": "Wikipedia - Copper",
