    "system.zinc.title": "Zinc",
    "system.zinc.desc": "Zinc is element #30, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.zinc.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Zn<br>• Atomic Number — 30<br>• A bluish-white, lustrous, and diamagnetic transition metal<br>• Primary use is for galvanizing (protecting iron and steel from rust)<br>• Essential trace mineral for human health and biological growth<br>• Known as 'philosopher's wool' when burned in air<br>• Brittle at room temperature but becomes malleable when heated<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 30 protons in the nucleus<br>• 30 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 34 neutrons (Zinc-64)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s² (fully filled d-shell stability)<br>• Located in the 4th period and 12th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Bluish-white metallic appearance<br>• Boiling point — 907°C<br>• Melting point — 419.5°C<br>• Relatively low melting point for a transition metal<br>• Good electrical conductivity<br>• Moderately hard material (2.5 on Mohs scale)<br>• Expands on heating and contracts on cooling<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with oxygen in air to form a protective carbonate layer<br>• Dissolves in both acids and strong alkalis (amphoteric behavior)<br>• Burns in air with a bright bluish-green flame<br>• Powerful reducing agent in chemical synthesis<br>• Forms a wide range of ionic and coordination compounds<br>• Common oxidation state — +2<br><br><b>Zinc Isotopes</b><br>• Zinc-64 (⁶⁴Zn) — most abundant stable isotope (49.17%)<br>• Zinc-66 (⁶⁶Zn) — stable isotope (27.73%)<br>• Zinc-67 (⁶⁷Zn) — stable isotope (4.04%)<br>• Zinc-68 (⁶⁸Zn) — stable isotope (18.45%)<br>• Zinc-70 (⁷⁰Zn) — stable isotope (0.61%)<br>• Artificial isotopes used in biomedical research and tracing<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in minerals like Sphalerite (zinc sulfide) and Smithsonite<br>• Present in the Earth's crust at about 70 ppm<br>• 24th most abundant element in the crust<br>• Essential component of over 300 enzymes in the human body<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Froth flotation of ores followed by roasting and smelting<br>• Electrolytic process for producing high-purity zinc (SHG grade)<br>• Widely recycled globally (about 30% of supply comes from scrap)<br><br><b>Applications of Zinc</b><br>• Galvanization of steel (approx. 50% of global usage)<br>• Die-casting for automotive and hardware components<br>• Production of Brass (copper-zinc alloy)<br>• Zinc oxide used in rubber, paints, and sunscreens<br>• Batteries: alkaline, zinc-carbon, and zinc-air chemistry<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Critical for DNA synthesis and cell division<br>• Essential for the immune system and wound healing<br>• Key material for electrochemical research and corrosion science<br>• Important for the study of metalloenzymes (e.g., Carbonic Anhydrase)<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — immune health and dermatology (zinc ointments)<br>• Construction — corrosion-resistant structures and roofing<br>• Industry — die-casting and metallurgical manufacturing<br>• Agriculture — essential micronutrient for crop yield and quality",
    "system.zinc.fact": "Zinc has the atomic number 30 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.zinc": "Wikipedia - Zinc",
    "resource.pubchem.zinc": "PubChem - Zinc",
