    "system.gallium.title": "Gallium",
    "system.gallium.desc": "Gallium is element #31, a versatile post-transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.gallium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ga<br>• Atomic Number — 31<br>• A soft, silvery-white post-transition metal<br>• Famous for melting in a human hand (low melting point)<br>• Essential material for modern electronics and semiconductors<br>• Does not occur as a free element in nature<br>• Discovered in 1875 and named after France (Gallia)<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 31 protons in the nucleus<br>• 31 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 38 neutrons (Gallium-69)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s² 4p¹<br>• Located in the 4th period and 13th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white appearance, liquid state is reflective<br>• Boiling point — 2229°C<br>• Melting point — 29.76°C (melts at slightly above room temp)<br>• One of the metals with the largest liquid temperature range<br>• Expands by 3.1% when it solidifies (like water ice)<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Brittle solid at low temperatures<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Relatively stable in dry air, but forms a thin oxide layer<br>• Reacts with most acids and strong alkalis (amphoteric)<br>• Forms trivalent compounds (oxidation state +3)<br>• Attacks other metals (like aluminum) by infiltrating their crystal lattice<br>• Non-toxic in small amounts, but can cause skin irritation<br><br><b>Gallium Isotopes</b><br>• Gallium-69 (⁶⁹Ga) — stable isotope (60.1%)<br>• Gallium-71 (⁷¹Ga) — stable isotope (39.9%)<br>• Gallium-67 (⁶⁷Ga) — radioactive, used in medical bone and tumor scans<br>• Gallium-68 (⁶⁸Ga) — used in PET imaging diagnostics<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in trace amounts in minerals like Sphalerite and Bauxite<br>• Found in the mineral Gallite (CuGaS₂), which is rare<br>• Concentration in the Earth's crust is about 19 ppm<br>• Obtained primarily as a byproduct of zinc and aluminum processing<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from alkaline solutions during the Bayer process (aluminum)<br>• Produced via electrolysis of gallium-rich solutions<br>• Refined to ultra-high purity (99.9999%) for the electronics industry<br><br><b>Applications of Gallium</b><br>• Gallium Arsenide (GaAs) for high-speed microchips and smartphones<br>• LEDs (Light Emitting Diodes) and laser diodes (Blu-ray players)<br>• Photovoltaic cells for satellites and concentrated solar power<br>• High-temperature thermometers and liquid metal alloys (Galinstan)<br>• Medical imaging and radiopharmaceuticals<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Enabling material for high-frequency telecommunications<br>• Critical for efficient lighting technology (LED revolution)<br>• Important in the study of low-temperature physics and metallurgy<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Electronics — high-speed computing and optical devices<br>• Medicine — diagnostic imaging and cancer detection<br>• Energy — advanced solar cells and thermal management<br>• Telecommunications — foundation of 5G and satellite tech",
    "system.gallium.fact": "Gallium has the atomic number 31 and belongs to the Post-Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.gallium": "Wikipedia - Gallium",
    "resource.pubchem.gallium": "PubChem - Gallium",
