    "system.germanium.title": "Germanium",
    "system.germanium.desc": "Germanium is element #32, a versatile metalloid essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.germanium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ge<br>• Atomic Number — 32<br>• A lustrous, hard-brittle, greyish-white metalloid<br>• Chemically similar to silicon and tin<br>• Critical material for fiber optics and infrared technology<br>• Named after Germany (Germania)<br>• Found in trace amounts in coal and zinc ores<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 32 protons in the nucleus<br>• 32 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 42 neutrons (Germanium-74)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s² 4p²<br>• Located in the 4th period and 14th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• High metallic luster and brittle nature<br>• Boiling point — 2833°C<br>• Melting point — 938.3°C<br>• Semiconductor: conductivity increases with temperature<br>• Transparent to infrared radiation (used in night vision)<br>• High refractive index and low optical dispersion<br>• Expands on solidification (like silicon and water)<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Stable in air and water under normal conditions<br>• Reacts with oxygen at high temperatures to form GeO₂<br>• Dissolves slowly in hot concentrated sulfuric and nitric acids<br>• Forms organogermanium compounds used in research<br>• Common oxidation states — +2 and +4<br><br><b>Germanium Isotopes</b><br>• Germanium-74 (⁷⁴Ge) — most abundant stable isotope (36.28%)<br>• Germanium-70, 72, 73, 76 — other stable isotopes<br>• Germanium-68 (⁶⁸Ge) — radioactive, used in medical PET scanners<br>• High-purity germanium (HPGe) crystals used in gamma-ray spectroscopy<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in the Earth's crust at about 1.6 ppm<br>• Present in minerals like Argyrodite and Renierite<br>• Found in some coal deposits (major commercial source)<br>• Recovered primarily as a byproduct of zinc smelting<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Fractional distillation of germanium tetrachloride (GeCl₄)<br>• Zone refining to reach ultra-high purity levels<br>• Recovered from flue dust of coal-fired power plants in some regions<br><br><b>Applications of Germanium</b><br>• Fiber optic communication systems (approx. 35% of usage)<br>• Infrared optics: night vision devices and thermal imaging<br>• Polymerization catalysts for PET plastics manufacturing<br>• Solar cells for satellites (high-efficiency multi-junction)<br>• Specialty alloys and transistors in specific electronics<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Material used for the first-ever transistor (invented in 1947)<br>• Enabling element for modern high-speed internet (fiber optics)<br>• Essential for advanced thermal detection and military technology<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Telecommunications — high-bandwidth optical fibers<br>• Energy — high-efficiency solar power for space missions<br>• Medicine — diagnostic PET scanning technology<br>• Defense — night vision and precision thermal guidance systems",
    "system.germanium.fact": "Germanium has the atomic number 32 and belongs to the Metalloid group.",
    "resource.wiki.germanium": "Wikipedia - Germanium",
    "resource.pubchem.germanium": "PubChem - Germanium",
