    "system.arsenic.title": "Arsenic",
    "system.arsenic.desc": "Arsenic is element #33, a versatile metalloid essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.arsenic.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — As<br>• Atomic Number — 33<br>• A brittle, grey metalloid that occurs in many minerals<br>• Famous for its historical use as a potent poison and medicine<br>• Critical component in semiconductor manufacturing (Gallium Arsenide)<br>• Exists in three common allotropes: grey, yellow, and black<br>• Sublimes at atmospheric pressure (turns directly from solid to gas)<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 33 protons in the nucleus<br>• 33 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 42 neutrons (Arsenic-75)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s² 4p³<br>• Located in the 4th period and 15th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Grey arsenic is the most common form (metallic appearance)<br>• Sublimation point — 614°C<br>• Brittle solid that conducts electricity poorly compared to metals<br>• Expands on freezing (in some forms)<br>• Emits a garlic-like odor when heated in air<br>• High structural density in its metallic form<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Forms poisonous oxides (e.g., Arsenic trioxide As₂O₃) when burned<br>• Reacts with halogens to form trihalides and pentahalides<br>• Insoluble in water, but soluble in nitric and concentrated sulfuric acids<br>• Forms organoarsenic compounds, some found in marine life<br>• Common oxidation states — +3, +5, and -3<br><br><b>Arsenic Isotopes</b><br>• Arsenic-75 (⁷⁵As) — the only stable natural isotope<br>• Arsenic-74 (⁷⁴As) — used in medical localization of tumors<br>• Arsenic-73 (⁷³As) — used in geological tracing and scientific research<br>• Short-lived isotopes used in specialized nuclear medicine<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in minerals like Arsenopyrite (FeAsS) and Realgar<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 1.8 ppm<br>• Found in some groundwaters and volcanic emissions<br>• Present in many soils as a result of geological weathering<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Obtained as a byproduct from copper and lead smelting<br>• Produced by roasting arsenopyrite or arsenic oxides with carbon<br>• Purified via sublimation to produce high-purity arsenic metal<br><br><b>Applications of Arsenic</b><br>• Semiconductor materials: Gallium Arsenide (GaAs) and Indium Arsenide<br>• Alloying agent for strengthening lead (batteries) and copper<br>• Preservation of wood (CCA treatment — now being phased out)<br>• Glass manufacturing to remove bubbles and color<br>• Pesticides and herbicides (mostly historical usage)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential for some species, but toxic to humans in small doses<br>• Fundamental for understanding toxicology and cell signaling<br>• Enabling element for high-frequency wireless electronics (WiFi, 5G)<br>• Important in the history of medicine (first chemotherapy agents)<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Electronics — high-performance wireless communication<br>• Medicine — historical pharmacology and modern oncology<br>• Environment — monitoring groundwater safety and soil pollution<br>• Industry — metallurgical strengthening and glass production",
    "system.arsenic.fact": "Arsenic has the atomic number 33 and belongs to the Metalloid group.",
    "resource.wiki.arsenic": "Wikipedia - Arsenic",
