    "system.selenium.title": "Selenium",
    "system.selenium.desc": "Selenium is element #34, a versatile nonmetal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.selenium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Se<br>• Atomic Number — 34<br>• A nonmetal with properties between sulfur and tellurium<br>• Essential trace element for human health and antioxidant systems<br>• Exceptional photoconductivity (conducts electricity better in light)<br>• Named after the Moon (Selene in Greek)<br>• Rare in its pure elemental form in nature<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 34 protons in the nucleus<br>• 34 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 46 neutrons (Selenium-80)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s² 4p⁴<br>• Located in the 4th period and 16th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Exists in several allotropic forms (red, grey, and black)<br>• Grey selenium is the most stable and conducts electricity<br>• Boiling point — 685°C<br>• Melting point — 221°C (grey form)<br>• Photovoltaic: converts light directly into electricity<br>• Poor thermal conductivity<br>• Distinctive metallic luster in its stable form<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with oxygen to form selenium dioxide (SeO₂)<br>• Forms selenides with many metals<br>• Chemically similar to sulfur but more metallic<br>• Reacts with halogens to form various halides<br>• Common oxidation states — -2, +4, and +6<br><br><b>Selenium Isotopes</b><br>• Selenium-80 (⁸⁰Se) — most abundant stable isotope (49.6%)<br>• Selenium-74, 76, 77, 78, 82 — other stable/long-lived isotopes<br>• Selenium-75 (⁷⁵Se) — radioactive, used in medical imaging of the pancreas<br>• Isotope ratios used to track the origin of food and minerals<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in minerals like Berzelianite and Clausthalite<br>• Present in the Earth's crust at about 0.05 ppm (rarer than silver)<br>• Often associated with sulfur and copper deposits<br>• Found in Brazil nuts and some cereals in significant amounts<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Obtained primarily as a byproduct of electrolytic copper refining<br>• Recovered from the anode slimes of copper smelting<br>• Purified via roasting with soda ash followed by leaching<br><br><b>Applications of Selenium</b><br>• Glass manufacturing (decolorizing glass and making red glass)<br>• Photocopying and laser printing (photoreceptors)<br>• Solar cells and light sensors (photoconductivity)<br>• Nutritional supplements and livestock feed additives<br>• Rectifiers for converting AC to DC electricity<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential component of antioxidant enzymes (e.g., Glutathione peroxidase)<br>• Vital for thyroid hormone metabolism and immune function<br>• Crucial material for understanding photoelectric effects<br>• Important in the development of semiconductor technology<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — dietary supplements and cancer prevention research<br>• Technology — light-sensitive sensors and xerography<br>• Industry — glass coloring and metallurgical additives<br>• Agriculture — preventing selenium deficiency in livestock",
    "system.selenium.fact": "Selenium has the atomic number 34 and belongs to the Nonmetal group.",
    "resource.wiki.selenium": "Wikipedia - Selenium",
