    "system.bromine.title": "Bromine",
    "system.bromine.desc": "Bromine is element #35, a versatile halogen essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.bromine.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Br<br>• Atomic Number — 35<br>• A reddish-brown, foul-smelling liquid halogen<br>• One of only two elements that are liquid at room temperature (with mercury)<br>• Highly reactive and volatile, evaporates easily into toxic gas<br>• Named after the Greek word 'bromos' (stench)<br>• Essential for marine biology but toxic to humans in high doses<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 35 protons in the nucleus<br>• 35 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 44 neutrons (Bromine-79)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s² 4p⁵<br>• Located in the 4th period and 17th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Dense, reddish-brown liquid with high vapor pressure<br>• Boiling point — 58.8°C<br>• Melting point — −7.2°C<br>• Evaporates quickly to form a suffocating brown gas<br>• Slightly soluble in water (forms bromine water)<br>• Highly soluble in organic solvents like carbon disulfide<br>• Non-metallic element with a strong, irritating odor<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Strong oxidizing agent, reacts with most metals and non-metals<br>• Reacts with water to form hypobromous acid (HBrO)<br>• Less reactive than chlorine but more reactive than iodine<br>• Forms bromides with alkali metals and other elements<br>• Common oxidation states — -1, +1, +3, +5, and +7<br><br><b>Bromine Isotopes</b><br>• Bromine-79 (⁷⁹Br) — stable isotope (50.69%)<br>• Bromine-81 (⁸¹Br) — stable isotope (49.31%)<br>• Bromine-82 (⁸²Br) — radioactive, used in hydrology and tracking leaks<br>• Isotope ratios used in studies of organic pollutants and atmosphere<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily as bromide ions (Br⁻) in seawater and salt lakes<br>• Abundant in the Dead Sea and deep salt deposits<br>• Concentration in the Earth's crust is about 2.5 ppm<br>• Found in certain marine plants and invertebrates<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced from brine via oxidation with chlorine gas<br>• Recovered by blowing air through chlorinated brine to strip bromine gas<br>• Purified through condensation and distillation<br><br><b>Applications of Bromine</b><br>• Flame retardants (BFRs) for electronics and furniture (major usage)<br>• Agricultural chemicals: pesticides and fumigants<br>• Water treatment: swimming pool and industrial water sanitation<br>• Photography: silver bromide for film and paper<br>• Pharmaceuticals: sedatives and specialty drugs<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential cofactor for tissue development in some animals<br>• Key element in the study of organic reaction mechanisms (halogenation)<br>• Vital for understanding ozone depletion in the atmosphere<br>• Important in specialized industrial chemical synthesis<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Safety — flame retardant technology in public spaces<br>• Environment — monitoring atmospheric chemistry and ozone layer<br>• Agriculture — soil fumigation and crop protection<br>• Medicine — historical use as sedatives and modern chemical synthesis",
    "system.bromine.fact": "Bromine has the atomic number 35 and belongs to the Halogen group.",
    "resource.wiki.bromine": "Wikipedia - Bromine",
    "resource.pubchem.bromine": "PubChem - Bromine",
