    "system.krypton.title": "Krypton",
    "system.krypton.desc": "Krypton is element #36, a versatile noble gas essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.krypton.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Kr<br>• Atomic Number — 36<br>• A noble gas from the 18th group<br>• Completely colorless, odorless, and tasteless<br>• Chemically inert, though it can form a few compounds under extreme conditions<br>• Named after the Greek word 'kryptos' (hidden)<br>• Rare gas found in the Earth's atmosphere (approx. 1 ppm)<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 36 protons in the nucleus<br>• 36 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 48 neutrons (Krypton-84)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s² 4p⁶ (full octet)<br>• Located in the 4th period and 18th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Gas at standard conditions<br>• Boiling point — −153.4°C<br>• Melting point — −157.4°C<br>• Roughly 3 times denser than air<br>• Produces a brilliant white/greenish light in an electric discharge<br>• High refractive index and low thermal conductivity<br>• Liquefies easily at very low temperatures<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Generally inert and does not react with other elements<br>• Can form krypton difluoride (KrF₂) when reacted with fluorine at low temps<br>• Clathrates with water and other molecules have been produced<br>• Does not support combustion<br>• Exists as monatomic atoms (Kr)<br><br><b>Krypton Isotopes</b><br>• Krypton-84 (⁸⁴Kr) — most abundant stable isotope (57.0%)<br>• Krypton-78, 80, 82, 83, 86 — other stable isotopes<br>• Krypton-81 (⁸¹Kr) — used for dating ancient Antarctic ice and groundwater<br>• Krypton-85 (⁸⁵Kr) — radioactive, used to monitor nuclear fuel processing<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Present in the Earth's atmosphere at 1.14 ppm by volume<br>• Found in the Earth's crust as a result of uranium fission<br>• Present in volcanic gases in trace amounts<br>• Abundant in space, formed in stars during nucleosynthesis<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Fractional distillation of liquid air (main commercial source)<br>• Separated from other noble gases through cryogenic chromatography<br>• Stored and transported in high-pressure gas cylinders<br><br><b>Applications of Krypton</b><br>• High-intensity lighting: airport runways and photography flashes<br>• Energy-efficient windows: used as a filler gas for better insulation<br>• Excimer lasers (KrF) for semiconductor manufacturing and eye surgery<br>• Neon-krypton signs for specialized advertising lighting<br>• Detection of clandestine nuclear reactors (via ⁸⁵Kr levels)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Was used to define the international meter from 1960 to 1983<br>• Crucial for high-precision scientific lasers<br>• Vital for environmental dating techniques (Krypton-dating)<br>• Important for high-performance thermal insulation technology<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Technology — advanced semiconductor lithography<br>• Physics — defining fundamental units of measurement<br>• Environment — tracking historical climate changes via ice cores<br>• Medicine — laser-based eye surgery and diagnostic research",
    "system.krypton.fact": "Krypton has the atomic number 36 and belongs to the Noble Gas group.",
    "resource.wiki.krypton": "Wikipedia - Krypton",
    "resource.pubchem.krypton": "PubChem - Krypton",
