    "system.rubidium.title": "Rubidium",
    "system.rubidium.desc": "Rubidium is element #37, a versatile alkali metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.rubidium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Rb<br>• Atomic Number — 37<br>• A very soft, silvery-white alkali metal from the 1st group<br>• Spontaneously ignites in air and reacts violently with water<br>• One of the most electropositive and easily liquefied metals<br>• Named after the Latin word 'rubidus' (deep red) due to its spectral lines<br>• Primarily used in high-precision atomic clocks<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 37 protons in the nucleus<br>• 37 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 48 neutrons (Rubidium-85)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 5s¹<br>• Located in the 5th period and 1st group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Extremely soft (can be cut like butter)<br>• Boiling point — 688°C<br>• Melting point — 39.3°C (melts on a hot day)<br>• Silvery luster that tarnishes instantly in air<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Low density (sinks in water but is very light)<br>• Produces a reddish-violet flame during a flame test<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: ignites spontaneously in air to form oxides<br>• Reacts explosively with water to form rubidium hydroxide and hydrogen<br>• Forms ionic compounds with halogens (e.g., RbCl, RbBr)<br>• Dissolves in liquid ammonia to form conductive blue solutions<br>• Common oxidation state — +1<br><br><b>Rubidium Isotopes</b><br>• Rubidium-85 (⁸⁵Rb) — the only stable natural isotope (72.2%)<br>• Rubidium-87 (⁸⁷Rb) — long-lived radioactive isotope (27.8%)<br>• Rubidium-82 (⁸²Rb) — radioactive, used in medical PET myocardial imaging<br>• ⁸⁷Rb is used in Rb-Sr dating to determine the age of rocks and minerals<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• 23rd most abundant element in the Earth's crust<br>• Found in minerals like Lepidolite and Pollucite<br>• Present in seawater at concentrations of about 0.12 ppm<br>• Never found free in nature due to extreme reactivity<br>• Found in small amounts in some fruits and plants<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Obtained as a byproduct of lithium and cesium extraction<br>• Produced via the reduction of rubidium chloride with calcium metal<br>• Refined using fractional distillation in a vacuum<br><br><b>Applications of Rubidium</b><br>• Rubidium atomic clocks (GPS systems and telecommunications)<br>• Specialized glass for fiber optic systems and night vision<br>• Vapor cell atomic frequency standards<br>• Medical imaging (PET scans for heart health)<br>• Research in Bose-Einstein condensation (BEC)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Essential for global positioning and timekeeping technology<br>• Critical for fundamental physics research at ultra-low temperatures<br>• Key material for advanced optical and quantum technologies<br>• Important in geochronology for dating the Earth's history<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Telecommunications — precise timing and synchronization<br>• Physics — study of quantum states and atomic physics<br>• Medicine — diagnostic heart imaging and medical research<br>• Geology — dating minerals and igneous rocks",
    "system.rubidium.fact": "Rubidium has the atomic number 37 and belongs to the Alkali Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.rubidium": "Wikipedia - Rubidium",
    "resource.pubchem.rubidium": "PubChem - Rubidium",
    "ai.rubidium.simple": "Rubidium is a chemical element with symbol Rb and atomic number 37. It is part of the Alkali Metal group.",
    "ai.rubidium.detailed": "Rubidium (Rb) is the 37th element in the periodic table. As a alkali metal, it possesses unique chemical and physical properties that make it vital in various industrial and biological processes.",
