    "system.strontium.title": "Strontium",
    "system.strontium.desc": "Strontium is element #38, a versatile alkaline earth metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.strontium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Sr<br>• Atomic Number — 38<br>• A soft, silvery-yellow alkaline earth metal from the 2nd group<br>• Highly reactive chemically, tarnishing quickly in air<br>• Famous for providing the brilliant red color in fireworks<br>• Chemically similar to calcium, allowing it to be absorbed into bones<br>• Named after the village of Strontian in Scotland<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 38 protons in the nucleus<br>• 38 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 50 neutrons (Strontium-88)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 5s²<br>• Located in the 5th period and 2nd group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery appearance that turns yellowish when exposed to air<br>• Boiling point — 1382°C<br>• Melting point — 777°C<br>• Softer than calcium and harder than sodium<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Low density for a metallic element<br>• Produces a brilliant crimson/red flame during a flame test<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts vigorously with water to form strontium hydroxide and hydrogen gas<br>• Reacts with oxygen at room temperature, must be stored under oil<br>• Forms ionic compounds with halogens and non-metals (e.g., SrCl₂)<br>• Finely divided strontium powder ignites spontaneously in air<br>• Common oxidation state — +2<br><br><b>Strontium Isotopes</b><br>• Strontium-88 (⁸⁸Sr) — most abundant stable isotope (82.6%)<br>• Strontium-84, 86, 87 — other stable isotopes<br>• Strontium-90 (⁹⁰Sr) — radioactive, found in nuclear fallout, used in RTGs<br>• Strontium-89 (⁸⁹Sr) — used in medicine to treat bone cancer pain<br>• ⁸⁷Sr/⁸⁶Sr ratios used to track animal and human migrations in archaeology<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• 15th most abundant element in the Earth's crust<br>• Found primarily in minerals like Celestite (SrSO₄) and Strontianite<br>• Present in seawater at about 8 ppm<br>• Never found free in nature due to high reactivity<br>• Found in the human body, mostly in skeletal tissues<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Obtained from celestite via chemical conversion to strontium carbonate<br>• Pure metal is produced by electrolysis of strontium chloride or reduction with aluminum<br>• Global production centered in China, Spain, and Mexico<br><br><b>Applications of Strontium</b><br>• Fireworks and flares: provides the signature deep red color<br>• Ferrite magnets: used in small motors and speakers<br>• Glass for color television cathode ray tubes (legacy technology)<br>• Medical treatment for bone pain and osteoporosis (Strontium ranelate)<br>• Master alloys for aluminum casting improvement<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential for understanding bone metabolism and mineralization<br>• Critical for high-precision atomic clocks (Strontium lattice clocks)<br>• Vital for archaeological studies of migration and diet<br>• Key material for radioactive energy sources in space exploration<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — bone health and oncology (cancer treatment)<br>• Archaeology — tracking historical human movements<br>• Technology — high-precision timing and magnetic materials<br>• Pyrotechnics — specialized lighting and visual effects",
    "system.strontium.fact": "Strontium has the atomic number 38 and belongs to the Alkaline Earth Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.strontium": "Wikipedia - Strontium",
    "resource.pubchem.strontium": "PubChem - Strontium",
