    "system.yttrium.title": "Yttrium",
    "system.yttrium.desc": "Yttrium is element #39, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.yttrium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Y<br>• Atomic Number — 39<br>• A silvery-metallic transition metal chemically similar to lanthanides<br>• Often classified as a 'rare earth element'<br>• Named after the village of Ytterby in Sweden<br>• Critical for producing phosphors (red color in older TVs)<br>• Found in almost all rare-earth minerals<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 39 protons in the nucleus<br>• 39 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 50 neutrons (Yttrium-89)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 4d¹ 5s²<br>• Located in the 5th period and 3rd group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white, lustrous appearance<br>• Boiling point — 3336°C<br>• Melting point — 1526°C<br>• Relatively stable in air in bulk form<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Soft and ductile metallic element<br>• Becomes superconducting at low temperatures<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with water to release hydrogen gas<br>• Dissolves easily in mineral acids<br>• Forms a protective oxide layer (Y₂O₃) in air<br>• Finely divided yttrium is highly unstable and may ignite in air<br>• Common oxidation state — +3<br><br><b>Yttrium Isotopes</b><br>• Yttrium-89 (⁸⁹Y) — the only stable natural isotope<br>• Yttrium-90 (⁹⁰Y) — radioactive, used in medical treatment for liver cancer<br>• Yttrium-91 (⁹¹Y) — used in biological tracing and industrial research<br>• Short-lived isotopes used in specialized nuclear medicine<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in minerals like Xenotime, Monazite, and Bastnäsite<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 31 ppm<br>• Never found free in nature; always found with other rare earths<br>• Present in trace amounts in most living organisms<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from monazite sand via solvent extraction<br>• Metal is produced by reduction of yttrium fluoride with calcium<br>• Highly purified via ion-exchange chromatography<br><br><b>Applications of Yttrium</b><br>• Yttrium Aluminum Garnet (YAG) for high-power lasers<br>• Phosphors for LEDs, radar screens, and old color TVs<br>• High-temperature superconductors (YBCO — Yttrium Barium Copper Oxide)<br>• Stabilized Zirconia: used in ceramic knives and jet engine coatings<br>• Alloying agent to increase strength of aluminum and magnesium<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Enabling material for high-power laser technology (surgery and cutting)<br>• Fundamental for research in high-temperature superconductivity<br>• Critical for energy-efficient lighting and display technologies<br>• Important for advanced aerospace engine components<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — radiotherapy for cancer and laser surgery<br>• Physics — superconductivity and quantum research<br>• Aerospace — heat-resistant coatings and light alloys<br>• Technology — high-performance lasers and display systems",
    "system.yttrium.fact": "Yttrium has the atomic number 39 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.yttrium": "Wikipedia - Yttrium",
    "resource.pubchem.yttrium": "PubChem - Yttrium",
