    "system.zirconium.title": "Zirconium",
    "system.zirconium.desc": "Zirconium is element #40, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.zirconium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Zr<br>• Atomic Number — 40<br>• A lustrous, greyish-white transition metal<br>• Highly resistant to corrosion by alkalis, acids, and salt water<br>• Critical material for the nuclear energy industry<br>• Named after the mineral Zircon (from Persian 'zargun' — gold-like)<br>• Chemically very similar to hafnium<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 40 protons in the nucleus<br>• 40 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 50 neutrons (Zirconium-90)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 4d² 5s²<br>• Located in the 5th period and 4th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Strong, malleable, and ductile metallic element<br>• Boiling point — 4409°C<br>• Melting point — 1855°C<br>• Excellent thermal and electrical conductivity<br>• Maintains structural integrity at extremely high temperatures<br>• Transparent to thermal neutrons (important for reactors)<br>• Forms a very hard oxide layer (Zirconia)<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Exceptionally resistant to corrosion in harsh environments<br>• Does not react with water or oxygen at room temperature<br>• Dissolves in hydrofluoric acid and aqua regia<br>• Finely divided powder can ignite spontaneously in air (pyrophoric)<br>• Common oxidation state — +4<br><br><b>Zirconium Isotopes</b><br>• Zirconium-90 (⁹⁰Zr) — most abundant stable isotope (51.45%)<br>• Zirconium-91, 92, 94 — other stable isotopes<br>• Zirconium-96 (⁹⁶Zr) — extremely long-lived radioisotope<br>• Zirconium-89 (⁸⁹Zr) — radioactive, used as a tracer in immuno-PET imaging<br>• Isotope ratios used in geochronology (Zircon dating)<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in the mineral Zircon (ZrSiO₄) and Baddeleyite<br>• 18th most abundant element in the Earth's crust<br>• Abundant in S-type stars and found in lunar rock samples<br>• Always found alongside hafnium in natural deposits<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced from zircon sand via the Kroll process (reduction with magnesium)<br>• Hafnium separation is a critical step for nuclear-grade zirconium<br>• Purified via the iodide process (Van Arkel-de Boer method)<br><br><b>Applications of Zirconium</b><br>• Nuclear fuel rod cladding (low neutron absorption)<br>• Chemical industry: corrosion-resistant pumps, valves, and pipes<br>• Cubic Zirconia: synthetic diamond substitute in jewelry<br>• Ceramic knives and dental implants (biocompatible)<br>• Jet engine components and spacecraft heat shields<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential for modern nuclear power safety and efficiency<br>• Key material for determining the age of the Earth (Zircon crystals)<br>• Biocompatible material used in advanced medical prosthetics<br>• Fundamental for high-temperature materials science<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Energy — nuclear reactor core construction<br>• Geology — dating the oldest rocks in the Earth's history<br>• Medicine — dental crowns and joint replacements<br>• Jewelry — accessible luxury and gemstone simulation",
    "system.zirconium.fact": "Zirconium has the atomic number 40 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.zirconium": "Wikipedia - Zirconium",
    "resource.pubchem.zirconium": "PubChem - Zirconium",
