    "system.niobium.title": "Niobium",
    "system.niobium.desc": "Niobium is element #41, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.niobium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Nb<br>• Atomic Number — 41<br>• A light grey, crystalline, and ductile transition metal<br>• Named after Niobe, daughter of Tantalus in Greek mythology<br>• Critical for superconducting magnets and high-strength alloys<br>• Does not occur as a free element in nature<br>• Often found alongside tantalum in minerals like Columbite<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 41 protons in the nucleus<br>• 41 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 52 neutrons (Niobium-93)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 4d⁴ 5s¹<br>• Located in the 5th period and 5th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Lustrous, grey metallic appearance<br>• Boiling point — 4744°C<br>• Melting point — 2477°C<br>• Becomes a superconductor at very low temperatures (9.2 K)<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Harder than pure iron and extremely ductile<br>• Maintains structural strength at high temperatures<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly resistant to corrosion by acids and alkalis<br>• Forms a protective oxide layer (Nb₂O₅) when exposed to air<br>• Reacts with oxygen only at high temperatures<br>• Dissolves in hydrofluoric acid and mixtures of HF and nitric acid<br>• Common oxidation states — +3 and +5<br><br><b>Niobium Isotopes</b><br>• Niobium-93 (⁹³Nb) — the only stable natural isotope<br>• Niobium-92 (⁹²Nb) — long-lived radioisotope (extinct in nature)<br>• Niobium-94 (⁹⁴Nb) — radioactive, used in nuclear reactor monitoring<br>• Niobium-95 (⁹⁵Nb) — used in biological and chemical research<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in minerals like Pyrochlore and Columbite<br>• 33rd most abundant element in the Earth's crust<br>• Large deposits found in Brazil and Canada<br>• Found in trace amounts in most igneous rocks<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Separation from tantalum via solvent extraction or fractional crystallization<br>• Metal produced by reduction of niobium oxides with aluminum or carbon<br>• Refined using electron-beam melting for high purity<br><br><b>Applications of Niobium</b><br>• Superconducting magnets for MRI machines and particle accelerators<br>• High-strength, low-alloy (HSLA) steels for pipelines and cars<br>• Superalloys for jet engines and rocket nozzles (heat resistance)<br>• Jewelry: hypoallergenic and can be anodized into vibrant colors<br>• Capacitors for high-performance electronic devices<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Enabling material for high-field superconducting magnets<br>• Critical for modern aerospace and transportation infrastructure<br>• Key material for advanced particle physics research<br>• Important for the development of quantum computing hardware<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — MRI technology and orthopedic implants<br>• Physics — superconductivity and particle acceleration<br>• Aerospace — high-performance engine manufacturing<br>• Art — colorful and durable anodized jewelry",
    "system.niobium.fact": "Niobium has the atomic number 41 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
