    "system.molybdenum.title": "Molybdenum",
    "system.molybdenum.desc": "Molybdenum is element #42, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.molybdenum.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Mo<br>• Atomic Number — 42<br>• A silvery-white, hard, and high-melting transition metal<br>• Essential trace element for human health and nitrogen fixation in plants<br>• Named after the Greek word 'molybdos' (lead-like)<br>• Maintains extreme strength at very high temperatures<br>• Critical for alloying steels and industrial chemical catalysts<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 42 protons in the nucleus<br>• 42 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 56 neutrons (Molybdenum-98)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 4d⁵ 5s¹ (stable half-filled shells)<br>• Located in the 5th period and 6th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white appearance with a high metallic luster<br>• Boiling point — 4639°C<br>• Melting point — 2623°C (one of the highest of all elements)<br>• Low coefficient of thermal expansion<br>• High thermal conductivity and electrical resistance<br>• Very hard material (5.5 on Mohs scale)<br>• Ductile: can be drawn into thin wires for heating elements<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Does not react with oxygen or water at room temperature<br>• Forms a protective oxide layer (MoO₃) at high temperatures<br>• Reacts with halogens to form various halides<br>• Dissolves in hot concentrated acids and oxidizing agents<br>• Displays a wide range of oxidation states from -2 to +6<br><br><b>Molybdenum Isotopes</b><br>• Molybdenum-98 (⁹⁸Mo) — most abundant stable isotope (24.14%)<br>• Molybdenum-92, 94, 95, 96, 97, 100 — other stable isotopes<br>• Molybdenum-99 (⁹⁹Mo) — radioactive parent of Technetium-99m<br>• Isotope ratios used to study marine redox conditions in Earth's history<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in the mineral Molybdenite (MoS₂)<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 1.2 ppm<br>• Found in trace amounts in most soils and ocean waters<br>• Never found free in nature; always as sulfides or oxides<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Roasting of molybdenite to produce molybdenum trioxide<br>• Pure metal produced by hydrogen reduction of molybdenum oxides<br>• Significant amount obtained as a byproduct of copper mining<br><br><b>Applications of Molybdenum</b><br>• Alloying agent for high-strength, high-temperature steels (HSLA)<br>• Jet engine components and turbine blades (heat resistance)<br>• Industrial catalysts for petroleum refining and chemical synthesis<br>• Electrical contacts and heating elements for vacuum furnaces<br>• Lubricants: Molybdenum disulfide (MoS₂) for high-load applications<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Critical cofactor for enzymes in human metabolism (e.g., Xanthine oxidase)<br>• Essential for the 'Nitrogenase' enzyme that allows plants to fix nitrogen<br>• Vital for understanding paleoceanographic climate cycles<br>• Key material for advanced materials science and high-temp engineering<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Energy — efficient petroleum refining and nuclear engineering<br>• Agriculture — essential micronutrient for nitrogen-fixing crops<br>• Aerospace — manufacturing of ultra-heat-resistant components<br>• Medicine — radioisotope precursor for diagnostic imaging",
    "system.molybdenum.fact": "Molybdenum has the atomic number 42 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.molybdenum": "Wikipedia - Molybdenum",
