    "system.technetium.title": "Technetium",
    "system.technetium.desc": "Technetium is element #43, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.technetium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Tc<br>• Atomic Number — 43<br>• The lowest atomic number element without stable isotopes<br>• First element to be produced artificially (hence 'Technetium' from Greek 'technetos' — artificial)<br>• Silvery-grey, radioactive transition metal<br>• Primarily used in nuclear medicine for diagnostic imaging<br>• Occurs naturally in trace amounts as a fission product of uranium<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 43 protons in the nucleus<br>• 43 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common isotope has 55 neutrons (Technetium-98)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 4d⁵ 5s²<br>• Located in the 5th period and 7th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-grey appearance, similar to platinum<br>• Boiling point — 4265°C<br>• Melting point — 2157°C<br>• Becomes superconducting at 7.46 K<br>• Paramagnetic (weakly attracted by external magnetic fields)<br>• Radioactive: emits beta and gamma radiation depending on the isotope<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Chemically similar to rhenium and manganese<br>• Dissolves in oxidizing acids (nitric, concentrated sulfuric)<br>• Forms a range of oxides, the most stable being Tc₂O₇<br>• Displays oxidation states from -1 to +7, with +4 and +7 being most common<br>• Effective corrosion inhibitor for steel (though limited by radioactivity)<br><br><b>Technetium Isotopes</b><br>• Technetium-99m (⁹⁹ᵐTc) — most widely used medical radioisotope (half-life 6 hours)<br>• Technetium-99 (⁹⁹Tc) — long-lived fission product (half-life 211,000 years)<br>• Technetium-98 (⁹⁸Tc) — most stable isotope (half-life 4.2 million years)<br>• Technetium-97 (⁹⁷Tc) — half-life 4.21 million years<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Extremely rare; found in trace amounts in uranium ores from spontaneous fission<br>• Found in the spectra of some red giant stars (proving nucleosynthesis)<br>• Found in the Earth's crust as a result of neutron capture by molybdenum<br>• Most on Earth is produced synthetically in nuclear reactors<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered from spent nuclear fuel rods via solvent extraction<br>• ⁹⁹ᵐTc is produced on-site in hospitals using 'Technetium generators' (from ⁹⁹Mo decay)<br>• Purified through ion-exchange and chemical precipitation<br><br><b>Applications of Technetium</b><br>• Medical Diagnostics: skeleton, heart, and organ imaging (approx. 80% of all nuclear medicine scans)<br>• Industrial Tracing: used to track flows in chemical plants and pipelines<br>• Calibration: Beta-emitter for scientific instrument calibration<br>• Research: used in materials science for corrosion studies<br>• Superconducting alloys for specialized scientific research<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Critical for non-invasive medical diagnostics and save millions of lives annually<br>• Fundamental for understanding stellar evolution and nucleosynthesis<br>• Vital for the development of radiopharmaceutical chemistry<br>• Key material for studying the properties of radioactive elements<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — diagnostic imaging and cancer localization<br>• Astrophysics — studying the composition and age of stars<br>• Energy — monitoring nuclear fuel cycles and reactor waste<br>• Chemistry — development of radioactive tracers and catalysts",
    "system.technetium.fact": "Technetium has the atomic number 43 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.technetium": "Wikipedia - Technetium",
    "resource.pubchem.technetium": "PubChem - Technetium",
