    "system.ruthenium.title": "Ruthenium",
    "system.ruthenium.desc": "Ruthenium is element #44, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.ruthenium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ru<br>• Atomic Number — 44<br>• A hard, brittle, silvery-white platinum group metal (PGM)<br>• Named after 'Ruthenia', the Latin name for Russia (region of origin)<br>• Exceptional resistance to chemical attack and wear<br>• One of the rarest elements in the Earth's crust<br>• Primarily used in the electronics and chemical industries<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 44 protons in the nucleus<br>• 44 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 58 neutrons (Ruthenium-102)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 4d⁷ 5s¹ (anomalous filling)<br>• Located in the 5th period and 8th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Lustrous, silvery-white metallic appearance<br>• Boiling point — 4150°C<br>• Melting point — 2334°C<br>• Highly resistant to tarnishing at room temperature<br>• Brittle metallic element (hard to machine but very durable)<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Becomes superconducting at 0.49 K<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Does not react with oxygen, water, or acids at room temperature<br>• Dissolves in molten alkalis and oxidizing agents (e.g., aqua regia with heating)<br>• Forms ruthenium tetroxide (RuO₄), a highly volatile and toxic oxide<br>• Acts as a powerful catalyst in organic chemistry and fuel cells<br>• Displays multiple oxidation states from 0 to +8<br><br><b>Ruthenium Isotopes</b><br>• Ruthenium-102 (¹⁰²Ru) — most abundant stable isotope (31.55%)<br>• Ruthenium-96, 98, 99, 100, 101, 104 — other stable isotopes<br>• Ruthenium-106 (¹⁰⁶Ru) — radioactive, used in medical radiotherapy for eye tumors<br>• Isotope ratios used in studies of meteorite origins and cosmic history<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in the Earth's crust as a minor component of platinum ores<br>• Concentration in the crust is about 0.001 ppm (extremely rare)<br>• Found in minerals like Laurite (RuS₂)<br>• Present in trace amounts in iron meteorites<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from platinum and nickel ores via complex chemical separation<br>• Purified through solvent extraction and reduction with hydrogen<br>• Obtained primarily as a byproduct of platinum mining in South Africa and Russia<br><br><b>Applications of Ruthenium</b><br>• Electronics: chip resistors and electrical contacts (wear resistance)<br>• Chemical Catalysts: ammonia synthesis and hydrogenation (Grubbs' catalysts)<br>• Hardening agent for platinum and palladium alloys<br>• Anodes for chlorine production in the chlor-alkali industry<br>• Medical treatment: plaques for ocular melanoma (radiotherapy)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Crucial for high-efficiency chemical and energy technologies<br>• Enabling material for advanced electronic components<br>• Potential in next-generation anti-cancer drugs (ruthenium-based complexes)<br>• Key material for studying solar energy conversion (dye-sensitized solar cells)<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Technology — high-reliability microelectronics and data storage<br>• Energy — fuel cells and solar energy research<br>• Medicine — radiotherapy and potential pharmaceutical developments<br>• Chemistry — advanced catalysis for industrial synthesis",
    "system.ruthenium.fact": "Ruthenium has the atomic number 44 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.ruthenium": "Wikipedia - Ruthenium",
    "resource.pubchem.ruthenium": "PubChem - Ruthenium",
