    "system.rhodium.title": "Rhodium",
    "system.rhodium.desc": "Rhodium is element #45, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.rhodium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Rh<br>• Atomic Number — 45<br>• A silver-white, hard, and chemically inert transition metal<br>• Member of the platinum group metals (PGM)<br>• One of the rarest and most valuable precious metals in the world<br>• Highly reflective and resistant to corrosion and oxidation<br>• Named after the Greek word 'rhodon' (rose), due to the color of its salts<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 45 protons in the nucleus<br>• 45 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 58 neutrons (Rhodium-103)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 4d⁸ 5s¹ (anomalous filling)<br>• Located in the 5th period and 9th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Lustrous, silvery-white metallic appearance<br>• Boiling point — 3695°C<br>• Melting point — 1964°C<br>• Lower density and higher melting point than platinum<br>• Exceptional reflectivity (often used for mirrors and jewelry plating)<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Ductile and malleable in its pure form<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Extremely resistant to corrosion by most acids (including aqua regia at room temp)<br>• Does not react with oxygen at room temperature<br>• Dissolves in hot concentrated sulfuric acid and molten alkalis<br>• Superb catalytic activity in automotive and industrial reactions<br>• Common oxidation states — +1, +2, +3, and +4<br><br><b>Rhodium Isotopes</b><br>• Rhodium-103 (¹⁰³Rh) — the only stable natural isotope<br>• Rhodium-101 (¹⁰¹Rh) — radioactive, used in scientific tracers<br>• Rhodium-102 (¹⁰²Rh) — long-lived radioisotope (half-life 2.9 years)<br>• Artificial isotopes used in nuclear medicine and physics research<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in the Earth's crust as a minor component of platinum ores<br>• Concentration in the crust is about 0.0001 ppm (extremely rare)<br>• Found in minerals like Rhodplumsite and Bowieite<br>• Present in trace amounts in iron-nickel meteorites<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from platinum and nickel ores via complex chemical processing<br>• Separated from other PGMs using solvent extraction and distillation<br>• Majority of global supply comes from South Africa and Russia<br><br><b>Applications of Rhodium</b><br>• Catalytic converters for cars (reduces nitrogen oxide emissions)<br>• Jewelry plating: gives white gold and silver a bright, non-tarnish finish<br>• High-performance mirrors for telescopes and searchlights<br>• Electrical contacts for high-reliability components<br>• Laboratory equipment: crucibles and thermocouples (heat resistance)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for reducing global air pollution (automotive catalysts)<br>• Essential for advanced optical and scientific instrumentation<br>• Enabling material for high-precision electrical engineering<br>• Important in the study of noble metal chemistry and catalysis<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Environment — emission control and air quality protection<br>• Arts — premium jewelry and luxury plating<br>• Technology — high-reliability electronics and optical devices<br>• Industry — chemical manufacturing and metallurgical engineering",
    "system.rhodium.fact": "Rhodium has the atomic number 45 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.rhodium": "Wikipedia - Rhodium",
    "resource.pubchem.rhodium": "PubChem - Rhodium",
