    "system.palladium.title": "Palladium",
    "system.palladium.desc": "Palladium is element #46, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.palladium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Pd<br>• Atomic Number — 46<br>• A lustrous, silvery-white transition metal in the platinum group (PGM)<br>• Named after the asteroid Pallas (which was named after the Greek goddess Athena)<br>• Unique ability to absorb up to 900 times its own volume of hydrogen gas<br>• Essential component of automotive catalytic converters<br>• Found primarily in South Africa and Russia<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 46 protons in the nucleus<br>• 46 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 60 neutrons (Palladium-106)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 4d¹⁰ (full 4d subshell, 5s empty)<br>• Located in the 5th period and 10th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white appearance, similar to platinum but less dense<br>• Boiling point — 2963°C<br>• Melting point — 1555°C (lowest of the platinum group metals)<br>• Soft and ductile metallic element (can be beaten into thin leaf)<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Maintains structural strength at high temperatures<br>• Non-magnetic and highly reflective<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Resistant to corrosion by air and most acids at room temperature<br>• Dissolves slowly in nitric acid and hot concentrated sulfuric acid<br>• Exceptional catalytic properties for hydrogenation and dehydrogenation<br>• Forms a range of complex compounds with organic molecules<br>• Common oxidation states — +2 and +4<br><br><b>Palladium Isotopes</b><br>• Palladium-106 (¹⁰⁶Pd) — most abundant stable isotope (27.33%)<br>• Palladium-102, 104, 105, 108, 110 — other stable isotopes<br>• Palladium-107 (¹⁰⁷Pd) — long-lived radioactive fission product<br>• Palladium-103 (¹⁰³Pd) — used in medical brachytherapy for prostate cancer<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in the Earth's crust as a component of platinum ores<br>• Concentration in the crust is about 0.015 ppm<br>• Found in minerals like Cooperite and Braggite<br>• Present in trace amounts in most nickel and copper sulfide deposits<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from copper and nickel ores via complex chemical separation<br>• Purified using solvent extraction and reduction with hydrogen<br>• Majority of global production is a byproduct of nickel mining in Russia<br><br><b>Applications of Palladium</b><br>• Catalytic converters for cars (reduces harmful emissions)<br>• Electronics: multi-layer ceramic capacitors and plating for connectors<br>• Hydrogen storage and purification (hydrogen filters)<br>• Dentistry: used in dental crowns and bridges (biocompatible)<br>• Jewelry: 'white gold' alloy and pure palladium jewelry<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Critical for green energy technology (hydrogen fuel cells)<br>• Key material for advanced organic chemical synthesis (Heck reaction)<br>• Vital for modern automotive emission control systems<br>• Fundamental for the study of metal-hydrogen interactions<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Environment — reducing automotive pollutants and carbon footprint<br>• Energy — hydrogen economy and fuel cell technology<br>• Medicine — cancer treatment (brachytherapy) and dental implants<br>• Technology — high-performance capacitors and microelectronics",
    "system.palladium.fact": "Palladium has the atomic number 46 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.palladium": "Wikipedia - Palladium",
    "resource.pubchem.palladium": "PubChem - Palladium",
