    "system.silver.title": "Silver",
    "system.silver.desc": "Silver is element #47, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.silver.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ag<br>• Atomic Number — 47<br>• A lustrous, white, and soft transition metal<br>• Highest electrical conductivity, thermal conductivity, and reflectivity of any metal<br>• Known since ancient times; one of the 'metals of antiquity'<br>• Valued as a precious metal for currency, jewelry, and investment<br>• Possesses natural antimicrobial properties (oligodynamic effect)<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 47 protons in the nucleus<br>• 47 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 60 neutrons (Silver-107)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 4d¹⁰ 5s¹ (stable full d-shell)<br>• Located in the 5th period and 11th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Brilliant white metallic luster, can be polished to a mirror finish<br>• Boiling point — 2162°C<br>• Melting point — 961.8°C<br>• Extremely ductile and malleable (second only to gold)<br>• Highest electrical conductivity (106% IACS)<br>• Best thermal conductor among all metals<br>• Diamagnetic (weakly repelled by magnetic fields)<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Relatively unreactive; does not oxidize in pure air or water<br>• Tarnishes when exposed to sulfur compounds in air (forms Ag₂S)<br>• Dissolves easily in nitric acid and hot concentrated sulfuric acid<br>• Forms sensitive compounds used in photography (Silver halides)<br>• Common oxidation states — +1 (most common) and +2<br><br><b>Silver Isotopes</b><br>• Silver-107 (¹⁰⁷Ag) — stable isotope (51.84%)<br>• Silver-109 (¹⁰⁹Ag) — stable isotope (48.16%)<br>• Silver-110m (¹¹⁰ᵐAg) — radioactive, used in industrial tracing<br>• Isotope ratios used to date objects and study archaeological silver origins<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in its native form as silver nuggets or 'wire' silver<br>• Found in minerals like Argentite (Ag₂S) and Chlorargyrite (AgCl)<br>• Often associated with gold, copper, lead, and zinc ores<br>• Concentration in the Earth's crust is about 0.075 ppm<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Primarily obtained as a byproduct of lead, zinc, and copper refining<br>• Parkes process: removes silver from lead using molten zinc<br>• Purified to high grade (99.9%+) via electrolytic refining<br><br><b>Applications of Silver</b><br>• Electronics: high-end connectors, PCBs, and solar panel cells<br>• Jewelry and Silverware (Sterling silver: 92.5% Ag, 7.5% Cu)<br>• Investment: coins, bars, and bullion products<br>• Photography: traditional film and paper (Silver bromide/nitrate)<br>• Medicine: wound dressings and catheters (antibacterial action)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Crucial for the global transition to renewable energy (solar PV)<br>• Vital for advanced electrical engineering and thermal management<br>• Important in the study of catalysis and nanotechnology (silver nanoparticles)<br>• Fundamental for understanding historical trade and economic development<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Energy — critical component for solar power generation<br>• Medicine — advanced infection control and wound care<br>• Finance — historical monetary standard and modern investment asset<br>• Arts — photography, fine jewelry, and luxury decorative arts",
    "system.silver.fact": "Silver has the atomic number 47 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.silver": "Wikipedia - Silver",
    "resource.pubchem.silver": "PubChem - Silver",
