    "system.cadmium.title": "Cadmium",
    "system.cadmium.desc": "Cadmium is element #48, a versatile transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.cadmium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Cd<br>• Atomic Number — 48<br>• A soft, silvery-white, and toxic transition metal<br>• Chemically similar to zinc and mercury<br>• Famous for its use in rechargeable NiCd batteries and bright pigments<br>• Highly toxic and carcinogenic; accumulates in the human body<br>• Primarily obtained as a byproduct of zinc production<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 48 protons in the nucleus<br>• 48 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 66 neutrons (Cadmium-114)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 4d¹⁰ 5s² (stable full shell)<br>• Located in the 5th period and 12th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white appearance with a bluish tinge<br>• Boiling point — 767°C<br>• Melting point — 321°C (relatively low melting point)<br>• Soft metal that can be cut with a knife<br>• Ductile and malleable<br>• Good electrical conductivity<br>• Produces a 'cry' (cracking sound) when bent, like tin<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts slowly with oxygen in moist air to form a protective oxide layer<br>• Dissolves easily in most acids, forming colorless Cd²⁺ ions<br>• Insoluble in alkalis<br>• Forms colorful compounds (e.g., Cadmium yellow CdS)<br>• Powerful neutron absorber (used in nuclear reactors)<br>• Common oxidation state — +2<br><br><b>Cadmium Isotopes</b><br>• Cadmium-114 (¹¹⁴Cd) — most abundant stable isotope (28.73%)<br>• Cadmium-106, 108, 110, 111, 112, 113, 116 — other stable isotopes<br>• Cadmium-109 (¹⁰⁹Cd) — radioactive, used in scientific X-ray fluorescence<br>• Isotope ratios used to track industrial pollution in soil and water<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in minerals like Greenockite (CdS)<br>• Always found in association with zinc, lead, and copper ores<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 0.1 ppm<br>• Naturally present in some phosphates and coal<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Obtained exclusively as a byproduct of zinc smelting and refining<br>• Separated from zinc via vacuum distillation or ion exchange<br>• Global production is carefully monitored due to toxicity<br><br><b>Applications of Cadmium</b><br>• Nickel-Cadmium (NiCd) rechargeable batteries (portable electronics)<br>• Corrosion-resistant plating for steel (electroplating)<br>• Pigments: Cadmium yellow, orange, and red for paints and plastics<br>• Control rods for nuclear reactors (neutron absorption)<br>• Semiconductors: Cadmium Telluride (CdTe) for thin-film solar cells<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Important for the development of thin-film photovoltaic technology<br>• Key element in toxicology research and environmental science<br>• Critical for neutron control in early nuclear physics research<br>• Major focus of international environmental protection regulations<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Energy — thin-film solar energy and battery storage<br>• Environment — monitoring heavy metal toxicity and industrial waste<br>• Industry — high-durability plating and vibrant pigments<br>• Physics — nuclear reactor control and X-ray fluorescence",
    "system.cadmium.fact": "Cadmium has the atomic number 48 and belongs to the Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.cadmium": "Wikipedia - Cadmium",
    "resource.pubchem.cadmium": "PubChem - Cadmium",
