    "system.indium.title": "Indium",
    "system.indium.desc": "Indium is element #49, a versatile post-transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.indium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — In<br>• Atomic Number — 49<br>• A very soft, silvery-white post-transition metal<br>• Critical component for touchscreens and liquid crystal displays (LCDs)<br>• Named after the indigo line in its atomic spectrum<br>• Does not occur as a free element in nature<br>• One of the least abundant minerals in the Earth's crust<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 49 protons in the nucleus<br>• 49 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 66 neutrons (Indium-115)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 4d¹⁰ 5s² 5p¹<br>• Located in the 5th period and 13th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white, lustrous appearance<br>• Boiling point — 2072°C<br>• Melting point — 156.6°C (very low for a metal)<br>• Extremely soft (can be scratched with a fingernail)<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Stays soft at extremely low temperatures (near absolute zero)<br>• Produces a 'cry' (cracking sound) when bent, like tin<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Stable in air and water under normal conditions<br>• Dissolves in mineral acids like hydrochloric and sulfuric acid<br>• Reacts with oxygen at high temperatures to form indium oxide (In₂O₃)<br>• Forms a wide range of organometallic compounds<br>• Common oxidation states — +1 and +3<br><br><b>Indium Isotopes</b><br>• Indium-115 (¹¹⁵In) — most abundant isotope (95.7%), extremely long-lived radioactive<br>• Indium-113 (¹¹³In) — stable isotope (4.3%)<br>• Indium-111 (¹¹¹In) — radioactive, used in medical diagnostic tracing (leukocytes)<br>• Isotope ratios used to track electronic waste and industrial pollution<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily as a trace component in zinc and lead ores<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 0.1 ppm (rarer than silver)<br>• Found in the mineral Indite (FeIn₂S₄), which is very rare<br>• Recovered almost exclusively as a byproduct of zinc smelting<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered from zinc-processing residues via solvent extraction<br>• Pure metal produced by electrolysis of indium-rich solutions<br>• Refined to ultra-high purity (99.9999%) for the semiconductor industry<br><br><b>Applications of Indium</b><br>• Indium Tin Oxide (ITO): transparent conductive coating for smartphones and TVs<br>• Low-melting alloys for fire sprinklers and specialized solder<br>• Control rods for nuclear reactors (high neutron capture cross-section)<br>• Thin-film solar cells (CIGS — Copper Indium Gallium Selenide)<br>• High-speed transistors and infrared detectors<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Enabling material for the modern touch-screen and display revolution<br>• Critical for next-generation efficient solar energy technology<br>• Important for understanding low-temperature materials science<br>• Vital for advanced medical diagnostics in nuclear medicine<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Technology — touchscreens, LCDs, and microelectronics<br>• Energy — advanced thin-film solar cells and nuclear control<br>• Medicine — radioisotope tracing and diagnostic imaging<br>• Engineering — vacuum seals and low-temperature soldering",
    "system.indium.fact": "Indium has the atomic number 49 and belongs to the Post-Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.indium": "Wikipedia - Indium",
    "resource.pubchem.indium": "PubChem - Indium",
