    "system.tin.title": "Tin",
    "system.tin.desc": "Tin is element #50, a versatile post-transition metal essential for various scientific and industrial applications.",
    "system.tin.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Sn<br>• Atomic Number — 50<br>• A silvery-white, soft, and malleable post-transition metal<br>• One of the earliest metals known to humanity (used for bronze since 3000 BC)<br>• Critical component of solder and protective coatings for food containers<br>• Named after the Latin word 'stannum'<br>• Possesses two major allotropes: grey (alpha) and white (beta) tin<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 50 protons in the nucleus<br>• 50 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 70 neutrons (Tin-120)<br>• Electron configuration — [Kr] 4d¹⁰ 5s² 5p²<br>• Located in the 5th period and 14th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• White tin is the common metallic form; grey tin is a non-metallic powder<br>• Boiling point — 2602°C<br>• Melting point — 231.9°C (relatively low for a metal)<br>• Highly malleable and ductile; can be rolled into thin foil<br>• Produces a 'tin cry' (characteristic sound) when bent due to crystal twining<br>• High corrosion resistance against water and atmospheric gases<br>• Good electrical conductivity in its metallic form<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Resistive to corrosion from air and distilled water<br>• Dissolves slowly in dilute acids and more rapidly in concentrated ones<br>• Forms a protective oxide film (SnO₂) on the surface<br>• Reacts with halogens to form various tin halides<br>• Common oxidation states — +2 (stannous) and +4 (stannic)<br><br><b>Tin Isotopes</b><br>• Tin has the largest number of stable isotopes of any element (10)<br>• Tin-120 (¹²⁰Sn) — most abundant stable isotope (32.59%)<br>• Tin-116, 117, 118, 119, 122, 124 — other stable isotopes<br>• Tin-126 (¹²⁶Sn) — long-lived radioactive fission product<br>• Isotope ratios used to trace the origin of ancient bronze artifacts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in the mineral Cassiterite (SnO₂)<br>• 49th most abundant element in the Earth's crust<br>• Concentration in the crust is about 2 ppm<br>• Found in alluvial deposits (placer tin) in many parts of the world<br>• Rarely found in its native elemental form<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Smelting of cassiterite ore with carbon in a reverberatory furnace<br>• Refined using electrolytic processes or liquation (heat separation)<br>• Large-scale recycling of tin plate and scrap is a major supply source<br><br><b>Applications of Tin</b><br>• Solder for electronics and plumbing (approx. 50% of usage)<br>• Tinplating for steel cans (food and beverage storage)<br>• Bronze and Brass manufacturing (copper-tin alloys)<br>• Babbitt metal for high-load bearings in machinery<br>• Float glass process: molten tin is used as a bed for high-quality glass sheets<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Fundamental for the development of human civilization (Bronze Age)<br>• Critical for modern electronics connectivity (solder technology)<br>• Key material for high-quality glass manufacturing<br>• Essential trace element for some biological systems (though toxic in organic form)<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Technology — electronic circuit assembly and connectivity<br>• History — study of ancient metallurgy and the Bronze Age<br>• Food Science — safe and durable food packaging technology<br>• Industry — high-load machinery components and glass production",
    "system.tin.fact": "Tin has the atomic number 50 and belongs to the Post-Transition Metal group.",
    "resource.wiki.tin": "Wikipedia - Tin",
    "resource.pubchem.tin": "PubChem - Tin",
