    "system.antimony.title": "Antimony",
    "system.antimony.desc": "An ancient metalloid that expands upon freezing, essential for flame retardants and semiconductors.",
    "system.antimony.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Sb<br>• Atomic Number — 51<br>• Lustrous gray metalloid known since ancient times<br>• Expands as it freezes (unusual property)<br>• Essential component of flame retardants (antimony trioxide)<br>• Name comes from 'anti' and 'monos' (not alone)<br>• Symbol Sb is from Latin 'stibium'<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 51 protons in the nucleus<br>• 51 electrons surrounding the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 70 neutrons (Antimony-121)<br>• Electron Configuration — [Kr] 4d¹⁰ 5s² 5p³<br>• Located in Period 5, Group 15 (Pnictogens)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white, brittle, and lustrous appearance<br>• Boiling Point — 1587°C<br>• Melting Point — 630.6°C<br>• Expands upon cooling, making it excellent for sharp-detail casting<br>• Poor conductor of heat and electricity compared to metals<br>• Mohs hardness of 3.0 (relatively soft for a solid)<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Stable in air at room temperature<br>• Reacts with oxygen when heated to form Sb₂O₃<br>• Dissolves in hot concentrated acids<br>• Reacts with halogens to form trihalides and pentahalides<br>• Typical oxidation states — -3, +3, and +5<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted mainly from the mineral stibnite (Sb₂S₃)<br>• Produced by roasting stibnite to oxide and then reducing with carbon<br>• High-purity antimony is refined by zone melting<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Flame Retardants: Used in plastics, textiles, and electronics<br>• Lead Alloys: Hardens lead for batteries and ammunition<br>• Electronics: Infrared detectors and Hall-effect devices<br>• Glass and Ceramics: Opacifier for enamels and glass coloring",
    "system.antimony.fact": "Antimony is one of the few substances (like water) that expands when it freezes from a liquid to a solid.",
    "resource.wiki.antimony": "Wikipedia: Antimony",
    "resource.pubchem.antimony": "PubChem - Antimony",
    "ai.antimony.simple": "Antimony is element 51, a metalloid used to make materials fire-resistant.",
    "ai.antimony.detailed": "Antimony is a semiconductor material. Its most stable form is a silvery-blue, brittle metal. It is primarily used in flame retardants and lead-acid batteries.",
