    "system.tellurium.title": "Tellurium",
    "system.tellurium.desc": "A rare silvery-white metalloid, critical for high-efficiency solar panels and rewriteable optical discs.",
    "system.tellurium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Te<br>• Atomic Number — 52<br>• Brittle, rare metalloid related to selenium and sulfur<br>• One of the rarest stable elements in the Earth's crust<br>• Essential for Cadmium Telluride (CdTe) solar cells<br>• Name comes from Latin 'tellus' meaning Earth<br>• Discovered in 1782 in Transylvania<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 52 protons in the nucleus<br>• 52 electrons surrounding the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 76 neutrons (Tellurium-128)<br>• Electron Configuration — [Kr] 4d¹⁰ 5s² 5p⁴<br>• Located in Period 5, Group 16 (Chalcogens)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white color with a metallic luster<br>• Boiling Point — 988°C<br>• Melting Point — 449.5°C<br>• Semiconductor (p-type conductivity improves with light exposure)<br>• Very brittle; easily pulverized into a powder<br>• High electrical resistivity compared to metals<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Insoluble in water and organic solvents<br>• Dissolves in oxidizing acids (nitric, aqua regia)<br>• Burns in air with a greenish-blue flame to form TeO₂<br>• Reacts with halogens to form various tellurides<br>• Typical oxidation states — -2, +2, +4, and +6<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered mainly from anode slimes of electrolytic copper refining<br>• Separated from selenium by selective precipitation<br>• Refined by vacuum distillation to high purity<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Solar Energy: Thin-film solar panels (CdTe)<br>• Metallurgy: Improves machinability of steel and copper<br>• Electronics: Thermal imaging and thermoelectric cooling devices<br>• Optical Discs: Phase-change material for rewriteable CDs/DVDs",
    "system.tellurium.fact": "Exposure to tellurium causes 'tellurium breath', giving the person a strong smell of garlic.",
    "resource.wiki.tellurium": "Wikipedia: Tellurium",
    "resource.pubchem.tellurium": "PubChem - Tellurium",
    "ai.tellurium.simple": "Tellurium is element 52, a rare material used to make solar panels efficient.",
    "ai.tellurium.detailed": "Tellurium is a p-type semiconductor. Chemically related to selenium and sulfur. Its main industrial uses are in alloying and solar energy.",
