    "system.iodine.title": "Iodine",
    "system.iodine.desc": "A dark-gray nonmetal that sublimes into purple vapors, vital for thyroid health and metabolism.",
    "system.iodine.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — I<br>• Atomic Number — 53<br>• Lustrous purple-black nonmetal from the halogen group<br>• Sublimes (turns from solid to gas) directly at room temperature<br>• Essential trace element for human health (hormone production)<br>• Heaviest element commonly needed by living organisms<br>• Name comes from Greek 'ioeides' meaning violet<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 53 protons in the nucleus<br>• 53 electrons surrounding the nucleus<br>• Only one stable natural isotope (Iodine-127)<br>• Electron Configuration — [Kr] 4d¹⁰ 5s² 5p⁵<br>• Located in Period 5, Group 17 (Halogens)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Shiny dark-gray solid; violet vapors with a pungent odor<br>• Boiling Point — 184.3°C<br>• Melting Point — 113.7°C<br>• Poor conductor of heat and electricity<br>• Slightly soluble in water, but highly soluble in organic solvents<br>• Reacts with starch to form an intense blue-black complex<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Least reactive of the common halogens but still a strong oxidant<br>• Combines with many elements to form iodides<br>• Forms unstable compounds with nitrogen (nitrogen triiodide)<br>• Can exhibit multiple oxidation states: -1, +1, +3, +5, and +7<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from brine deposits (underground salt water)<br>• Also recovered from caliche (Chile saltpeter) deposits<br>• Purified by sublimation to technical or pharmaceutical grade<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Health: Antiseptic (tincture of iodine) and thyroid treatment<br>• Imaging: X-ray contrast agents for medical scanning<br>• Technology: Polarizing films for LCD displays<br>• Agriculture: Animal feed supplements and soil treatment<br>• Meteorology: Silver iodide for cloud seeding (rain making)",
    "system.iodine.fact": "Iodine is the only element whose name is a single letter that is also a common word in English (as in 'I am').",
    "resource.wiki.iodine": "Wikipedia: Iodine",
    "resource.pubchem.iodine": "PubChem - Iodine",
    "ai.iodine.simple": "Iodine is element 53, a purple-colored material that helps our body stay healthy.",
    "ai.iodine.detailed": "Iodine is a blue-black solid. It is essential for producing thyroid hormones. Industrially, it is used in dyes, photography, and disinfectants.",
