    "system.xenon.title": "Xenon",
    "system.xenon.desc": "A heavy noble gas used in high-power lamps, ion propulsion, and medical anesthesia.",
    "system.xenon.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Xe<br>• Atomic Number — 54<br>• Heavy, colorless, and odorless noble gas<br>• Extremely rare in Earth's atmosphere (approx. 1 part per 11.5 million)<br>• First noble gas found to form true chemical compounds<br>• Name comes from Greek 'xenos' meaning stranger<br>• Emits a brilliant blue-lavender glow when excited by discharge<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 54 protons in the nucleus<br>• 54 electrons (full valence shell, stable)<br>• 9 natural isotopes; Xeonon-132 is the most common<br>• Electron Configuration — [Kr] 4d¹⁰ 5s² 5p⁶<br>• Located in Period 5, Group 18 (Noble Gases)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Gas at standard temperature; 4.5 times denser than air<br>• Boiling Point — -108.1°C<br>• Melting Point — -111.7°C<br>• High refractive index and optical clarity<br>• Can be liquefied and solidified under pressure<br>• Paralyzing effect on biological systems in high concentrations (anesthesia)<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Most reactive of the stable noble gases<br>• Forms compounds with fluorine and oxygen (e.g., XeF₂, XeO₃)<br>• Xe-fluorides are powerful fluorinating agents<br>• Can form clathrates with water and other molecules<br>• Oxidation states range from +2 to +8 in compounds<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced as a byproduct of fractional distillation of liquid air<br>• Extremely expensive due to low atmospheric concentration<br>• Purified to electronic or medical grade by repeated distillation<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Lighting: High-intensity discharge lamps, camera flashes, cinema projectors<br>• Space Travel: Propellant for ion thrusters (high atomic mass)<br>• Medicine: General anesthetic (safer than traditional agents)<br>• Imaging: MRI of lungs using hyperpolarized Xenon-129<br>• Industry: Bubble chambers for particle detection",
    "system.xenon.fact": "Xenon is used in ion engines for deep space missions because its heavy atoms provide efficient thrust.",
    "resource.wiki.xenon": "Wikipedia: Xenon",
    "resource.pubchem.xenon": "PubChem - Xenon",
    "ai.xenon.simple": "Xenon is element 54, a special gas used in bright lights and space rockets.",
    "ai.xenon.detailed": "Xenon is used in light-emitting devices and general anesthesia. It is significantly denser than air. It is also the propellant of choice for ion engines in space.",
    "ai.xenon.study.1": "Atomic Number: 54",
