    "system.cesium.title": "Cesium",
    "system.cesium.desc": "The most reactive alkali metal, defining the global standard of time through atomic clocks.",
    "system.cesium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Cs<br>• Atomic Number — 55<br>• Silvery-gold, extremely reactive alkali metal<br>• Softest metal at room temperature (can be cut with a leaf)<br>• Defines the international 'second' (9,192,631,770 cycles)<br>• Explodes violently upon contact with water or ice<br>• Name comes from Latin 'caesius' meaning sky-blue<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 55 protons in the nucleus<br>• 55 electrons (one valence electron, highly unstable)<br>• One stable natural isotope (Cesium-133)<br>• Electron Configuration — [Xe] 6s¹<br>• Located in Period 6, Group 1 (Alkali Metals)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-gold color, very soft and ductile<br>• Boiling Point — 671°C<br>• Melting Point — 28.4°C (melts in a warm room)<br>• Lowest electronegativity and ionization energy of all elements<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Liquid range is larger than any other element except Gallium<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Most electropositive of all stable elements<br>• Reacts explosively with water to form CsOH and H₂<br>• Ignites spontaneously in air (pyrophoric)<br>• Forms stable salts with halides (e.g., CsCl)<br>• Strongest reducing agent known in chemistry<br>• Typical oxidation state — +1<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from the mineral pollucite<br>• Produced by reducing cesium chloride with calcium at high temp<br>• Handled in vacuum or inert atmosphere due to high reactivity<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Timekeeping: Cesium atomic clocks (primary time standards)<br>• Petroleum: Cesium formate brine for high-pressure drilling<br>• Electronics: Vacuum tubes, photoelectric cells, and IR lamps<br>• Science: Centrifugation in biochemistry (CsCl gradients)<br>• Energy: Thermionic power converters",
    "system.cesium.fact": "A cesium atomic clock is so accurate that it would lose only one second in over 100 million years.",
    "resource.wiki.cesium": "Wikipedia: Cesium",
    "resource.pubchem.cesium": "PubChem - Cesium",
    "ai.cesium.simple": "Cesium is element 55, a metal that is so sensitive it explodes in water, but also helps us keep time perfectly.",
    "ai.cesium.detailed": "Cesium is vital for high-precision time measurement. Cesium atomic clocks lose only one second every 100 million years.",
    "ai.cesium.study.1": "Atomic Number: 55",
    "ai.cesium.study.2": "Symbol: Cs",
    "ai.cesium.study.3": "Group: Alkali Metals",
    "ai.cesium.study.4": "Mass: 132.91",
    "ai.cesium.study.5": "Defines: The Second",
