    "system.barium.title": "Barium",
    "system.barium.desc": "A dense alkaline earth metal, essential for medical imaging of the digestive system and oil drilling.",
    "system.barium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ba<br>• Atomic Number — 56<br>• Soft, silvery-white alkaline earth metal<br>• Rapidly oxidizes in air, turning dark gray<br>• Used as 'barium swallow' for X-ray imaging of the GI tract<br>• Name comes from Greek 'barys' meaning heavy<br>• Highly toxic in soluble form, but safe in insoluble BaSO₄<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 56 protons in the nucleus<br>• 56 electrons (two valence electrons)<br>• 7 stable natural isotopes; Barium-138 is the most abundant<br>• Electron Configuration — [Xe] 6s²<br>• Located in Period 6, Group 2 (Alkaline Earth Metals)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white appearance when pure<br>• Boiling Point — 1897°C<br>• Melting Point — 727°C<br>• High density (3.51 g/cm³) compared to lighter group members<br>• Very soft; slightly harder than lead<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Burns with a distinctive apple-green flame<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive; must be stored under oil<br>• Reacts vigorously with water to form Ba(OH)₂ and H₂<br>• Reacts with oxygen at room temp to form BaO<br>• Forms stable, insoluble sulfates and carbonates<br>• Typical oxidation state — +2<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Mainly extracted from the mineral barite (BaSO₄)<br>• Produced by reducing barium oxide with aluminum at high temp<br>• Purified by vacuum distillation<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Medicine: Radiocontrast agent (barium sulfate) for X-rays<br>• Oil Industry: Weighting agent in drilling fluids (barite)<br>• Pyrotechnics: Green color in fireworks and flares<br>• Industry: 'Getter' in vacuum tubes to remove traces of air<br>• Metallurgy: Alloyed with lead to harden spark plug wires",
    "system.barium.fact": "Barium is responsible for the brilliant green color you see in professional fireworks displays.",
    "resource.wiki.barium": "Wikipedia: Barium",
    "resource.pubchem.barium": "PubChem - Barium",
    "ai.barium.simple": "Barium is element 56, a heavy metal used by doctors to see inside the body and to make green fireworks.",
    "ai.barium.detailed": "Barium is a soft silvery-white metal. Its sulfate is widely used in digestive X-rays because it is opaque to radiation and does not dissolve in the body.",
    "ai.barium.study.1": "Atomic Number: 56",
