    "system.cerium.title": "Cerium",
    "system.cerium.desc": "The most abundant rare earth metal, essential for catalytic converters and making sparks in lighters.",
    "system.cerium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ce<br>• Atomic Number — 58<br>• Most common rare earth element in the Earth's crust<br>• Pyrophoric (creates sparks when scratched or struck)<br>• Key component of self-cleaning ovens and glass polishing<br>• Named after the dwarf planet Ceres<br>• Discovered in 1803 in Sweden and Germany simultaneously<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 58 protons in the nucleus<br>• 58 electrons (4f¹, 5d¹, 6s² configuration)<br>• 4 stable isotopes; Cerium-140 is the most abundant<br>• Electron Configuration — [Xe] 4f¹ 5d¹ 6s²<br>• Located in Period 6 (Lanthanides)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Iron-gray color; malleable and ductile<br>• Boiling Point — 3443°C<br>• Melting Point — 798°C<br>• One of the few elements with multiple crystal structures (allotropes)<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br>• Relatively soft (Mohs hardness 2.5)<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive, especially in moist air<br>• Reacts with water to form Ce(OH)₃ and H₂<br>• Burns easily if heated or scratched (pyrophoric)<br>• Forms two main oxides: Ce₂O₃ and CeO₂ (Ceria)<br>• Exhibits dual oxidation states: +3 and +4<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered from bastnäsite and monazite minerals<br>• Separated from other lanthanides by selective oxidation to +4 state<br>• High-purity cerium is produced by electrolysis of the chloride<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Environment: Catalytic converters in cars (reduces emissions)<br>• Optics: Ceria (CeO₂) is the standard for glass polishing<br>• Fire: Flints for cigarette lighters and torches (mischmetal)<br>• Industry: Self-cleaning ovens and specialized glass manufacturing<br>• Metallurgy: Improves the properties of stainless steel and cast iron",
    "system.cerium.fact": "Cerium is so pyrophoric that small pieces will catch fire just from being scratched by a knife.",
    "resource.wiki.cerium": "Wikipedia: Cerium",
    "resource.pubchem.cerium": "PubChem - Cerium",
    "ai.cerium.simple": "Cerium is element 58, a common metal that helps clean car exhausts and makes lighters work.",
    "ai.cerium.detailed": "Cerium is used in lighter flints because it sparks when struck. Its oxide is the standard material for polishing optics and glass.",
