    "system.praseodymium.title": "Praseodymium",
    "system.praseodymium.desc": "A soft silvery metal used in high-power magnets, aircraft engines, and specialized welding goggles.",
    "system.praseodymium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Pr<br>• Atomic Number — 59<br>• Soft, silvery-white rare earth metal<br>• Always found together with Neodymium (the 'twins')<br>• Used in Didymium glass to filter out bright yellow sodium light<br>• Name comes from Greek 'prasios' (green) and 'didymos' (twin)<br>• Develops a green oxide layer when exposed to air<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 59 protons in the nucleus<br>• 59 electrons surrounding the nucleus<br>• One stable natural isotope (Praseodymium-141)<br>• Electron Configuration — [Xe] 4f³ 6s²<br>• Located in Period 6 (Lanthanides)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Soft, silvery appearance; malleable and ductile<br>• Boiling Point — 3130°C<br>• Melting Point — 935°C<br>• More corrosion-resistant than many other lanthanides<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br>• High electrical conductivity for a rare earth element<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Slowly oxidizes in air to form a green coating (Pr₆O₁₁)<br>• Reacts with water to form Pr(OH)₃ and H₂<br>• Dissolves in dilute mineral acids<br>• Forms brilliantly colored green salts used in ceramics<br>• Exhibits multiple oxidation states: +3 and +4<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered from monazite and bastnäsite minerals<br>• Separated from neodymium by solvent extraction or ion exchange<br>• Metal is produced by electrolysis of the fused chloride<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Safety: Didymium glass for welders' and glassblowers' goggles<br>• Magnets: Component of Pr-Nd high-strength magnets<br>• Engines: High-strength alloys for aircraft engine parts<br>• Ceramics: Vibrant green coloring for tiles and enamels<br>• Lighting: Specialized studio lighting and carbon arcs",
    "system.praseodymium.fact": "Praseodymium salts are used to color cubic zirconia a vibrant yellow-green, mimicking fine peridot.",
    "resource.wiki.praseodymium": "Wikipedia: Praseodymium",
    "resource.pubchem.praseodymium": "PubChem - Praseodymium",
    "ai.praseodymium.simple": "Praseodymium is element 59, a silvery metal that makes magnets stronger and protects welders' eyes.",
    "ai.praseodymium.detailed": "Praseodymium is always found together with neodymium. It is used in aircraft engines and in didymium glass, which filters out bright yellow sodium flames.",
    "ai.praseodymium.study.1": "Atomic Number: 59",
