    "system.neodymium.title": "Neodymium",
    "system.neodymium.desc": "A bright silvery metal, the key ingredient in the world's strongest permanent magnets.",
    "system.neodymium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Nd<br>• Atomic Number — 60<br>• Silvery-white, lustrous rare earth metal<br>• Primary component of NdFeB magnets (strongest magnets known)<br>• Used in high-power lasers for surgery and industry<br>• Name comes from Greek 'neos' (new) and 'didymos' (twin)<br>• Oxidizes quickly in air, requiring a protective coating<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 60 protons in the nucleus<br>• 60 electrons surrounding the nucleus<br>• 5 stable natural isotopes; Neodymium-142 is the most common<br>• Electron Configuration — [Xe] 4f⁴ 6s²<br>• Located in Period 6 (Lanthanides)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Bright silvery appearance; soft and malleable<br>• Boiling Point — 3074°C<br>• Melting Point — 1021°C<br>• Strong magnetic susceptibility; ferromagnetic in alloy form<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature as a pure metal<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• One of the more reactive rare earth metals<br>• Tarnish in air forms a gray oxide layer (Nd₂O₃) that flakes off<br>• Reacts with water to form Nd(OH)₃ and H₂<br>• Dissolves readily in mineral acids<br>• Typical oxidation state — +3<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from monazite and bastnäsite minerals<br>• Separated from praseodymium by ion exchange or solvent extraction<br>• Metal is produced by electrolysis of the halide or fluoride<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Energy: Neodymium magnets for electric vehicle motors and wind turbines<br>• Technology: Hard drives, headphones, and smartphone speakers<br>• Medicine: Nd:YAG lasers for laser eye surgery and dentistry<br>• Industry: Glass coloring (purple/violet) and UV filters<br>• Science: Powerful magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) equipment",
    "system.neodymium.fact": "A neodymium magnet the size of a coin can lift a weight of more than 10 kilograms.",
    "resource.wiki.neodymium": "Wikipedia: Neodymium",
    "resource.pubchem.neodymium": "PubChem - Neodymium",
    "ai.neodymium.simple": "Neodymium is element 60, a silvery metal famous for making incredibly strong magnets.",
    "ai.neodymium.detailed": "Neodymium magnets are essential for smartphones, electric vehicles, and wind turbines. It is also used for lasers in surgery and industry.",
