    "ai.neodymium.q5.opt.4": "Shoes",
    "system.immune.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>\n• Chemical Symbol — O<br>\n• Atomic Number — 8<br>\n• Atomic Mass — 15.999<br>\n• Group — Chalcogens (Nonmetals)<br>\n• Most abundant element in the Earth's crust (46% by mass)<br>\n• Vital for the respiration of most living organisms<br><br>\n\n<b>Atomic Structure</b><br>\n• 8 protons in the nucleus<br>\n• 8 electrons around the nucleus<br>\n• Contains 8 neutrons (Oxygen-16)<br>\n• Electron configuration — [He] 2s² 2p⁴<br>\n• Located in the 2nd period and 16th group<br><br>\n\n<b>Physical Properties</b><br>\n• Colorless, odorless, and tasteless gas<br>\n• In liquid and solid states, it has a pale blue color<br>\n• Boiling point — −183°C<br>\n• Possesses paramagnetic properties (attracted by a magnet in liquid form)<br>\n• Ozone (O₃) — an allotropic modification with a characteristic odor<br><br>\n\n<b>Chemical Properties</b><br>\n• Strong oxidant (second only to fluorine in electronegativity — 3.44)<br>\n• Supports combustion but is not flammable itself<br>\n• Reacts with almost all elements to form oxides<br>\n• Interacts with hydrogen releasing huge amounts of energy (water formation)<br><br>\n\n<b>Oxygen Isotopes</b><br>\n• Oxygen-16 (¹⁶O) — primary isotope (99.76%)<br>\n• Oxygen-18 (¹⁸O) — used in paleoclimatology to study past temperatures<br><br>\n\n<b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>\n• 21% of the Earth's atmosphere by volume<br>\n• Found in water (89% by mass) and rocks<br>\n• A component of all organic substances: proteins, fats, carbohydrates<br>\n• The ozone layer in the stratosphere protects Earth from UV radiation<br><br>\n\n<b>Industrial Production</b><br>\n• Fractional distillation of liquid air<br>\n• Electrolysis of water (for ultra-pure oxygen)<br>\n• Membrane air separation<br><br>\n\n<b>Applications of Oxygen</b><br>\n• Medicine: breathing mixtures, resuscitation, therapy<br>\n• Metallurgy: steel manufacturing (oxygen blast)<br>\n• Rocketry: as a fuel oxidant (LOX)<br>\n• Metal welding and cutting (oxy-fuel)<br>\n• Wastewater treatment and chemical production<br><br>\n\n<b>Biological Significance</b><br>\n• Cellular metabolism: glucose oxidation for energy (ATP)<br>\n• Photosynthesis: oxygen release by plants as a byproduct<br>\n• Involvement in decomposition and mineralization of organic matter<br><br>\n\n<b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>\n• Ecology — maintaining atmospheric composition<br>\n• Energy — combustion of fossil fuels<br>\n• Aerospace — life support systems on spacecraft<br>\n• Chemistry — study of oxidation and combustion processes",
    "system.urinary.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Cl<br>• Atomic Number — 17<br>• A highly reactive pale green gas from the Halogens group<br>• Powerful oxidizing agent used for disinfection<br>• Essential for life, found in salt and stomach acid<br>• Second lightest halogen after fluorine<br>• Distinctive, suffocating odor even at low concentrations<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 17 protons in the nucleus<br>• 17 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 18 neutrons (Chlorine-35)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ne] 3s² 3p⁵<br>• Located in the 3rd period and 17th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Gas at standard temperature and pressure<br>• Boiling point — −34.04°C<br>• Melting point — −101.5°C<br>• 2.5 times denser than air<br>• Pale yellow-green color<br>• Soluble in water (forms chlorine water)<br>• Liquefies easily under pressure<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with nearly all elements<br>• Supports combustion of many substances<br>• Reacts with water to form hypochlorous acid (HClO)<br>• Strong bleaching and disinfecting properties<br>• Forms ionic chlorides with metals and covalent chlorides with non-metals<br>• Common oxidation states — -1, +1, +3, +5, and +7<br><br><b>Chlorine Isotopes</b><br>• Chlorine-35 (³⁵Cl) — stable isotope (75.77%)<br>• Chlorine-37 (³⁷Cl) — stable isotope (24.23%)<br>• Chlorine-36 (³⁶Cl) — radioactive tracer found in the environment<br>• Isotope ratios used for geological dating and tracking water sources<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Primarily found as Chloride ions (Cl⁻) in seawater<br>• Found in mineral deposits as Halite (NaCl) and Sylvite (KCl)<br>• Essential component of solar system's planetary crusts<br>• Never found as a free gas in nature due to high reactivity<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Chloralkali process (electrolysis of brine)<br>• Produced as a coproduct with sodium hydroxide and hydrogen<br>• Liquefied and transported in pressurized tanks<br><br><b>Applications of Chlorine</b><br>• Water purification and swimming pool sanitation<br>• Production of PVC (polyvinyl chloride) plastic<br>• Bleaching agent for paper and textiles<br>• Manufacture of pharmaceuticals and disinfectants<br>• Synthesis of agricultural chemicals (pesticides)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential electrolyte for maintaining fluid balance in humans<br>• Component of hydrochloric acid in the stomach for digestion<br>• Crucial for industrial organic chemistry and polymer science<br>• Fundamental in the study of oxidation-reduction reactions<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Biology — digestion and cellular electrolyte balance<br>• Medicine — disinfection and drug synthesis<br>• Industry — plastics, textiles, and paper production<br>• Ecology — monitoring water quality and ozone depletion",
    "ai.title": "Syntara AI Assistant",
    "ai.chat.placeholder": "Select a mode to start learning...",
    "ai.btn.simple": "Briefly",
    "ai.btn.details": "In detail",
    "ai.btn.study": "Study",
