    "ai.rec.industry": "Check the industrial applications of the element.",
    "system.muscular.title": "Sodium",
    "system.muscular.desc": "A soft, silvery, and highly reactive metal, essential for life and industry.",
    "system.muscular.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>\n• Chemical Symbol — Na<br>\n• Atomic Number — 11<br>\n• An alkali metal from the 1st group<br>\n• Highly reactive, soft, silvery-white metal<br>\n• Essential for life and widely used in industry<br>\n• Quickly oxidizes when exposed to air<br>\n• Must be stored under mineral oil to prevent reaction<br><br>\n\n<b>Atomic Structure</b><br>\n• 11 protons in the nucleus<br>\n• 11 electrons around the nucleus<br>\n• Most common stable isotope has 12 neutrons (Sodium-23)<br>\n• Electron configuration — [Ne] 3s¹ (one valence electron)<br>\n• Located in the 3rd period and 1st group of the periodic table<br><br>\n\n<b>Physical Properties</b><br>\n• Low density (floats on water)<br>\n• Boiling point — 883°C<br>\n• Melting point — 97.8°C<br>\n• Soft enough to be cut with a knife<br>\n• Metallic element with high thermal and electrical conductivity<br>\n• Silvery luster when freshly cut<br>\n• Excellent heat conductor in liquid form<br><br>\n\n<b>Chemical Properties</b><br>\n• Reacts violently with water → forms sodium hydroxide and hydrogen<br>\n• Produces a characteristic bright yellow flame during a flame test<br>\n• Forms ionic bonds with non-metals (e.g., NaCl)<br>\n• Highly electropositive and a strong reducing agent<br>\n• Rapidly forms an oxide layer in contact with moisture<br>\n• Common oxidation state — +1<br><br>\n\n<b>Sodium Isotopes</b><br>\n• Sodium-23 (²³Na) — the only stable natural isotope<br>\n• Sodium-22 (²²Na) — radioactive isotope used in medicine (PET)<br>\n• Sodium-24 (²⁴Na) — used as a tracer in industrial pipelines<br>\n• Artificial isotopes are used in nuclear and medical research<br><br>\n\n<b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>\n• Found in seawater as dissolved ions (Na⁺)<br>\n• Present in mineral deposits as Halite (table salt)<br>\n• Found in silicate minerals like feldspar<br>\n• Part of the Earth's crust (6th most abundant element)<br>\n• Never exists in free elemental form in nature due to high reactivity<br><br>\n\n<b>Industrial Production</b><br>\n• Electrolysis of molten sodium chloride (Downs process)<br>\n• Obtained from underground salt mines or salt flats<br>\n• Produced as a byproduct in some chemical processes<br>\n• Energy-intensive process requiring high-temperature molten salts<br><br>\n\n<b>Applications of Sodium</b><br>\n• Production of table salt (NaCl) and baking soda<br>\n• Sodium-vapor lamps for energy-efficient street lighting<br>\n• Coolant in fast breeder nuclear reactors<br>\n• Synthesis of chemical compounds and pharmaceuticals<br>\n• Desiccant in organic chemistry for drying solvents<br>\n• Key component in sodium-ion batteries<br><br>\n\n<b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>\n• Primary cation in extracellular fluid for humans<br>\n• Essential for nerve impulse transmission and muscle contraction<br>\n• Regulates osmotic pressure and water balance in cells<br>\n• Fundamental in salt chemistry and ionic bonding studies<br>\n• Critical for the food industry as a preservative and seasoning<br><br>\n\n<b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>\n• Chemistry — basic element in inorganic synthesis<br>\n• Biology — critical electrolyte for life<br>\n• Medicine — saline solutions and diagnostic tracers<br>\n• Energy — nuclear coolants and battery technology<br>\n• Industry — production of glass, paper, and soap",
    "system.nervous.title": "Magnesium",
    "system.nervous.desc": "A lightweight metal essential for plant photosynthesis and human muscle function.",
    "system.nervous.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>\n• Chemical Symbol — Mg<br>\n• Atomic Number — 12<br>\n• An alkaline earth metal from the 2nd group<br>\n• Lightweight, strong, silvery-gray metal<br>\n• Essential mineral for plants and the human body<br>\n• Burns with a brilliant, dazzling white light<br>\n• 8th most abundant element in the Earth's crust<br><br>\n\n<b>Atomic Structure</b><br>\n• 12 protons in the nucleus<br>\n• 12 electrons around the nucleus<br>\n• Most common stable isotope has 12 neutrons (Magnesium-24)<br>\n• Electron configuration — [Ne] 3s² (two valence electrons)<br>\n• Located in the 3rd period and 2nd group of the periodic table<br><br>\n\n<b>Physical Properties</b><br>\n• Low density (1/3 lighter than aluminum)<br>\n• Boiling point — 1090°C<br>\n• Melting point — 650°C<br>\n• High strength-to-weight ratio<br>\n• Metallic luster that tarnishes slightly in air<br>\n• Good thermal and electrical conductivity<br>\n• Brittle at room temperature, but ductile when heated<br><br>\n\n<b>Chemical Properties</b><br>\n• Reacts with water slowly at room temperature, rapidly when boiling<br>\n• Highly flammable when in thin strips or powder form<br>\n• Reacts with acids to release hydrogen gas<br>\n• Forms a protective oxide layer that prevents further corrosion<br>\n• Strong reducing agent used in metal extraction<br>\n• Common oxidation state — +2<br><br>\n\n<b>Magnesium Isotopes</b><br>\n• Magnesium-24 (²⁴Mg) — most common stable isotope (79%)<br>\n• Magnesium-25 (²⁵Mg) — stable isotope (10%)<br>\n• Magnesium-26 (²⁶Mg) — stable isotope (11%)<br>\n• Used in scientific research for tracing metabolic pathways<br><br>\n\n<b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>\n• Found in minerals such as Magnesite and Dolomite<br>\n• Abundant in seawater as dissolved magnesium salts<br>\n• Present in the Earth's crust as a component of many rocks<br>\n• Central atom in the chlorophyll molecule of plants<br>\n• Never found free in nature due to high reactivity<br><br>\n\n<b>Industrial Production</b><br>\n• Electrolysis of molten magnesium chloride from seawater<br>\n• Pidgeon process (thermal reduction of magnesium oxide)<br>\n• Extraction from brine or magnesium-rich minerals<br>\n• Purified through specialized smelting and distillation<br><br>\n\n<b>Applications of Magnesium</b><br>\n• Aerospace and automotive alloys for weight reduction<br>\n• Production of flares, fireworks, and incendiary devices<br>\n• Lightweight cases for laptops, phones, and cameras<br>\n• Medical uses: antacids, laxatives, and supplements<br>\n• Desulfurization in iron and steel manufacturing<br>\n• Sacrificial anodes to prevent corrosion in pipelines<br><br>\n\n<b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>\n• Essential for photosynthesis (central part of chlorophyll)<br>\n• Involved in over 300 enzymatic reactions in the human body<br>\n• Critical for bone health, muscle function, and DNA synthesis<br>\n• Key element in the development of lightweight structural materials<br>\n• Important for heart rhythm regulation and nerve signaling<br><br>\n\n<b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>\n• Chemistry — used as a reagent (Grignard reagents)<br>\n• Biology — fundamental for plant and animal life<br>\n• Medicine — widely used in nutritional supplements<br>\n• Aerospace — critical for building lightweight aircraft<br>\n• Engineering — development of high-performance alloys",
    "system.integumentary.title": "Aluminum",
    "system.integumentary.desc": "The most abundant metal in the Earth's crust, lightweight and corrosion-resistant.",
    "system.integumentary.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Al<br>• Atomic Number — 13<br>• A post-transition metal from the 13th group<br>• Most abundant metal in the Earth's crust<br>• Lightweight, silvery-white, and durable metal<br>• Non-magnetic and non-sparking<br>• Highly resistant to corrosion due to its oxide layer<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 13 protons in the nucleus<br>• 13 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 14 neutrons (Aluminum-27)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ne] 3s² 3p¹<br>• Located in the 3rd period and 13th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Low density (approx. 2.70 g/cm³)<br>• Boiling point — 2470°C<br>• Melting point — 660.3°C<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Excellent malleability and ductility<br>• Reflects about 92% of visible light<br>• Remains strong at very low temperatures<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with oxygen to form a thin protective Al₂O₃ layer<br>• Amphoteric: reacts with both acids and strong bases<br>• Not easily flammable in solid form, but powder is explosive<br>• Forms trivalent compounds (oxidation state +3)<br>• Reacts with halogens to form halides<br><br><b>Aluminum Isotopes</b><br>• Aluminum-27 (²⁷Al) — the only stable natural isotope<br>• Aluminum-26 (²⁶Al) — radioactive, used in radiometric dating<br>• Artificial isotopes used in scientific tracing<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in minerals like Bauxite and Cryolite<br>• Present in gems like Rubies and Sapphires (as Al₂O₃)<br>• Never found in free elemental form in nature<br>• Found in almost all rocks and soils<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Hall-Héroult process (electrolysis of alumina)<br>• Bayer process (extraction from bauxite ore)<br>• Recyclable indefinitely with low energy cost<br><br><b>Applications of Aluminum</b><br>• Aerospace industry ('the winged metal')<br>• Packaging: foil, beverage cans, and containers<br>• Construction: window frames, roofs, and siding<br>• Transportation: car bodies and train components<br>• High-voltage power transmission lines<br><br><b>Significance in Science</b><br>• Fundamental for modern lightweight engineering<br>• Essential for the development of sustainable transport<br>• Key material for cryogenic technology<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Engineering — aircraft and vehicle design<br>• Food Industry — safe packaging and utensils<br>• Construction — modern skyscrapers and bridges<br>• Energy — efficient electrical grids",
    "system.respiratory.title": "Silicon",
    "system.respiratory.desc": "The foundation of modern electronics and the second most abundant element in the Earth's crust.",
    "system.respiratory.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Br<br>• Atomic Number — 35<br>• A reddish-brown, foul-smelling liquid halogen<br>• One of only two elements that are liquid at room temperature (with mercury)<br>• Highly reactive and volatile, evaporates easily into toxic gas<br>• Named after the Greek word 'bromos' (stench)<br>• Essential for marine biology but toxic to humans in high doses<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 35 protons in the nucleus<br>• 35 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 44 neutrons (Bromine-79)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s² 4p⁵<br>• Located in the 4th period and 17th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Dense, reddish-brown liquid with high vapor pressure<br>• Boiling point — 58.8°C<br>• Melting point — −7.2°C<br>• Evaporates quickly to form a suffocating brown gas<br>• Slightly soluble in water (forms bromine water)<br>• Highly soluble in organic solvents like carbon disulfide<br>• Non-metallic element with a strong, irritating odor<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Strong oxidizing agent, reacts with most metals and non-metals<br>• Reacts with water to form hypobromous acid (HBrO)<br>• Less reactive than chlorine but more reactive than iodine<br>• Forms bromides with alkali metals and other elements<br>• Common oxidation states — -1, +1, +3, +5, and +7<br><br><b>Bromine Isotopes</b><br>• Bromine-79 (⁷⁹Br) — stable isotope (50.69%)<br>• Bromine-81 (⁸¹Br) — stable isotope (49.31%)<br>• Bromine-82 (⁸²Br) — radioactive, used in hydrology and tracking leaks<br>• Isotope ratios used in studies of organic pollutants and atmosphere<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily as bromide ions (Br⁻) in seawater and salt lakes<br>• Abundant in the Dead Sea and deep salt deposits<br>• Concentration in the Earth's crust is about 2.5 ppm<br>• Found in certain marine plants and invertebrates<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced from brine via oxidation with chlorine gas<br>• Recovered by blowing air through chlorinated brine to strip bromine gas<br>• Purified through condensation and distillation<br><br><b>Applications of Bromine</b><br>• Flame retardants (BFRs) for electronics and furniture (major usage)<br>• Agricultural chemicals: pesticides and fumigants<br>• Water treatment: swimming pool and industrial water sanitation<br>• Photography: silver bromide for film and paper<br>• Pharmaceuticals: sedatives and specialty drugs<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential cofactor for tissue development in some animals<br>• Key element in the study of organic reaction mechanisms (halogenation)<br>• Vital for understanding ozone depletion in the atmosphere<br>• Important in specialized industrial chemical synthesis<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Safety — flame retardant technology in public spaces<br>• Environment — monitoring atmospheric chemistry and ozone layer<br>• Agriculture — soil fumigation and crop protection<br>• Medicine — historical use as sedatives and modern chemical synthesis",
    "system.digestive.title": "Phosphorus",
    "system.digestive.desc": "A vital element that is part of DNA, bones, and provides energy transfer in cells.",
    "system.digestive.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — P<br>• Atomic Number — 15<br>• A highly reactive nonmetal from the 15th group<br>• Essential for all living organisms (DNA, ATP)<br>• Exists in several allotropic forms (white, red, black)<br>• White phosphorus glows in the dark (chemiluminescence)<br>• Never found as a free element in nature<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 15 protons in the nucleus<br>• 15 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 16 neutrons (Phosphorus-31)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ne] 3s² 3p³<br>• Located in the 3rd period and 15th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• White phosphorus: waxy solid, poisonous, flammable<br>• Red phosphorus: amorphous solid, stable, non-toxic<br>• Boiling point — 280.5°C (white)<br>• Melting point — 44.1°C (white)<br>• Poor conductor of heat and electricity<br>• Insoluble in water, but white P dissolves in carbon disulfide<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Spontaneously ignites in air (white phosphorus)<br>• Reacts with halogens to form trihalides and pentahalides<br>• Forms phosphine (PH₃), a highly toxic gas<br>• Forms phosphoric acid (H₃PO₄) when oxides react with water<br>• Common oxidation states — +3, +5, and -3<br><br><b>Phosphorus Isotopes</b><br>• Phosphorus-31 (³¹P) — the only stable natural isotope<br>• Phosphorus-32 (³²P) — radioactive, used as a tracer in biology and medicine<br>• Phosphorus-33 (³³P) — radioactive, used in biochemical research<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in phosphate rocks (e.g., Apatite)<br>• Present in fertile soils and seawater<br>• Major component of bones and teeth in animals<br>• Crucial part of the DNA backbone and energy-carrying ATP<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced by heating phosphate rock with silica and coke in electric furnaces<br>• Red phosphorus is made by heating white phosphorus in an inert atmosphere<br>• Purified through sublimation and distillation<br><br><b>Applications of Phosphorus</b><br>• Agricultural fertilizers (superphosphates)<br>• Safety matches (red phosphorus on the striker)<br>• Steel manufacturing (deoxidizer)<br>• Detergents and water softeners<br>• Pyrotechnics and tracer bullets<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Fundamental for energy transfer in cells (ATP cycle)<br>• Essential for genetic information storage (DNA/RNA)<br>• Critical for bone structural integrity (calcium phosphate)<br>• Important in understanding mineral nutrition and ecology<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Biology — metabolic energy and genetics<br>• Agriculture — global food security via fertilizers<br>• Medicine — bone health and radiopharmaceuticals<br>• Industry — metallurgical and chemical manufacturing",
    "system.endocrine.title": "Sulfur",
    "system.endocrine.desc": "A lemon-yellow nonmetal essential for protein creation and sulfuric acid production.",
    "system.endocrine.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — S<br>• Atomic Number — 16<br>• A bright yellow nonmetal from the 16th group (Chalcogens)<br>• Brittle, odorless, and insoluble in water<br>• Essential for all life, found in amino acids and proteins<br>• Known since ancient times (brimstone)<br>• Forms a wide variety of compounds, including sulfuric acid<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 16 protons in the nucleus<br>• 16 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 16 neutrons (Sulfur-32)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ne] 3s² 3p⁴<br>• Located in the 3rd period and 16th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Solid at room temperature (cyclooctasulfur S₈)<br>• Boiling point — 444.6°C<br>• Melting point — 115.2°C<br>• Poor electrical and thermal conductor<br>• Exists in multiple allotropes (rhombic, monoclinic)<br>• Emits a blue flame when burned<br>• Dissolves in carbon disulfide and benzene<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with oxygen to form sulfur dioxide (SO₂)<br>• Reacts with most metals to form sulfides<br>• Forms sulfuric acid (H₂SO₄), the 'king of chemicals'<br>• Forms hydrogen sulfide (H₂S), which has a rotten egg smell<br>• Common oxidation states — -2, +4, and +6<br><br><b>Sulfur Isotopes</b><br>• Sulfur-32 (³²S) — most abundant stable isotope (95.02%)<br>• Sulfur-33 (³³S) — stable isotope (0.75%)<br>• Sulfur-34 (³⁴S) — stable isotope (4.21%)<br>• Sulfur-36 (³⁶S) — very rare stable isotope (0.02%)<br>• Isotope ratios used to track pollution and biological activity<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in its elemental state near volcanoes and hot springs<br>• Present in minerals like Pyrite (fool's gold) and Gypsum<br>• Found in fossil fuels (coal, oil, natural gas)<br>• Found in essential proteins and vitamins (B1, H)<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Frasch process (pumping superheated water into deposits)<br>• Claus process (recovering sulfur from natural gas and oil)<br>• Byproduct of copper and zinc smelting<br><br><b>Applications of Sulfur</b><br>• Production of sulfuric acid (fertilizers, batteries)<br>• Vulcanization of rubber (tires, elastic materials)<br>• Gunpowder and fireworks manufacturing<br>• Fungicides and pesticides for agriculture<br>• Bleaching agent for paper and textiles<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential component of amino acids (cysteine and methionine)<br>• Forms disulfide bridges that stabilize protein structures (hair, nails)<br>• Fundamental in the study of geochemical cycles<br>• Critical for heavy chemical industrial development<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Biology — protein structure and enzyme function<br>• Agriculture — crop protection and soil pH adjustment<br>• Industry — rubber, paper, and battery production<br>• Environment — study of acid rain and air quality",
    "system.immune.title": "Oxygen",
    "system.immune.desc": "Oxygen is element #8, a life-sustaining gas essential for aerobic respiration and combustion.",
    "system.urinary.title": "Fluorine",
    "system.urinary.desc": "Fluorine is element #9, a versatile halogen essential for various industrial and biological processes.",
    "system.skeletal.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ca<br>• Atomic Number — 20<br>• An alkaline earth metal from the 2nd group<br>• Essential mineral for all living organisms, especially for bones and teeth<br>• Silvery metal that tarnishes rapidly in air<br>• 5th most abundant element in the Earth's crust<br>• Key component in structural materials like cement and lime<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 20 protons in the nucleus<br>• 20 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 20 neutrons (Calcium-40)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 4s²<br>• Located in the 4th period and 2nd group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Soft metal (harder than lead, can be cut with difficulty)<br>• Boiling point — 1484°C<br>• Melting point — 842°C<br>• Relatively low density compared to other metals<br>• Silvery-white appearance when pure<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Forms an orange-red flame during a flame test<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with water to release hydrogen gas and form calcium hydroxide<br>• Less reactive than alkali metals but more reactive than magnesium<br>• Reacts with oxygen to form calcium oxide (CaO), also known as quicklime<br>• Forms ionic bonds with non-metals (e.g., CaCl₂, CaCO₃)<br>• Strong reducing agent used in metallurgical processes<br>• Common oxidation state — +2<br><br><b>Calcium Isotopes</b><br>• Calcium-40 (⁴⁰Ca) — most abundant stable isotope (96.9%)<br>• Calcium-44 (⁴⁴Ca) — stable isotope (2.1%)<br>• Calcium-48 (⁴⁸Ca) — very rare, nearly stable isotope<br>• Isotope analysis used to study nutritional cycles and medical diagnostics<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in massive deposits of Limestone, Chalk, and Marble (CaCO₃)<br>• Present in minerals like Gypsum, Fluorite, and Apatite<br>• Abundant in seawater as dissolved calcium salts<br>• Never found free in nature due to high reactivity<br>• Essential component of shells, skeletons, and corals<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Electrolysis of molten calcium chloride (CaCl₂)<br>• Thermal reduction of lime with aluminum in a vacuum<br>• Obtained from natural minerals via chemical processing and refining<br><br><b>Applications of Calcium</b><br>• Construction industry: cement, mortar, and concrete<br>• Steelmaking: removing impurities (deoxidizer and desulfurizer)<br>• Production of paper, glass, and plastics as a filler<br>• Food industry: calcium fortification and additives<br>• Agriculture: soil treatment (lime) to adjust pH<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Primary structural component of bones and teeth (hydroxyapatite)<br>• Essential for blood clotting and muscle contraction<br>• Acts as a secondary messenger in cellular signaling pathways<br>• Fundamental in the study of mineralization and skeletal health<br>• Critical for the carbon cycle (formation of marine carbonates)<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Biology — skeletal structure and cell signaling<br>• Medicine — bone health supplements and diagnostics<br>• Construction — foundational building materials<br>• Geology — formation of sedimentary rocks and fossils<br>• Industry — metallurgical and chemical processing",
    "system.circulatory.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Fe<br>• Atomic Number — 26<br>• A lustrous, silvery-grey transition metal<br>• Most common element on Earth by mass (forming the core)<br>• Backbone of modern civilization and infrastructure<br>• Essential for oxygen transport in blood (hemoglobin)<br>• Ferromagnetic at room temperature<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 26 protons in the nucleus<br>• 26 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 30 neutrons (Iron-56)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d⁶ 4s²<br>• Located in the 4th period and 8th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Dense, strong, and malleable<br>• Boiling point — 2862°C<br>• Melting point — 1538°C<br>• High thermal and electrical conductivity<br>• Lustrous appearance that rusts (oxidizes) easily in moist air<br>• Forms alloys like steel with carbon and other metals<br>• Highest binding energy per nucleon (most stable nucleus)<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with oxygen and water to form iron oxides (rust)<br>• Dissolves easily in dilute acids<br>• Displays multiple oxidation states, primarily +2 and +3<br>• Acts as a catalyst in many industrial chemical reactions<br>• Forms stable complex compounds (e.g., ferrocene)<br>• Common oxidation states — +2, +3, +4, and +6<br><br><b>Iron Isotopes</b><br>• Iron-56 (⁵⁶Fe) — most abundant stable isotope (91.75%)<br>• Iron-54 (⁵⁴Fe) — stable isotope (5.85%)<br>• Iron-57 (⁵⁷Fe) — stable isotope (2.12%)<br>• Iron-58 (⁵⁸Fe) — stable isotope (0.28%)<br>• Isotope ratios used in studies of meteorite origins and planetary science<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in minerals like Hematite (Fe₂O₃) and Magnetite<br>• Makes up a large part of the Earth's inner and outer core<br>• Abundant in the Universe, formed in large stars before supernovae<br>• Essential component of many proteins and enzymes in life<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Reduction of iron ores with coke in blast furnaces<br>• Direct reduction processes for sponge iron<br>• Refined into various grades of steel via oxygen and electric arc furnaces<br><br><b>Applications of Iron</b><br>• Construction: bridges, skyscrapers, and reinforced concrete<br>• Transportation: ships, cars, trains, and heavy machinery<br>• Tools, cookware, and industrial equipment<br>• Magnetic materials and electromagnetic cores<br>• Steel manufacturing (iron-carbon alloys)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Critical for oxygen transport in mammals (hemoglobin/myoglobin)<br>• Vital for electron transfer in metabolic processes (cytochromes)<br>• Fundamental in understanding the Earth's magnetic field (geodynamo)<br>• Important in the study of nucleosynthesis in astrophysics<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Biology — respiration and metabolism<br>• Engineering — structural integrity and machinery design<br>• Geology — study of the Earth's interior and core<br>• Medicine — treatment of anemia and iron supplements",
    "system.reproductive.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Zn<br>• Atomic Number — 30<br>• A bluish-white, lustrous, and diamagnetic transition metal<br>• Primary use is for galvanizing (protecting iron and steel from rust)<br>• Essential trace mineral for human health and biological growth<br>• Known as 'philosopher's wool' when burned in air<br>• Brittle at room temperature but becomes malleable when heated<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 30 protons in the nucleus<br>• 30 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 34 neutrons (Zinc-64)<br>• Electron configuration — [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s² (fully filled d-shell stability)<br>• Located in the 4th period and 12th group<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Bluish-white metallic appearance<br>• Boiling point — 907°C<br>• Melting point — 419.5°C<br>• Relatively low melting point for a transition metal<br>• Good electrical conductivity<br>• Moderately hard material (2.5 on Mohs scale)<br>• Expands on heating and contracts on cooling<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with oxygen in air to form a protective carbonate layer<br>• Dissolves in both acids and strong alkalis (amphoteric behavior)<br>• Burns in air with a bright bluish-green flame<br>• Powerful reducing agent in chemical synthesis<br>• Forms a wide range of ionic and coordination compounds<br>• Common oxidation state — +2<br><br><b>Zinc Isotopes</b><br>• Zinc-64 (⁶⁴Zn) — most abundant stable isotope (49.17%)<br>• Zinc-66 (⁶⁶Zn) — stable isotope (27.73%)<br>• Zinc-67 (⁶⁷Zn) — stable isotope (4.04%)<br>• Zinc-68 (⁶⁸Zn) — stable isotope (18.45%)<br>• Zinc-70 (⁷⁰Zn) — stable isotope (0.61%)<br>• Artificial isotopes used in biomedical research and tracing<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found in minerals like Sphalerite (zinc sulfide) and Smithsonite<br>• Present in the Earth's crust at about 70 ppm<br>• 24th most abundant element in the crust<br>• Essential component of over 300 enzymes in the human body<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Froth flotation of ores followed by roasting and smelting<br>• Electrolytic process for producing high-purity zinc (SHG grade)<br>• Widely recycled globally (about 30% of supply comes from scrap)<br><br><b>Applications of Zinc</b><br>• Galvanization of steel (approx. 50% of global usage)<br>• Die-casting for automotive and hardware components<br>• Production of Brass (copper-zinc alloy)<br>• Zinc oxide used in rubber, paints, and sunscreens<br>• Batteries: alkaline, zinc-carbon, and zinc-air chemistry<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Critical for DNA synthesis and cell division<br>• Essential for the immune system and wound healing<br>• Key material for electrochemical research and corrosion science<br>• Important for the study of metalloenzymes (e.g., Carbonic Anhydrase)<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — immune health and dermatology (zinc ointments)<br>• Construction — corrosion-resistant structures and roofing<br>• Industry — die-casting and metallurgical manufacturing<br>• Agriculture — essential micronutrient for crop yield and quality",
    "system.promethium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Pm<br>• Atomic Number — 61<br>• Radioactive rare earth metal, first element with no stable isotopes<br>• One of only two elements lighter than Bismuth with no stable form<br>• Extremely rare on Earth; mostly produced in nuclear reactors<br>• Named after Prometheus, who stole fire from the gods<br>• Discovered in 1945 at Oak Ridge National Laboratory<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 61 protons in the nucleus<br>• 61 electrons surrounding the nucleus<br>• No stable natural isotopes; Promethium-145 is the most stable<br>• Electron Configuration — [Xe] 4f⁵ 6s²<br>• Located in Period 6 (Lanthanides)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Metallic appearance; suspected to be silvery-white<br>• Boiling Point — approx. 3000°C<br>• Melting Point — 1042°C<br>• Glows with a pale blue or greenish light due to radioactivity<br>• Emits beta particles (electrons) during radioactive decay<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity like other lanthanides<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Chemically similar to Neodymium and Samarium<br>• Reacts with oxygen to form Pm₂O₃<br>• Dissolves in acids to form pink or rose-colored salts<br>• Radioactivity causes chemical compounds to slowly decompose over time<br>• Typical oxidation state — +3<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced as a byproduct of uranium fission in nuclear reactors<br>• Separated from other fission products by ion exchange chromatography<br>• Pure metal is obtained by reducing fluoride with lithium<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Energy: Nuclear batteries (atomic cells) for spacecraft and pacemakers<br>• Safety: Luminous paints for watch dials and aircraft instruments<br>• Industry: Thickness gauges (using beta radiation absorption)<br>• Science: Portable X-ray sources and specialized research probes<br>• Technology: Radioisotope thermoelectric generators (RTGs)",
    "system.samarium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Sm<br>• Atomic Number — 62<br>• Hard silvery metal that is relatively stable in air<br>• Used in Sm-Co magnets (resistant to demagnetization at high temps)<br>• Essential for precision-guided weapons and stealth technology<br>• Named after the mineral samarskite, honoring engineer Vasili Samarsky-Bykhovets<br>• First element named after a person<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 62 protons in the nucleus<br>• 62 electrons surrounding the nucleus<br>• 7 natural isotopes; Samarium-152 is the most abundant<br>• Electron Configuration — [Xe] 4f⁶ 6s²<br>• Located in Period 6 (Lanthanides)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Bright silvery appearance; hardness similar to iron<br>• Boiling Point — 1794°C<br>• Melting Point — 1072°C<br>• Highly magnetic susceptibility; permanent magnets in alloys<br>• Oxidizes slowly at room temperature<br>• Lustrous when freshly cut but tarnishes in air<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Very reactive rare earth metal<br>• Reacts with water to form Sm(OH)₃ and H₂<br>• Ignites in air at temperatures above 150°C<br>• Forms trivalent compounds (Sm³⁺) and some divalent ones (Sm²⁺)<br>• Typical oxidation state — +3<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Magnets: Samarium-cobalt magnets for aerospace and high-temp use<br>• Medicine: Samarium-153 Lexidronam for treating bone cancer pain<br>• Optics: Infrared absorbing glass and specialized camera lenses<br>• Nuclear: Control rods in reactors due to high neutron absorption<br>• Electronics: Capacitors and solid-state devices",
    "system.europium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Eu<br>• Atomic Number — 63<br>• Most reactive of all rare earth elements; rapidly oxidizes in air<br>• Essential for phosphors that produce red and blue colors in screens<br>• Used as a security marker in Euro banknotes (glows under UV)<br>• Named after the continent of Europe<br>• Discovered in 1901 by Eugène-Anatole Demarçay<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 63 protons in the nucleus<br>• 63 electrons (highly reactive valence shell)<br>• 2 natural isotopes; Europium-153 is the most common stable one<br>• Electron Configuration — [Xe] 4f⁷ 6s²<br>• Located in Period 6 (Lanthanides)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Soft silvery metal; hardness similar to lead<br>• Boiling Point — 1529°C<br>• Melting Point — 822°C<br>• Most ductile and malleable of the rare earth metals<br>• Density is the lowest of all lanthanides (5.26 g/cm³)<br>• Becomes superconducting at very low temperatures<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Extremely reactive; tarnishes instantly in air<br>• Reacts vigorously with water to form Eu(OH)₂ or Eu(OH)₃<br>• One of the few lanthanides that easily forms divalent (Eu²⁺) compounds<br>• Highly efficient at absorbing neutrons<br>• Typical oxidation states — +2 and +3<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Display Tech: Phosphors for LEDs, smartphone screens, and TVs<br>• Lighting: Fluorescent lamps for better color rendering<br>• Security: Anti-counterfeiting markers in bank notes and passports<br>• Nuclear: Control rods and neutron absorbers in nuclear reactors<br>• Science: Biomolecular probes for medical research",
    "system.gadolinium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Gd<br>• Atomic Number — 64<br>• Silvery-white, malleable rare earth metal<br>• Highest thermal neutron capture cross-section of any element<br>• Vital contrast agent in MRI (Magnetic Resonance Imaging)<br>• Ferromagnetic at temperatures below 20°C (curie point)<br>• Named after chemist Johan Gadolin<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 64 protons in the nucleus<br>• 64 electrons (unique 4f⁷ 5d¹ valence shell)<br>• 6 stable natural isotopes; Gadolinium-158 is common<br>• Electron Configuration — [Xe] 4f⁷ 5d¹ 6s²<br>• Located in Period 6 (Lanthanides)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white lustrous appearance; ductile<br>• Boiling Point — 3273°C<br>• Melting Point — 1313°C<br>• One of the few elements with a Curie point near room temp<br>• Exhibits the magnetocaloric effect (heats up in magnetic field)<br>• Stable in dry air but tarnishes in moist air<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Slowly reacts with water to form Gd(OH)₃<br>• Dissolves easily in dilute mineral acids<br>• Strong paramagnetic behavior at room temperature<br>• Forms trivalent compounds; salts are typically white<br>• Typical oxidation state — +3<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Medicine: MRI contrast agents for diagnosing tumors and brain issues<br>• Tech: Magnetocaloric refrigeration (eco-friendly cooling)<br>• Nuclear: Shielding and control rods in nuclear reactors<br>• Electronics: Gadolinium gallium garnet (GGG) for memory devices<br>• Metallurgy: Improves high-temp resistance of iron and chromium",
    "system.terbium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Tb<br>• Atomic Number — 65<br>• Silvery-gray, soft rare earth metal<br>• Critical component for green phosphors in displays<br>• Key material for Terfenol-D (smart material that changes shape in B-field)<br>• Named after the Swedish village Ytterby<br>• One of four elements named after Ytterby<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 65 protons in the nucleus<br>• 65 electrons surrounding the nucleus<br>• Only one stable natural isotope (Terbium-159)<br>• Electron Configuration — [Xe] 4f⁹ 6s²<br>• Located in Period 6 (Lanthanides)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-gray luster; malleable and soft<br>• Boiling Point — 3230°C<br>• Melting Point — 1356°C<br>• Terbium exhibits the highest 'magnetostriction' of all elements<br>• Fluoresces bright green when excited (photoluminescence)<br>• Relatively stable in air compared to other early lanthanides<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with water to form Tb(OH)₃ and H₂<br>• Dissolves in dilute mineral acids<br>• Forms trivalent (Tb³⁺) and tetravalent (Tb⁴⁺) states<br>• Terbium(III) salts produce a brilliant green fluorescence<br>• Typical oxidation state — +3<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Display Tech: Green phosphor for OLEDs, TVs, and smartphones<br>• Lighting: Low-energy light bulbs (compact fluorescents)<br>• Materials: Terfenol-D for sensors, actuators, and sonar devices<br>• Data: Magneto-optical recording films for high-density storage<br>• Science: Biomolecular probes and medical imaging tracers",
    "system.dysprosium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Dy<br>• Atomic Number — 66<br>• Soft, silvery metal with a high magnetic susceptibility<br>• Essential additive in Neodymium magnets to withstand high temps<br>• Used in specialized halogen lamps for brilliant white light<br>• Name comes from Greek 'dysprositos' meaning hard to get<br>• Discovered in 1886 in Paris<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 66 protons in the nucleus<br>• 66 electrons surrounding the nucleus<br>• 7 stable natural isotopes; Dysprosium-164 is common<br>• Electron Configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁰ 6s²<br>• Located in Period 6 (Lanthanides)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white luster; malleable and ductile<br>• Boiling Point — 2562°C<br>• Melting Point — 1412°C<br>• Paramagnetic at room temp; ferromagnetic at low temps<br>• High magnetic strength; used in data storage devices<br>• Relatively stable in dry air but reacts slowly with moisture<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with water to form Dy(OH)₃ and H₂<br>• Dissolves easily in dilute mineral acids<br>• Forms trivalent compounds; salts are yellow-green or white<br>• High neutron absorption cross-section (used in control rods)<br>• Typical oxidation state — +3<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Energy: High-temp magnets for EV motors and wind turbines<br>• Technology: Hard disk drives and data storage materials<br>• Lighting: Gas-discharge lamps and commercial studio lights<br>• Nuclear: Control rods in nuclear reactors to regulate reactions<br>• Optics: Specialized glass for infrared lasers and detectors",
    "system.holmium.details": "<b>Key Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ho<br>• Atomic Number — 67<br>• Silvery-white rare earth metal with unusual magnetic properties<br>• Has the highest magnetic moment (strength) of any natural element<br>• Used in medical lasers for surgery and kidney stone treatment<br>• Named after Stockholm (Latin 'Holmia')<br>• Discovered in 1878 in Switzerland and Sweden<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 67 protons in the nucleus<br>• 67 electrons surrounding the nucleus<br>• Only one stable natural isotope (Holmium-165)<br>• Electron Configuration — [Xe] 4f¹¹ 6s²<br>• Located in Period 6 (Lanthanides)<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white luster; soft and malleable<br>• Boiling Point — 2700°C<br>• Melting Point — 1472°C<br>• Paramagnetic at room temp; intensely ferromagnetic below -254°C<br>• Can concentrate high-intensity magnetic fields (flux concentrator)<br>• Stable in dry air but oxidizes in moist conditions<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with water to form Ho(OH)₃ and H₂<br>• Dissolves in dilute mineral acids to form yellow-pink salts<br>• Forms trivalent compounds (Ho³⁺)<br>• Oxide (Ho₂O₃) has unusual color-changing properties in different light<br>• Typical oxidation state — +3<br><br><b>Applications</b><br>• Medicine: Holmium-YAG (Ho:YAG) lasers for non-invasive surgery<br>• Magnets: Pole pieces for high-intensity magnetic field generation<br>• Optics: Yellow or pink coloring for cubic zirconia and glass<br>• Nuclear: Control rods and neutron absorbers in nuclear reactors<br>• Science: Research in high-field physics and magnetic materials",
    "system.erbium.details": "<b>Негізгі фактілер</b><br>• Химиялық таңбасы — Er<br>• Атомдық нөмірі — 68<br>• Күміс-ақ, салыстырмалы түрде тұрақты сирек жер металы<br>• Интернет үшін өте маңызды: Эрбиймен легирленген талшықты күшейткіштер (EDFA)<br>• Шыны мен керамикаға әдемі қызғылт түс береді<br>• Швецияның Иттербю ауылының құрметіне аталған<br>• 1843 жылы Карл Густав Мосандер ашқан<br><br><b>Атомдық құрылымы</b><br>• Ядрода 68 протон бар<br>• 68 электрон ядроны айнала қозғалады<br>• 6 тұрақты табиғи изотоп; Эрбий-166 ең жиі кездеседі<br>• Электрондық конфигурациясы — [Xe] 4f¹² 6s²<br>• 6-шы кезеңде орналасқан (лантаноидтар)<br><br><b>Физикалық қасиеттері</b><br>• Күміс-ақ жылтыр; жұмсақ және созылғыш<br>• Қайнау температурасы — 2868°C<br>• Балқу температурасы — 1529°C<br>• Ауада тұрақты және басқа сирек жер элементтеріне қарағанда баяу тотығады<br>• Тұздары мен оксиді (Er₂O₃) қызғылт түсті<br>• Күшті инфрақызыл жұтылу мен сәуле шығару қабілетіне ие<br><br><b>Химиялық қасиеттері</b><br>• Сумен баяу әрекеттесіп, Er(OH)₃ түзеді<br>• Минералды қышқылдарда еріп, қызғылт түсті ерітінділер түзеді<br>• Басқа лантаноидтармен салыстырғанда жоғары электрлік кедергіге ие<br>• Үш валентті тотығу дәрежесі ең көп таралған<br>• Тән тотығу дәрежесі — +3<br><br><b>Қолданылуы</b><br>• Телекоммуникациялар: оптикалық талшықтарға арналған EDFA сигнал күшейткіштері (Жаһандық интернет)<br>• Медицина: теріні қалпына келтіруге және стоматологиялық процедураларға арналған Er:YAG лазерлері<br>• Оптика: инфрақызыл сәулелерді жұтатын шыны және сәнді қызғылт шыны бұйымдары<br>• Ядролық энергетика: ядролық реакторлардағы нейтрондарды жұтатын бақылау өзектері<br>• Зергерлік бұйымдар: жасанды асыл тастарға (текше цирконий) қызғылт түс беру",
    "system.thulium.details": "<b>Негізгі фактілер</b><br>• Химиялық таңбасы — Tm<br>• Атомдық нөмірі — 69<br>• Жер қыртысындағы ең сирек кездесетін табиғи лантаноид<br>• Портативті рентген құрылғылары үшін көз ретінде қолданылады (Тулий-170)<br>• Еуро банкноттарының жасандылықтан қорғайтын көк люминесцентті жолақтарында кездеседі<br>• Скандинавияның ежелгі атауы «Туле» құрметіне аталған<br>• 1879 жылы Пер Теодор Клеве ашқан<br><br><b>Атомдық құрылымы</b><br>• Ядрода 69 протон бар<br>• 69 электрон ядроны айнала қозғалады<br>• Тек бір тұрақты табиғи изотоп (Тулий-169)<br>• Электрондық конфигурациясы — [Xe] 4f¹³ 6s²<br>• 6-шы кезеңде орналасқан (лантаноидтар)<br><br><b>Физикалық қасиеттері</b><br>• Күміс-сұр жылтыр; пышақпен кесуге болатындай жұмсақ<br>• Қайнау температурасы — 1950°C<br>• Балқу температурасы — 1545°C<br>• Бөлме температурасында парамагнитті<br>• Жоғары созылғыштығына байланысты оңай өңделеді және пішінделеді<br>• УК-сәулесі астында ашық көк түспен жарқырайды (кейбір қосылыстарда)<br><br><b>Химиялық қасиеттері</b><br>• Сумен баяу әрекеттеседі; сұйық қышқылдарда ериді<br>• Ауада баяу күңгірттенеді, бірақ құрғақ жағдайда тұрақты<br>• Үш валентті қосылыстар түзеді; тұздары әдетте ақшыл-жасыл түсті<br>• Тулий(III) ионы қозған кезде күшті көк жарық шығарады<br>• Тән тотығу дәрежесі — +3<br><br><b>Қолданылуы</b><br>• Медицина: портативті рентген көздері (Tm-170) және хирургияға арналған тулий лазерлері<br>• Қауіпсіздік: Еуро банкноттарындағы көк люминесцентті сия<br>• Техника: керамикалық магниттік материалдарға (ферриттерге) арналған қоспа<br>• Ғылым: жоғары температуралы асқын өткізгіштер және арнайы зондтар<br>• Өнеркәсіп: арнайы фотосуреттерге арналған доғалық жарықтандыру",
    "system.ytterbium.details": "<b>Негізгі фактілер</b><br>• Химиялық таңбасы — Yb<br>• Атомдық нөмірі — 70<br>• Ашық, күміс-ақ сирек жер металы<br>• Әлемдегі ең тұрақты атомдық сағаттар үшін негіз<br>• Металдарды кесуге және дәнекерлеуге арналған қуатты лазерлерде қолданылады<br>• Швецияның Иттербю ауылының құрметіне аталған<br>• 1878 жылы Жан Шарль Мариньяк ашқан<br><br><b>Атомдық құрылымы</b><br>• Ядрода 70 протон бар<br>• 70 электрон (толық 4f¹⁴ қабығы, тұрақты)<br>• 7 тұрақты изотоп; Иттербий-174 ең жиі кездесетіні<br>• Электрондық конфигурациясы — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 6s²<br>• 6-шы кезеңде орналасқан (лантаноидтар)<br><br><b>Физикалық қасиеттері</b><br>• Ашық күміс жылтыр; жұмсақ және созылғыш<br>• Қайнау температурасы — 1196°C<br>• Балқу температурасы — 824°C<br>• Үш түрлі кристалдық құрылымы бар (аллотропия)<br>• Жоғары қысымда электр өткізгіштігі артады<br>• Бөлме температурасында парамагнитті<br><br><b>Химиялық қасиеттері</b><br>• Ауада баяу күңгірттенеді, қорғаныс оксид қабатын түзеді<br>• Сумен әрекеттесіп, Yb(OH)₃ және H₂ түзеді<br>• Минералды қышқылдарда еріп, түссіз ерітінділер түзеді<br>• +3 (Yb³⁺) және +2 (Yb²⁺) тотығу дәрежелерін көрсетеді<br>• Тән тотығу дәрежесі — +3<br><br><b>Қолданылуы</b><br>• Ғылым: иттербийлік атомдық сағаттар (цезийлік сағаттардан тұрақтырақ)<br>• Өнеркәсіп: болатты кесуге арналған қуатты талшықты лазерлер<br>• Медицина: рентген көзі ретіндегі радиоактивті Иттербий-169<br>• Технология: тот баспайтын болат пен лазерлік кристалдарға арналған қоспа<br>• Зерттеулер: жоғары қысым мен температурадағы материалдардың қасиеттерін зерттеу",
    "system.lutetium.details": "<b>Негізгі фактілер</b><br>• Химиялық таңбасы — Lu<br>• Атомдық нөмірі — 71<br>• Ең ауыр және ең қатты лантаноид<br>• Ядролық медицинада қатерлі ісікті емдеу үшін қолданылады<br>• Табиғаттағы ең сирек және ең қымбат металдардың бірі<br>• Париждің ежелгі атауы «Лютеция» құрметіне аталған<br>• 1907 жылы үш ғалым бір-біріне тәуелсіз ашқан<br><br><b>Атомдық құрылымы</b><br>• Ядрода 71 протон бар<br>• 71 электрон (толық d және f қабықтары)<br>• 2 табиғи изотоп; Лютеций-175 — тұрақты<br>• Электрондық конфигурациясы — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d¹ 6s²<br>• 6-шы кезеңде орналасқан (лантаноидтардың соңғысы)<br><br><b>Физикалық қасиеттері</b><br>• Күміс-ақ металдық жылтыр; коррозияға төзімді<br>• Қайнау температурасы — 3402°C<br>• Балқу температурасы — 1663°C<br>• Барлық лантаноидтардың ішіндегі ең жоғары тығыздық (9.84 г/см³)<br>• Ең жоғары балқу температурасы мен қаттылыққа ие лантаноид<br>• Бөлме температурасында парамагнитті<br><br><b>Химиялық қасиеттері</b><br>• Ауада баяу күңгірттенеді; қышқылдарда ериді<br>• Химиялық белсенділігі басқа лантаноидтардан төменірек<br>• Үш валентті қосылыстар түзеді; тұздары әдетте түссіз<br>• Оның қосылыстары мұнайды крекингілеуде катализатор ретінде қолданылады<br>• Тән тотығу дәрежесі — +3<br><br><b>Қолданылуы</b><br>• Медицина: қатерлі ісік жасушаларын жоюға арналған Лютеций-177 терапиясы<br>• Технология: жарық диодты шамдар мен лазерлік кристалдарға арналған қоспа<br>• Өнеркәсіп: мұнай өңдеудегі катализатор және полимерлеу реакциялары<br>• Ғылым: метеориттердің жасын анықтауға арналған Лютеций-Гафний мерзімдеуі<br>• Оптика: линзалардың сыну көрсеткішін жақсартуға арналған қоспа",
    "system.hafnium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Hf<br>• Atomic Number — 72<br>• A lustrous, silvery-grey transition metal with exceptional corrosion resistance<br>• Named after 'Hafnia', the Latin name for Copenhagen (where it was discovered)<br>• Essential for nuclear reactor control rods and advanced microprocessors<br>• Chemically nearly identical to Zirconium, making it very difficult to separate<br>• Critical for high-temperature superalloys used in jet engines and rockets<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 72 protons in the nucleus<br>• 72 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 108 neutrons (Hafnium-180)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d² 6s²<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 4 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-grey luster; forms a protective oxide layer that resists corrosion<br>• Boiling point — 4603°C (extremely high)<br>• Melting point — 2233°C (very high for a transition metal)<br>• High density (approx. 13.31 g/cm³) and typical metallic conductivity<br>• Ductile and relatively easy to work when pure<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br>• Excellent thermal neutron absorption cross-section<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly resistant to concentrated alkalis and most acids (except hydrofluoric acid)<br>• Reacts with oxygen at high temperatures to form Hafnium(IV) oxide (HfO₂)<br>• Exhibits stable +4 oxidation state (most common)<br>• Forms a range of compounds, including halides and organometallic complexes<br>• Surface oxide layer provides incredible protection against seawater and hot steam<br>• Pyrophoric in finely divided powder form (can ignite spontaneously in air)<br><br><b>Hafnium Isotopes</b><br>• Hafnium has 5 stable natural isotopes (Hf-176, 177, 178, 179, 180)<br>• Hafnium-180 (¹⁸⁰Hf) — most abundant stable isotope (35.08%)<br>• Hafnium-174 (¹⁷⁴Hf) — naturally occurring radioisotope with a very long half-life<br>• Hafnium-182 (¹⁸²Hf) — extinct radionuclide used to date early solar system events<br>• Over 30 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Never found free in nature; always found with Zirconium (ratio approx. 1:50)<br>• Primarily found in minerals like Zircon and Baddeleyite<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 3.0 ppm (relatively common transition metal)<br>• Recovered exclusively as a byproduct of Zirconium refining<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from zirconium ores via complex chemical separation processes<br>• Separated from zirconium using liquid-liquid extraction or distillation<br>• Metal produced by reduction of hafnium tetrachloride with magnesium (Kroll process)<br><br><b>Applications of Hafnium</b><br>• Nuclear Power: control rods for nuclear reactors (high neutron absorption)<br>• Electronics: high-k gate dielectrics (HfO₂) in advanced microprocessors (Intel/AMD)<br>• Aerospace: superalloys for jet engine nozzles and high-temperature nozzles<br>• Plasma Cutting: used as electrode tips in high-performance plasma torches<br>• Metallurgy: added to titanium, niobium, and tantalum to increase heat resistance<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Enabling material for the continued shrinking of transistors in modern computers<br>• Critical for safe and efficient nuclear power and submarine propulsion<br>• Essential for high-performance flight in extreme thermal environments<br>• Vital tool for dating the formation of the Earth's core and early solar system<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Technology — core material for modern CPUs and high-speed electronics<br>• Energy — nuclear reactor safety and advanced turbine efficiency<br>• Aerospace — high-temperature components for rockets and jet engines<br>• Geology — dating the earliest events in planetary history",
    "system.tantalum.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ta<br>• Atomic Number — 73<br>• A hard, dense, blue-grey transition metal with extreme corrosion resistance<br>• Named after 'Tantalus', a figure from Greek mythology (due to its inability to absorb acids)<br>• Essential for high-performance capacitors in smartphones and electronics<br>• Biocompatible: used extensively in medical implants and surgical tools<br>• One of the most chemically inert metals known to science<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 73 protons in the nucleus<br>• 73 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 108 neutrons (Tantalum-181)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d³ 6s²<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 5 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Blue-grey luster; forms a stable, dense oxide layer that prevents further corrosion<br>• Boiling point — 5458°C (extremely high)<br>• Melting point — 3017°C (one of the highest melting points of all metals)<br>• High density (approx. 16.69 g/cm³) and excellent thermal conductivity<br>• Highly ductile and malleable; can be drawn into very thin wires<br>• Superconducting at very low temperatures<br>• Exceptional resistance to chemicals, even at high temperatures<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Completely inert to most acids at room temperature (including aqua regia)<br>• Dissolves only in hydrofluoric acid or hot sulfuric acid/acidic melts<br>• Reacts with oxygen at high temperatures to form Tantalum(V) oxide (Ta₂O₅)<br>• Exhibits stable +5 oxidation state (most common)<br>• Forms a range of interesting organometallic and nitride compounds<br>• Surface oxide layer is highly stable and provides self-healing protection<br><br><b>Tantalum Isotopes</b><br>• Tantalum has 2 natural isotopes: Tantalum-180m and Tantalum-181<br>• Tantalum-181 (¹⁸¹Ta) — only stable isotope (99.988%)<br>• Tantalum-180m (¹⁸⁰ᵐTa) — only naturally occurring nuclear isomer (extremely rare)<br>• Over 35 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• Isotope ratios used to track the chemical evolution of the Earth's crust<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in minerals like Tantalite, Columbite, and Microlite<br>• Always found in association with Niobium (Nb)<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 2.0 ppm (relatively rare element)<br>• Major deposits found in Australia, Brazil, Canada, and Central Africa<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from mineral concentrates via complex chemical processing (acid leaching)<br>• Separated from niobium using liquid-liquid extraction (solvent extraction)<br>• Metal produced by reduction of potassium fluorotantalate with sodium or electrolysis<br><br><b>Applications of Tantalum</b><br>• Electronics: high-performance capacitors for smartphones, computers, and medical devices<br>• Medicine: surgical implants (bone pins, joints), surgical mesh, and instruments<br>• Aerospace: superalloys for jet engine components and high-temperature nozzles<br>• Chemical Industry: lining for reactors, heat exchangers, and pipes handling acids<br>• Optics: high-refractive index glass for camera lenses and precision optics<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Enabling material for the miniaturization of modern mobile electronics<br>• Critical for life-saving medical implants and advanced surgical techniques<br>• Essential for safe handling of extremely corrosive industrial chemicals<br>• Important material for research into superconductivity and high-temp physics<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Technology — miniaturized power storage in mobile devices and gadgets<br>• Medicine — permanent medical implants and advanced surgical tools<br>• Energy — critical for high-efficiency turbines and nuclear research<br>• Industry — corrosion-resistant equipment for chemical manufacturing",
    "system.tungsten.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — W<br>• Atomic Number — 74<br>• A dense, steel-grey transition metal with the highest melting point of all elements<br>• Named 'Tungsten' (Swedish for 'heavy stone') or 'Wolfram' (due to its 'wolf-like' devouring of tin)<br>• Essential for high-speed cutting tools, incandescent filaments, and armor-piercing munitions<br>• Critical for high-temperature superalloys used in aerospace and defense<br>• One of the densest and most heat-resistant materials known to science<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 74 protons in the nucleus<br>• 74 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 110 neutrons (Tungsten-184)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d⁴ 6s²<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 6 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Steel-grey to white appearance; exceptionally hard and dense<br>• Boiling point — 5555°C (one of the highest of all elements)<br>• Melting point — 3422°C (the highest of all non-alloy metals)<br>• High density (approx. 19.25 g/cm³) — comparable to gold<br>• Excellent electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Lowest coefficient of thermal expansion of any pure metal<br>• Highly resistant to most acids and bases at room temperature<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Forms a thin protective oxide layer in air, but oxidizes rapidly above 400°C<br>• Dissolves in a mixture of hydrofluoric and nitric acids<br>• Exhibits multiple oxidation states, with +6 being the most stable (e.g., WO₃)<br>• Forms Tungsten Carbide (WC), an exceptionally hard material<br>• Resistant to attack by hydrogen and nitrogen at high temperatures<br>• Forms complex polyoxometalates used in catalysis<br><br><b>Tungsten Isotopes</b><br>• Tungsten has 5 naturally occurring isotopes (W-180, 182, 183, 184, 186)<br>• Tungsten-184 (¹⁸⁴W) — most abundant stable isotope (30.64%)<br>• Tungsten-180 (¹⁸⁰W) — naturally occurring radioisotope with a vast half-life (1.8 quintillion years)<br>• Over 30 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• Isotope ratios used to date the separation of the Earth's mantle and core<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in minerals like Wolframite and Scheelite<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 1.25 ppm (relatively rare transition metal)<br>• Never found free in nature; major deposits in China, Russia, and Canada<br>• Essential component in certain deep-earth mineral structures<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from mineral concentrates via alkaline leaching or roasting<br>• Purified into Ammonium Paratungstate (APT), then converted to Tungsten Trioxide (WO₃)<br>• Metal powder produced by hydrogen reduction of WO₃ at high temperature<br><br><b>Applications of Tungsten</b><br>• Tool Industry: Tungsten Carbide (WC) for high-speed drills, saws, and milling cutters<br>• Aerospace: jet engine components, heat sinks, and ballast weights<br>• Defense: armor-piercing penetrators (kinetic energy penetrators)<br>• Lighting: filaments for incandescent bulbs (historical) and specialized lamps<br>• Electronics: heat sinks, electrical contacts, and specialized vacuum tubes<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Enabling material for modern high-precision machining and manufacturing<br>• Critical for advanced aerospace flight and defense technology<br>• Essential for extreme high-temperature scientific and industrial research<br>• Vital tool for understanding the early separation of planetary cores<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Industry — high-speed cutting tools and heavy-duty manufacturing<br>• Aerospace — heat-resistant components for jet engines and rockets<br>• Defense — advanced ballistics and armor-piercing technology<br>• Technology — high-temperature electronics and specialized lighting",
    "system.rhenium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Re<br>• Atomic Number — 75<br>• One of the rarest and densest elements in the Earth's crust<br>• Named after the river Rhine ('Rhenus' in Latin)<br>• Critical for high-temperature superalloys used in jet engine turbines<br>• Possesses the third-highest melting point of any element (after C and W)<br>• Exceptional catalyst for lead-free high-octane gasoline production<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 75 protons in the nucleus<br>• 75 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 112 neutrons (Rhenium-187)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d⁵ 6s²<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 7 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white, lustrous appearance; extremely dense (approx. 21.02 g/cm³)<br>• Boiling point — 5596°C (one of the highest of all elements)<br>• Melting point — 3186°C (exceptionally high)<br>• Highly resistant to corrosion and wear; remains stable at extreme temperatures<br>• Ductile and malleable after annealing; high electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br>• High elastic modulus (stiff material)<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Resistant to corrosion by most acids, but dissolves in nitric and sulfuric acids<br>• Exhibits a wide range of oxidation states from -1 to +7 (+7 is most stable)<br>• Reacts with oxygen at high temperatures to form Rhenium(VII) oxide (Re₂O₇)<br>• Forms complex organometallic compounds and stable halides<br>• Exceptional catalytic properties for hydrogenation and reforming reactions<br>• Forms Rhenium Diboride (ReB₂), an ultra-hard material comparable to diamond<br><br><b>Rhenium Isotopes</b><br>• Rhenium has 2 natural isotopes: Rhenium-185 and Rhenium-187<br>• Rhenium-185 (¹⁸⁵Re) — stable isotope (37.4%)<br>• Rhenium-187 (¹⁸⁷Re) — long-lived natural radioisotope used in Re-Os dating<br>• Over 30 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• Isotope ratios used to date the formation of the Earth's core and asteroids<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Extremely rare; 77th most abundant element in the Earth's crust (approx. 0.7 ppb)<br>• Never found free in nature; occurs primarily as a trace element in Molybdenite ores<br>• Estimated total Earth's crust abundance is very low<br>• Major producers include Chile, Kazakhstan, and the United States<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered as a byproduct of molybdenum and copper mining/roasting<br>• Extracted from flue gases of molybdenum roasters as Perhenic acid (HReO₄)<br>• Metal produced by hydrogen reduction of ammonium perrhenate at high temp<br><br><b>Applications of Rhenium</b><br>• Aerospace: nickel-based superalloys for jet engine turbine blades (70% of use)<br>• Petroleum Industry: Pt-Re catalysts for reforming naphtha into high-octane gasoline<br>• Electronics: filaments for mass spectrometers, thermocouples, and flash bulbs<br>• Medicine: radioactive isotopes used for specialized cancer treatments<br>• Metallurgy: added to tungsten and molybdenum alloys to increase ductility<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Enabling material for modern high-efficiency jet engines and air travel<br>• Critical for the sustainable production of high-performance transportation fuels<br>• Essential tool for precision dating of planetary and geological processes<br>• Fundamental for research into ultra-hard materials and high-temp chemistry<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Aerospace — high-performance turbine technology for aviation<br>• Energy — critical for high-octane fuel production and nuclear research<br>• Geology — dating the formation of the solar system and Earth's core<br>• Medicine — specialized radiopharmaceuticals and diagnostics",
    "system.osmium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Os<br>• Atomic Number — 76<br>• The densest naturally occurring element on Earth<br>• Named after the Greek word 'osme' (smell) due to the sharp odor of its tetroxide<br>• Hard, brittle, bluish-white transition metal in the platinum group<br>• Remains lustrous even at high temperatures<br>• Critical for specialized high-wear applications and chemical catalysis<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 76 protons in the nucleus<br>• 76 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 116 neutrons (Osmium-192)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d⁶ 6s²<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 8 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Bluish-white luster; exceptionally dense (approx. 22.59 g/cm³)<br>• Boiling point — 5012°C (very high)<br>• Melting point — 3033°C (high for a transition metal)<br>• Hardest of the platinum-group metals; extremely brittle and difficult to work<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br>• Exceptional resistance to compression (low compressibility)<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly resistant to most acids, including aqua regia at room temperature<br>• Reacts with oxygen at moderate temperatures to form volatile Osmium tetroxide (OsO₄)<br>• Osmium tetroxide is highly toxic and has a strong, penetrating odor<br>• Exhibits multiple oxidation states from -2 to +8 (+4 and +8 are common)<br>• Forms complex organometallic compounds used in advanced synthesis<br>• Surface oxide layer provides some protection, but it can be bypassed at high temp<br><br><b>Osmium Isotopes</b><br>• Osmium has 7 natural isotopes: Os-184, 186, 187, 188, 189, 190, 192<br>• Osmium-192 (¹⁹²Os) — most abundant stable isotope (41.0%)<br>• Osmium-186 (¹⁸⁶Os) — naturally occurring radioisotope with a very long half-life<br>• Osmium-187 (¹⁸⁷Os) — daughter product of Rhenium-187 (used in Re-Os dating)<br>• Over 30 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in platinum-group metal (PGM) ores and nickel-copper deposits<br>• Occurs as native alloys like Osmiridium and Iridosmium<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 0.0015 ppm (one of the rarest elements)<br>• Major producers include South Africa, Russia, and Canada<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered as a byproduct of nickel and platinum refining<br>• Extracted via complex chemical processes involving distillation of OsO₄<br>• Purified into metal powder by reduction with hydrogen at high temperature<br><br><b>Applications of Osmium</b><br>• Metallurgy: added to platinum and iridium to create exceptionally hard alloys<br>• Writing Instruments: used for high-end fountain pen nibs (historical and luxury)<br>• Electronics: used in specialized electrical contacts and high-wear pivots<br>• Chemical Industry: catalysts for hydrogenation and specialized organic reactions<br>• Medicine: used in specialized microscopy stains and forensic fingerprinting (as OsO₄)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Standard for extreme density and hardness in materials science<br>• Critical tool for geological dating and understanding planetary formation<br>• Essential for high-precision mechanical components in extreme environments<br>• Important material for research into high-oxidation-state chemistry<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Industry — exceptionally hard alloys and high-precision components<br>• Geology — dating the formation of the Earth's crust and meteorites<br>• Science — advanced chemical synthesis and specialized microscopy<br>• Luxury Goods — premium nibs for writing instruments and durable coatings",
    "system.iridium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ir<br>• Atomic Number — 77<br>• The most corrosion-resistant material known to man<br>• Named after the Greek goddess 'Iris' (rainbow) due to the vibrant colors of its salts<br>• Very hard, brittle, silvery-white transition metal in the platinum group<br>• Famous for the 'Iridium Anomaly' (evidence of the asteroid that killed the dinosaurs)<br>• Critical for high-temperature crucibles and specialized aerospace components<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 77 protons in the nucleus<br>• 77 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 116 neutrons (Iridium-193)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d⁷ 6s²<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 9 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white, bright luster; exceptionally dense (approx. 22.56 g/cm³)<br>• Boiling point — 4428°C (very high)<br>• Melting point — 2446°C (extremely high)<br>• Second-densest element (slightly less than osmium, though results vary)<br>• Most corrosion-resistant metal: resists almost all acids even at high temp<br>• Brittle and extremely difficult to machine or work<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Unaffected by any acid, including aqua regia, at room temperature<br>• Dissolves only in molten salts or specialized alkaline mixtures<br>• Reacts with oxygen at high temperatures to form Iridium(IV) oxide (IrO₂)<br>• Exhibits multiple oxidation states from -3 to +9 (+3 and +4 are most common)<br>• Forms a wide range of colorful complex salts (red, yellow, blue, green)<br>• Exceptional catalytic properties for industrial chemical reactions<br><br><b>Iridium Isotopes</b><br>• Iridium has 2 stable natural isotopes: Iridium-191 and Iridium-193<br>• Iridium-193 (¹⁹³Ir) — most abundant stable isotope (62.7%)<br>• Iridium-192 (¹⁹²Ir) — powerful radioisotope used in industrial radiography and cancer therapy<br>• Over 35 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• Isotope ratios used to identify extraterrestrial impacts in geological layers<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• One of the rarest elements in the Earth's crust (approx. 0.001 ppm)<br>• Found primarily in native alloys with osmium and platinum<br>• Highly concentrated in iron meteorites compared to the Earth's crust<br>• Global 'Iridium Layer' marks the boundary of the Mesozoic and Cenozoic eras<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered as a byproduct of nickel and copper mining and platinum refining<br>• Extracted via complex chemical processing involving leaching and solvent extraction<br>• Metal produced by reduction of ammonium hexachloroiridate with hydrogen<br><br><b>Applications of Iridium</b><br>• High-Temperature Crucibles: used to grow high-quality single crystals (lasers, electronics)<br>• Spark Plugs: high-end automotive spark plugs for extreme longevity and performance<br>• Medicine: Ir-192 for brachytherapy (targeted radiation treatment for cancer)<br>• Aerospace: jet engine components and rocket nozzles capable of resisting extreme heat<br>• Chemistry: core catalyst for carbonylation and other industrial processes<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Definitive marker for the K-Pg extinction event (the end of the dinosaurs)<br>• Enabling material for high-performance combustion and flight systems<br>• Critical tool for advanced cancer treatment and industrial safety testing<br>• Fundamental for the synthesis of advanced optical and electronic materials<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Paleontology — evidence for mass extinction events and asteroid impacts<br>• Aerospace — high-performance components for extreme thermal environments<br>• Medicine — precise internal radiation therapy for cancer patients<br>• Technology — high-end electronics and industrial crystal growth",
    "system.platinum.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Pt<br>• Atomic Number — 78<br>• A dense, malleable, ductile, and highly unreactive noble metal<br>• Named after the Spanish 'platina' (little silver)<br>• Critical for automotive catalytic converters to reduce pollution<br>• Famous for use in high-end jewelry and investment coins<br>• Essential for medical chemotherapy drugs (Cisplatin)<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 78 protons in the nucleus<br>• 78 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 117 neutrons (Platinum-195)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d⁹ 6s¹ (unusual d-shell configuration)<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 10 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Lustrous silvery-white appearance; exceptionally dense (approx. 21.45 g/cm³)<br>• Boiling point — 3825°C<br>• Melting point — 1768°C (relatively high for a precious metal)<br>• Highly malleable and ductile; can be drawn into very fine wire<br>• Does not oxidize or tarnish in air even at high temperatures<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Extremely resistant to corrosion and most acids; dissolves in aqua regia<br>• Reacts with halogens and sulfur at high temperatures<br>• Exhibits stable +2 and +4 oxidation states (most common)<br>• One of the most effective catalysts known for chemical reactions<br>• Forms stable organometallic complexes (e.g., Zeise's salt)<br>• Absorbs large volumes of hydrogen gas onto its surface (catalytic property)<br><br><b>Platinum Isotopes</b><br>• Platinum has 5 stable natural isotopes: Pt-192, 194, 195, 196, 198<br>• Platinum-195 (¹⁹⁵Pt) — most abundant stable isotope (33.78%)<br>• Platinum-190 (¹⁹⁰Pt) — naturally occurring radioisotope with a vast half-life<br>• Over 30 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• Isotope ratios used to track pollution and geological processes<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Often found in native form, frequently alloyed with other PGMs<br>• Found primarily in copper and nickel ores and alluvial deposits<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 0.005 ppm (extremely rare)<br>• Major deposits in South Africa (Bushveld Complex), Russia, and Zimbabwe<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted as a primary product or byproduct of nickel and copper mining<br>• Refined via complex chemical processing involving leaching and precipitation<br>• Pure metal produced by heating ammonium hexachloroplatinate in air<br><br><b>Applications of Platinum</b><br>• Catalytic Converters: reduces toxic exhaust emissions in vehicles (largest use)<br>• Jewelry: prized for its purity, luster, and resistance to wear and tarnish<br>• Medicine: Cisplatin and Carboplatin drugs used to treat various cancers<br>• Industry: high-temperature crucibles, electrical contacts, and glass manufacturing<br>• Electronics: hard disk coatings, sensors, and specialized thermocouples<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Crucial tool for environmental protection through emission control<br>• Life-saving material for modern cancer chemotherapy treatments<br>• Standard material for precision measurement (e.g., standard meter bar/kg)<br>• Fundamental for the development of modern catalytic chemistry<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Environment — critical for reducing air pollution from transportation<br>• Medicine — essential for cancer treatment and permanent implants<br>• Finance — globally recognized investment asset and store of value<br>• Technology — high-end electronics and industrial manufacturing",
    "system.gold.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Au<br>• Atomic Number — 79<br>• The most malleable and ductile of all known metals<br>• Named after the Old English word for yellow; symbol 'Au' from Latin 'Aurum' (shining dawn)<br>• Historically the primary global monetary standard and store of value<br>• Famous for its brilliant yellow luster and resistance to tarnish<br>• Essential for corrosion-resistant coatings in modern electronics<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 79 protons in the nucleus<br>• 79 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 118 neutrons (Gold-197)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d¹⁰ 6s¹ (filled d-shell stability)<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 11 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Vibrant yellow luster; exceptionally dense (approx. 19.30 g/cm³)<br>• Boiling point — 2856°C<br>• Melting point — 1064°C (typical for a precious metal)<br>• Most malleable metal: can be beaten into transparent sheets only 100 nm thick<br>• Most ductile metal: 1 gram can be drawn into a wire 2.4 kilometers long<br>• Excellent conductor of electricity and heat<br>• Reflects infrared radiation highly effectively (used in space tech)<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Least reactive of all metals; does not oxidize in air or water<br>• Dissolves only in aqua regia (mixture of nitric and hydrochloric acids)<br>• Exhibits stable +1 and +3 oxidation states (+3 is more common)<br>• Forms stable complexes with cyanides and various organic ligands<br>• Resistant to attack by most individual acids and alkalis<br>• Surface atoms can form strong bonds with sulfur (thiol chemistry)<br><br><b>Gold Isotopes</b><br>• Gold-197 (¹⁹⁷Au) — the only stable natural isotope (100% abundance)<br>• Gold-198 (¹⁹⁸Au) — radioactive, used in medical treatment for specialized cancers<br>• Over 35 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• Isotope ratios in rocks used to track the history of the Earth's crust and core<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Often found in native (pure) form in quartz veins and alluvial (placer) deposits<br>• Frequently found alloyed with silver (Electrum) or other metals<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 0.004 ppm (very rare element)<br>• Found in trace amounts in seawater (too dilute to extract economically)<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered via mining (shaft mining or open-pit) and panning<br>• Extracted from ores using cyanidation (dissolving gold in cyanide solution)<br>• Refined via electrolysis (Wohlwill process) or chemical precipitation<br><br><b>Applications of Gold</b><br>• Finance: monetary reserves, investment bars, and coinage<br>• Jewelry: prized for its beauty, rarity, and resistance to corrosion and skin reaction<br>• Electronics: corrosion-free connectors, switch contacts, and bonding wires<br>• Aerospace: infrared shielding on satellites and visors for astronauts<br>• Medicine: dental alloys, specialized arthritis drugs, and cancer diagnostics<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Historically the foundation of global economics and human civilization<br>• Essential for the long-term reliability of modern digital technology<br>• Critical tool for high-end optical and space exploration research<br>• Fundamental for the study of surface chemistry and nanotechnology<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Finance — ultimate global store of value and economic hedge<br>• Technology — reliable connectivity in computers and smartphones<br>• Aerospace — protection against solar radiation in space<br>• History — driver of exploration, trade, and cultural development",
    "system.mercury.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Hg<br>• Atomic Number — 80<br>• The only metal that is liquid at standard temperature and pressure<br>• Named after the Roman messenger god; symbol 'Hg' from Greek 'Hydrargyrum' (liquid silver)<br>• Famous for its historical use in thermometers, barometers, and alchemical research<br>• Forms 'amalgams' (liquid alloys) with many other metals like gold and silver<br>• Highly toxic: poses a significant environmental and health risk if not handled correctly<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 80 protons in the nucleus<br>• 80 electrons around the nucleus (stable closed shell configuration)<br>• Most common stable isotope has 122 neutrons (Mercury-202)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d¹⁰ 6s² (completely filled subshells)<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 12 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white luster; liquid state at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — 356.7°C (low for a metal)<br>• Melting point — -38.8°C (the lowest of all stable metals)<br>• High density (approx. 13.53 g/cm³) and high surface tension<br>• Fair conductor of electricity; poor conductor of heat<br>• Vaporizes easily at room temperature (mercury vapor is invisible and toxic)<br>• Diamagnetic at room temperature<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Relatively unreactive; does not oxidize in air at room temperature<br>• Reacts with sulfur at room temperature (used to clean up spills)<br>• Dissolves in oxidizing acids like nitric and concentrated sulfuric acid<br>• Exhibits stable +1 (as Hg₂²⁺) and +2 oxidation states<br>• Forms stable organometallic compounds like Methylmercury (highly neurotoxic)<br>• Does not react with most individual alkalis or dilute non-oxidizing acids<br><br><b>Mercury Isotopes</b><br>• Mercury has 7 stable natural isotopes: Hg-196, 198, 199, 200, 201, 202, 204<br>• Mercury-202 (²⁰²Hg) — most abundant stable isotope (29.86%)<br>• Mercury-197 (¹⁹⁷Hg) — radioactive, used in specialized medical research and tracing<br>• Over 30 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• Isotope ratios used to track the source and movement of mercury in the environment<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Primarily found in the mineral Cinnabar (Mercury sulfide, HgS)<br>• Occasionally found as native (liquid) mercury in small droplets in rocks<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 0.08 ppm (relatively rare element)<br>• Major producers include China, Kyrgyzstan, and Spain (Almadén mines)<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted by roasting Cinnabar in a furnace to release mercury vapor<br>• Mercury vapor is then condensed and purified via filtration or distillation<br>• Can be recovered from industrial waste and specialized batteries<br><br><b>Applications of Mercury</b><br>• Scientific Instruments: barometers, manometers, and specialized switches (historical)<br>• Lighting: high-pressure mercury vapor lamps and fluorescent tubes<br>• Chemical Industry: historical use as a cathode in chlor-alkali production<br>• Mining: used in artisanal gold mining to extract gold via amalgamation<br>• Medicine: historical use in dental amalgams and specialized preservatives (Thimerosal)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Historically crucial for the development of modern thermodynamics and chemistry<br>• Significant environmental priority due to bioaccumulation in the food chain<br>• Vital tool for research into low-temperature physics and superconductivity<br>• Key material for specialized high-intensity lighting and industrial sensors<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Environment — global efforts to reduce mercury pollution (Minamata Convention)<br>• Medicine — neurotoxicology and historical dental restorations<br>• Physics — study of fluid dynamics and early superconductivity research<br>• Industry — high-intensity lighting and specialized electronics",
    "system.thallium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Tl<br>• Atomic Number — 81<br>• A soft, malleable, silvery-grey post-transition metal<br>• Named after the Greek word 'thallos' (green shoot) due to its bright green spectral line<br>• Highly toxic: once used extensively as a rodenticide and ant killer<br>• Critical for specialized high-refractive index glass and IR sensors<br>• Tarnishes quickly in air, resembling lead in appearance<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 81 protons in the nucleus<br>• 81 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 124 neutrons (Thallium-205)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d¹⁰ 6s² 6p¹<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 13 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white luster when fresh; turns bluish-grey upon exposure to air<br>• Boiling point — 1473°C<br>• Melting point — 304°C (relatively low for a metal)<br>• High density (approx. 11.85 g/cm³) and typical metallic conductivity<br>• Extremely soft: can be cut with a knife at room temperature<br>• Diamagnetic at room temperature<br>• High electrical resistance compared to most other metals<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with oxygen and moisture to form Thallium(I) oxide and hydroxide<br>• Exhibits stable +1 and +3 oxidation states (+1 is more stable/common)<br>• Dissolves easily in nitric and sulfuric acids; slow reaction with hydrochloric acid<br>• Forms stable halides and specialized organometallic compounds<br>• Thallium(I) compounds behave similarly to alkali metals (K, Rb)<br>• Thallium(III) compounds are strong oxidizing agents and behave like Al or Ga<br><br><b>Thallium Isotopes</b><br>• Thallium has 2 stable natural isotopes: Thallium-203 and Thallium-205<br>• Thallium-205 (²⁰⁵Tl) — most abundant stable isotope (70.48%)<br>• Thallium-201 (²⁰¹Tl) — radioactive, used in medical heart stress tests (scintigraphy)<br>• Over 35 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• Isotope ratios used to track industrial pollution in environmental studies<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in trace amounts in sulfide ores of zinc, lead, and copper<br>• Occasionally found in minerals like Crookesite and Lorándite<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 0.7 ppm (relatively rare element)<br>• Never found free in nature; recovered as a byproduct of smelting other metals<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered from flue dusts during the smelting of zinc and lead ores<br>• Purified via leaching with sulfuric acid and subsequent precipitation<br>• Metal produced by electrolysis of thallium sulfate or reduction with zinc/sodium<br><br><b>Applications of Thallium</b><br>• Optics: high-refractive index glass for camera lenses and fiber optics<br>• Electronics: specialized infrared (IR) detectors and gamma radiation sensors<br>• Medicine: Thallium-201 used as a radioactive tracer for cardiac imaging<br>• Research: used in high-temperature superconductivity studies<br>• Industry: specialized low-melting alloys and mercury-thallium thermometers<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Historically significant (and notorious) as a potent, odorless poison<br>• Crucial tool for non-invasive diagnostic cardiac medical imaging<br>• Essential material for advanced optical systems and photonics<br>• Important for understanding the behavior of heavy post-transition metals<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — diagnostic heart imaging and nuclear medicine<br>• Technology — specialized sensors for night vision and radiation detection<br>• Environmental Science — monitoring toxic heavy metal contamination<br>• Chemistry — study of 'inert pair effect' in heavy elements",
    "system.lead.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Pb<br>• Atomic Number — 82<br>• A dense, soft, malleable, and corrosion-resistant post-transition metal<br>• Named after the Latin 'Plumbum' (hence the symbol Pb and word 'plumbing')<br>• Historically significant: used by Romans for pipes and water systems<br>• Critical for radiation shielding and lead-acid batteries (vehicle starters)<br>• Highly toxic: accumulates in the body and affects the nervous system<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 82 protons in the nucleus (a 'magic number' of protons for stability)<br>• 82 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 126 neutrons (Lead-208 — doubly magic)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d¹⁰ 6s² 6p²<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 14 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Bluish-white luster when fresh; turns dull grey upon exposure to air<br>• Boiling point — 1749°C<br>• Melting point — 327.5°C (relatively low for a metal)<br>• High density (approx. 11.34 g/cm³) and low electrical conductivity<br>• Exceptionally soft: can be easily scratched or marked with a fingernail<br>• Diamagnetic at room temperature<br>• Effective absorber of X-rays and gamma radiation<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Forms a protective oxide and carbonate layer that prevents deep corrosion<br>• Exhibits stable +2 and +4 oxidation states (+2 is much more common/stable)<br>• Dissolves slowly in water in the presence of oxygen; dissolves in nitric acid<br>• Highly resistant to sulfuric and phosphoric acids due to insoluble coatings<br>• Forms a vast range of compounds including halides, oxides, and sulfides<br>• Amphoteric: can react with both strong acids and strong bases<br><br><b>Lead Isotopes</b><br>• Lead has 4 stable natural isotopes: Pb-204, 206, 207, 208<br>• Lead-208 (²⁰⁸Pb) — most abundant and exceptionally stable (52.4%)<br>• Lead-206 and Lead-207 — the end-products of Uranium and Actinium decay chains<br>• Over 35 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• Isotope ratios used to date rocks (U-Pb dating) and track pollution sources<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in the mineral Galena (Lead sulfide, PbS)<br>• Also occurs in minerals like Cerussite (PbCO₃) and Anglesite (PbSO₄)<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 14 ppm (relatively abundant heavy metal)<br>• Frequently found in association with silver, zinc, and copper ores<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from Galena via roasting (to form PbO) followed by carbon reduction<br>• Refined via the Parkes process (to remove silver) and electrolytic methods<br>• Highly sustainable: more lead is produced via recycling (secondary) than mining<br><br><b>Applications of Lead</b><br>• Energy: lead-acid batteries for starting vehicle engines and backup power<br>• Protection: radiation shielding in hospitals, nuclear facilities, and X-ray labs<br>• Construction: soundproofing, flashing for roofs, and historical plumbing<br>• Electronics: lead-based solders (decreasing due to RoHS regulations)<br>• Industry: weighted ballast for ships and specialized glass (lead crystal)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• End-product of the decay of the heaviest elements in the universe<br>• Critical tool for geochronology (dating the age of the Earth)<br>• Major environmental priority due to its persistent toxicity and neurotoxicity<br>• Fundamental for the safety of medical and industrial nuclear applications<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Environmental Science — remediation of lead-contaminated soil and water<br>• Geology — dating planetary formation and tectonic processes<br>• Medicine — radiation safety for both patients and healthcare workers<br>• Archeology — isotopic analysis to determine the origin of ancient artifacts",
    "system.bismuth.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Bi<br>• Atomic Number — 83<br>• A brittle, crystalline, silvery-white post-transition metal with a pinkish tinge<br>• Named after the German 'Wismut' (white mass)<br>• The most naturally diamagnetic metal known to science<br>• Famous for its spectacular iridescent 'hopper crystals' (synthetic)<br>• Exceptionally low toxicity compared to other heavy metals (often replaces lead)<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 83 protons in the nucleus<br>• 83 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common isotope is Bismuth-209<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d¹⁰ 6s² 6p³<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 15 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white luster with a distinct iridescent/pink oxidation film<br>• Boiling point — 1564°C<br>• Melting point — 271.4°C (relatively low for a metal)<br>• High density (approx. 9.78 g/cm³) but expands upon freezing (like water)<br>• Very brittle and easily pulverized into powder<br>• Lowest thermal conductivity of all metals (except mercury)<br>• Highest Hall effect of any metal (large increase in electrical resistance in magnetic fields)<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Stable in air and water at room temperature; forms a colorful oxide layer<br>• Exhibits stable +3 and +5 oxidation states (+3 is more common/stable)<br>• Dissolves easily in nitric and concentrated sulfuric acids<br>• Forms stable halides, nitrates, and specialized organobismuth compounds<br>• Bismuth(III) oxide (Bi₂O₃) is an important yellow industrial pigment<br>• Non-reactive with non-oxidizing acids like dilute hydrochloric acid<br><br><b>Bismuth Isotopes</b><br>• Bismuth-209 (²⁰⁹Bi) — previously thought stable, now known to be radioactive<br>• Bismuth-209 half-life — 1.9 quintillion years (longer than the age of the universe)<br>• Effectively stable for all practical and scientific purposes<br>• Over 35 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• Bismuth-213 — used in advanced targeted alpha-therapy (TAT) for cancer<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in minerals like Bismuthinite (Bi₂S₃) and Bismite (Bi₂O₃)<br>• Occurs in its native (pure) metallic form more often than many other elements<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 0.009 ppm (relatively rare element)<br>• Frequently found as a byproduct of lead, copper, and tin ores<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered as a byproduct of lead and copper smelting and refining<br>• Purified via the Betterton-Kroll process or electrolytic methods<br>• Metal produced by reduction of bismuth oxide with carbon or iron<br><br><b>Applications of Bismuth</b><br>• Medicine: Bismuth subsalicylate (Pepto-Bismol) for digestive issues and H. pylori treatment<br>• Metallurgy: low-melting 'fusible alloys' for fire sprinklers and specialized solder<br>• Safety: replaces lead in ammunition (hunting shot) and fishing weights (non-toxic)<br>• Cosmetics: Bismuth oxychloride used to give a pearlescent luster to makeup<br>• Electronics: used in specialized semiconductors and thermoelectric materials<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• The 'heaviest' stable element (practically) in the periodic table<br>• Enabling material for eco-friendly, non-toxic alternatives to lead<br>• Critical tool for advanced targeted alpha-radiation cancer therapy<br>• Fundamental for the study of diamagnetism and exotic metallic properties<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — gastrointestinal health and targeted oncology (TAT)<br>• Environment — non-toxic replacement for lead in hunting and fishing<br>• Technology — specialized low-temp alloys and optical materials<br>• Industry — pearlescent pigments for cosmetics and automotive paints",
    "system.polonium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Po<br>• Atomic Number — 84<br>• A highly radioactive and rare chalcogen metalloid<br>• Named after 'Polonia' (Poland), the homeland of its discoverer Marie Curie<br>• One of the most dangerous substances known: millions of times more toxic than cyanide<br>• Critical as a high-power alpha-particle source for specialized research<br>• Famous for its historical and controversial use in high-profile poisoning cases<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 84 protons in the nucleus<br>• 84 electrons around the nucleus<br>• All known isotopes are radioactive (no stable isotopes exist)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d¹⁰ 6s² 6p⁴<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 16 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-grey, metallic appearance; exists in alpha and beta allotropes<br>• Boiling point — 962°C<br>• Melting point — 254°C (relatively low)<br>• High density (approx. 9.20 g/cm³) and metallic-level conductivity<br>• Unique crystal structure (primitive cubic) in its alpha form<br>• Glows blue in air due to excitation of surrounding nitrogen by alpha particles<br>• Releases significant heat (approx. 140 W/g) due to intense radioactivity<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with oxygen and moisture to form Polonium(IV) oxide (PoO₂)<br>• Exhibits stable +2 and +4 oxidation states (+4 is more common/stable)<br>• Dissolves easily in dilute mineral acids like hydrochloric or nitric acid<br>• Forms stable halides and specialized polonides with other metals<br>• Behaves chemically like a heavier version of Tellurium and Selenium<br>• Highly volatile: vaporizes easily even at moderate temperatures<br><br><b>Polonium Isotopes</b><br>• Polonium has no stable isotopes; over 30 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Polonium-210 (²¹⁰Po) — most common and significant isotope (half-life: 138 days)<br>• Polonium-209 (²⁰⁹Po) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: approx. 125 years)<br>• Part of the natural decay chains of Uranium, Thorium, and Actinium<br>• Naturally occurring in trace amounts in the Earth's crust and atmosphere<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Extremely rare: present in Earth's crust at about 1 part per 10¹⁵ (quadrillion)<br>• Found primarily as a decay product in uranium ores (e.g., Pitchblende)<br>• Present in trace amounts in tobacco and some specialized sea life<br>• Global environmental background levels are exceptionally low<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced primarily via nuclear transmutation in nuclear reactors<br>• Bismuth-209 is bombarded with neutrons to form Bismuth-210, which decays to Po-210<br>• Purified via distillation or electrodeposition from bismuth targets<br><br><b>Applications of Polonium</b><br>• Space Tech: high-power heat source for Radioisotope Thermoelectric Generators (RTGs)<br>• Industry: static eliminators in specialized machinery (brushes and blowers)<br>• Research: pure alpha-particle source for nuclear physics and chemistry experiments<br>• History: neutron trigger for early nuclear weapons (in combination with Beryllium)<br>• Forensics: specialized analysis of environmental and biological contamination<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• First element discovered by Marie and Pierre Curie in their search for radioactivity<br>• Powerful tool for understanding alpha decay and nuclear heat generation<br>• Major health concern if ingested due to intense internal alpha radiation<br>• Fundamental for the study of the heaviest group 16 elements<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Nuclear Physics — pure alpha emission and heat generation research<br>• Medicine — study of internal radiation damage and toxicology<br>• Aerospace — heat sources for autonomous planetary probes<br>• Environmental Science — monitoring natural and industrial radioactive pathways",
    "system.astatine.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — At<br>• Atomic Number — 85<br>• The rarest naturally occurring element in the Earth's crust<br>• Named after the Greek word 'astatos' (unstable)<br>• Highly radioactive halogen: all isotopes have very short half-lives<br>• Potentially game-changing for Targeted Alpha-Therapy (TAT) in cancer treatment<br>• Total amount in the Earth's crust at any moment is less than 30 grams<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 85 protons in the nucleus<br>• 85 electrons around the nucleus<br>• All known isotopes are radioactive (no stable isotopes exist)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d¹⁰ 6s² 6p⁵<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 17 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dark, metallic-looking solid; behaves as a metalloid/halogen<br>• Boiling point — 337°C (estimated)<br>• Melting point — 302°C (estimated)<br>• Predicted density (approx. 7.0 g/cm³) and semiconductor-like conductivity<br>• Highly volatile: vaporizes easily even at low temperatures<br>• Releases intense heat due to extreme radioactivity (samples vaporize themselves)<br>• Darker and more metallic than Iodine in appearance<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Exhibits multiple oxidation states: -1, +1, +3, +5, +7<br>• Behaves chemically like Iodine but with more metallic characteristics<br>• Forms stable astatides with metals and organoastatine compounds<br>• Dissolves in various organic solvents similar to iodine<br>• Forms complex anions and behaves as a halogen in many reactions<br>• Accumulates in the thyroid gland if ingested, similar to radioactive iodine<br><br><b>Astatine Isotopes</b><br>• Astatine has no stable isotopes; over 35 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Astatine-210 (²¹⁰At) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 8.1 hours)<br>• Astatine-211 (²¹¹At) — critical for medical research and cancer therapy<br>• Naturally occurring isotopes (At-215, 217, 218, 219) are part of decay chains<br>• Naturally occurring isotopes have half-lives of less than a minute<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Extremely rare: less than 1 ounce (approx. 28g) exists in the entire Earth's crust<br>• Found only as a transient decay product in Uranium and Thorium ores<br>• Background levels in the environment are virtually non-existent<br>• Considered the rarest 'natural' element due to its extreme instability<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced exclusively in particle accelerators (cyclotrons)<br>• Bismuth-209 is bombarded with alpha particles to form Astatine-211<br>• Purified via distillation at high temperatures from the bismuth target<br><br><b>Applications of Astatine</b><br>• Medicine: Astatine-211 is a prime candidate for Targeted Alpha-Therapy (TAT)<br>• Research: used to study the chemical trends of the heaviest halogens<br>• Nuclear Chemistry: used to investigate extreme radioactive decay pathways<br>• Specialized tracing: study of thyroid and biological uptake of heavy halogens<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Enabling material for next-generation, highly targeted cancer treatments<br>• Essential for testing chemical theories of the heaviest elements<br>• Represents the extreme limit of the naturally occurring periodic table<br>• Fundamental for research into alpha-emitting radiopharmaceuticals<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — advanced oncology and targeted internal radiation<br>• Nuclear Physics — study of heavy-ion reactions and decay modes<br>• Chemistry — exploring the boundary between halogens and metals<br>• Toxicology — research into heavy radioactive element bioaccumulation",
    "system.radon.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Rn<br>• Atomic Number — 86<br>• A colorless, odorless, and tasteless radioactive noble gas<br>• Named after 'Radium' (as it is a direct decay product of Radium)<br>• The densest gas known to science (approx. 9.73 g/L)<br>• Major environmental health concern: the leading cause of lung cancer in non-smokers<br>• Critical for geological research and specialized medical radiotherapy (historical)<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 86 protons in the nucleus<br>• 86 electrons around the nucleus (stable closed shell configuration)<br>• All isotopes are radioactive (no stable isotopes exist)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d¹⁰ 6s² 6p⁶<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 18 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Colorless and odorless as a gas; glows with a yellow-to-orange luminescence when cold<br>• Boiling point — -61.7°C<br>• Melting point — -71°C<br>• High density: about 8 times denser than air at sea level<br>• Slightly soluble in water; highly soluble in organic solvents (e.g., alcohol)<br>• Condenses into a phosphorescent liquid/solid at very low temperatures<br>• Chemically inert under most conditions but can form some compounds<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Most chemically reactive of the noble gases (after Xenon and Krypton)<br>• Can react with fluorine to form Radon difluoride (RnF₂)<br>• Exhibits stable +2 and +6 oxidation states in specialized compounds<br>• Forms stable complexes with some specialized acids and oxidizing agents<br>• Highly radioactive: the decay of radon produces radioactive 'progeny' (solid particles)<br>• Adsorbs easily onto activated charcoal (used for testing and removal)<br><br><b>Radon Isotopes</b><br>• Radon has no stable isotopes; over 35 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Radon-222 (²²²Rn) — most common and significant isotope (half-life: 3.8 days)<br>• Radon-220 (²²⁰Rn) — also known as 'Thoron' (half-life: 55.6 seconds)<br>• Radon-219 (²¹⁹Rn) — also known as 'Actinon' (half-life: 3.96 seconds)<br>• Part of the natural decay chains of Uranium-238, Thorium-232, and Uranium-235<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found naturally in the atmosphere in trace amounts (approx. 1 atom in 10²¹)<br>• Concentrates in soil and groundwater as a result of uranium decay in rocks<br>• Can accumulate to dangerous levels in enclosed spaces like basements and mines<br>• Present in Earth's crust as a transient gas; constantly being replenished by decay<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Collected primarily from radium-containing solutions or ores<br>• Radon gas is pumped out and purified via cryogenic distillation or adsorption<br>• Produced on demand for specialized research and medical applications<br><br><b>Applications of Radon</b><br>• Geology: used to track groundwater movement and predict earthquake activity<br>• Medicine: historical use in 'radon seeds' for brachytherapy (now mostly replaced)<br>• Research: used as a tracer for studying atmospheric mixing and soil gas transport<br>• Industrial Safety: calibration source for radiation detection and monitoring systems<br>• Hydrology: used to study the interaction between surface water and groundwater<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Major environmental priority due to its role in indoor air quality and cancer risk<br>• Critical tool for understanding the movement of fluids within the Earth's crust<br>• Important for the study of noble gas chemistry and extreme radioactive environments<br>• Fundamental for the development of national radiation safety guidelines<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Environmental Health — lung cancer prevention and indoor air testing<br>• Geology — earthquake prediction and mapping of tectonic faults<br>• Medicine — historical radiotherapy and study of alpha radiation biology<br>• Physics — research into noble gas bonding and cryogenic behavior",
    "system.francium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Fr<br>• Atomic Number — 87<br>• An extremely radioactive alkali metal; the most unstable of the natural elements<br>• Named after 'France', the country where it was discovered by Marguerite Perey<br>• Occurs only in trace amounts in uranium and thorium ores<br>• Second rarest naturally occurring element in the Earth's crust (after Astatine)<br>• Primarily of theoretical interest due to its extreme scarcity and radioactivity<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 87 protons in the nucleus<br>• 87 electrons around the nucleus (highly reactive alkali metal config)<br>• All isotopes are radioactive (no stable isotopes exist)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 7s¹<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 1 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a highly reactive, silvery-white metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — 677°C (estimated)<br>• Melting point — 27°C (estimated; possibly liquid near room temp)<br>• Predicted density (approx. 1.87 g/cm³); very low density for a heavy element<br>• High electrical and thermal conductivity (predicted)<br>• Highly volatile: quickly vaporizes and decays due to intense radioactivity<br>• Most electropositive element known to science<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Most chemically reactive alkali metal; reacts violently with water<br>• Exhibits stable +1 oxidation state (exclusively)<br>• Behaves chemically like a heavier version of Cesium and Rubidium<br>• Forms stable halides and specialized salts (predicted)<br>• Dissolves in various organic solvents (predicted)<br>• Forms complex cations and behaves as a heavy alkali metal in reactions<br><br><b>Francium Isotopes</b><br>• Francium has no stable isotopes; over 30 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Francium-223 (²²³Fr) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 22 minutes)<br>• Francium-221 (²²¹Fr) — part of the natural Actinium decay chain<br>• All isotopes have extremely short half-lives, making study very difficult<br>• Naturally occurring isotopes exist only in fleeting trace amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Extremely rare: less than 30 grams exists in the entire Earth's crust at any time<br>• Found only as a transient decay product in Uranium and Thorium ores<br>• Background levels in the environment are virtually non-existent<br>• Considered a 'trace' element found in minerals like Pitchblende<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced exclusively in particle accelerators or by the decay of Actinium-227<br>• Can be trapped as ions or atoms in specialized magneto-optical traps (MOT)<br>• Purified via specialized chemical separation or mass spectrometry methods<br><br><b>Applications of Francium</b><br>• Research: used to study weak nuclear forces and atomic parity violation<br>• Nuclear Physics: investigation of extreme radioactive decay and nuclear structure<br>• Laser Cooling: studied in MOT systems to understand heavy atom behavior<br>• Tracing: studied as a potential tracer in specialized biological research<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Represents the extreme limit of the alkali metal group<br>• Essential for testing quantum electrodynamics and relativistic atomic theories<br>• Powerful tool for understanding the forces that hold the nucleus together<br>• Fundamental for the study of the heaviest naturally occurring elements<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — testing the Standard Model of particle physics<br>• Nuclear Chemistry — exploring the chemistry of short-lived radioactive atoms<br>• Laser Science — high-precision trapping and manipulation of heavy ions<br>• History — the last element to be discovered in nature (not synthesized)",
    "system.radium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ra<br>• Atomic Number — 88<br>• A highly radioactive alkaline earth metal; nearly pure white luster<br>• Named after the Latin 'radius' (ray) due to its intense radioactivity<br>• Famous for its historical use in luminous 'glow-in-the-dark' paints and watches<br>• Discovered by Marie and Pierre Curie in their search for the cause of radioactivity<br>• Historically used in radiotherapy; now mostly replaced by safer isotopes<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 88 protons in the nucleus<br>• 88 electrons around the nucleus (alkaline earth metal configuration)<br>• All isotopes are radioactive (no stable isotopes exist)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 2 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white luster when fresh; turns black upon exposure to air<br>• Boiling point — 1737°C<br>• Melting point — 700°C<br>• High density (approx. 5.5 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity<br>• Luminesces with a faint blue glow in the dark due to high radioactivity<br>• Releases significant heat (approx. 28 W/g) due to radioactive decay<br>• Volatilizes more easily than barium in a vacuum<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: reacts violently with water to form Radium hydroxide<br>• Exhibits stable +2 oxidation state (exclusively)<br>• Behaves chemically like a heavier version of Barium and Strontium<br>• Forms stable halides, sulfates, and carbonates (most are insoluble)<br>• Soluble in most mineral acids with the release of hydrogen gas<br>• Tarnishes instantly in air, forming a layer of nitride and oxide<br><br><b>Radium Isotopes</b><br>• Radium has no stable isotopes; over 30 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Radium-226 (²²⁶Ra) — most common and significant isotope (half-life: 1600 years)<br>• Radium-228 (²²⁸Ra) — naturally occurring radioisotope (half-life: 5.75 years)<br>• Radium-223 (²²³Ra) — used in modern targeted alpha-therapy for bone cancer<br>• Part of the natural decay chains of Uranium-238 and Thorium-232<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in trace amounts in Uranium and Thorium ores (e.g., Pitchblende)<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 1 part per trillion (extremely rare)<br>• Occurs in groundwater and soil in very low concentrations<br>• Marie Curie processed tons of ore to extract just 1 gram of pure radium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered as a byproduct of uranium mining and refining<br>• Extracted from mineral concentrates via complex chemical leaching and fractional crystallization<br>• Metal produced by electrolysis of radium chloride or reduction with aluminum<br><br><b>Applications of Radium</b><br>• Medicine: Radium-223 (Xofigo) for treatment of metastatic bone cancer<br>• Research: used as a source of neutrons when mixed with beryllium<br>• Industry: historical use in self-luminous dials (now largely banned)<br>• Geology: used to study groundwater flow and age of sediment layers<br>• Nuclear Physics: used in the calibration of radiation detection equipment<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• The first radioactive element to be isolated in pure metallic form<br>• Historically triggered the 'Radium Age' of medicine and science<br>• Major health priority due to its behavior as a 'bone seeker' (mimics calcium)<br>• Fundamental for the study of the biological effects of alpha radiation<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — advanced oncology (bone cancer) and historical radiotherapy<br>• History — the story of the 'Radium Girls' and workplace safety laws<br>• Environmental Science — monitoring radium levels in drinking water<br>• Physics — understanding the structure of the atomic nucleus",
    "system.actinium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ac<br>• Atomic Number — 89<br>• A highly radioactive, silvery-white metal; the first of the Actinide series<br>• Named after the Greek word 'aktinos' (beam or ray)<br>• Glows with an eerie blue light in the dark due to its intense radioactivity<br>• Critical for advanced medical research into Targeted Alpha-Therapy (TAT)<br>• Extremely rare and difficult to study due to its high radioactivity and heat generation<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 89 protons in the nucleus<br>• 89 electrons around the nucleus<br>• All isotopes are radioactive (no stable isotopes exist)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 6d¹ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white appearance; glows bright blue in the dark<br>• Boiling point — 3197°C (estimated)<br>• Melting point — 1050°C<br>• High density (approx. 10.07 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity<br>• Soft metal with a crystal structure similar to lead<br>• Highly volatile at high temperatures; samples self-heat significantly<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: reacts with moisture and oxygen to form Actinium(III) oxide (Ac₂O₃)<br>• Exhibits stable +3 oxidation state (exclusively)<br>• Behaves chemically like a heavier version of Lanthanum<br>• Forms stable halides, hydroxides, and oxalates (mostly insoluble)<br>• Dissolves easily in mineral acids like hydrochloric or nitric acid<br>• Strongest known electropositive element after Cesium and Francium<br><br><b>Actinium Isotopes</b><br>• Actinium has no stable isotopes; over 30 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Actinium-227 (²²⁷Ac) — most common isotope (half-life: 21.77 years)<br>• Actinium-225 (²²⁵Ac) — 'Holy Grail' of targeted alpha-therapy for cancer<br>• Naturally occurring isotopes (Ac-227, 228) are part of decay chains<br>• Over 30 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Extremely rare: present in Earth's crust at about 0.0005 ppm<br>• Found primarily in trace amounts in Uranium ores (approx. 1 ton of ore per 0.1g of Ac)<br>• Present in groundwater and soil in virtually undetectable concentrations<br>• Never found free in nature; always found in association with Uranium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced primarily via neutron bombardment of Radium-226 in nuclear reactors<br>• Can also be extracted in trace amounts from uranium ore residues<br>• Purified via complex solvent extraction and ion exchange processes<br><br><b>Applications of Actinium</b><br>• Medicine: Ac-225 used in advanced targeted alpha-therapy (TAT) for various cancers<br>• Space Tech: potential fuel for high-efficiency radioisotope thermoelectric generators<br>• Research: used as a source of neutrons and alpha particles for nuclear experiments<br>• Tracing: used in specialized deep-sea research to study ocean mixing rates<br>• Nuclear Medicine: used to produce Bismuth-213 for cancer treatment<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Enabling material for some of the most advanced cancer treatments in development<br>• Important for testing theories of the electronic structure of heavy elements<br>• Powerful tool for understanding the geological and oceanographic cycles<br>• Fundamental for the study of the transition from lanthanides to actinides<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — next-generation oncology and radiopharmaceuticals<br>• Oceanography — tracing deep-water currents and ocean mixing<br>• Nuclear Physics — research into nuclear fission and alpha decay<br>• Aerospace — long-term power sources for deep-space exploration",
    "system.thorium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Th<br>• Atomic Number — 90<br>• A weakly radioactive, silvery-white metal; named after 'Thor', the Norse god of thunder<br>• Three to four times more abundant in nature than Uranium<br>• High potential as a cleaner, safer, and more abundant alternative to uranium in nuclear reactors<br>• Used historically in gas mantles to produce bright white light<br>• Forms the most stable oxide of any element (ThO₂)<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 90 protons in the nucleus<br>• 90 electrons around the nucleus<br>• All isotopes are radioactive (but Thorium-232 is exceptionally stable)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 6d² 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white luster when fresh; turns black upon exposure to air<br>• Boiling point — 4788°C (extremely high)<br>• Melting point — 1750°C (high for an actinide)<br>• High density (approx. 11.7 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity<br>• Soft and ductile; can be easily worked, rolled, and drawn into wire<br>• Highest refractive index of any metal oxide (as ThO₂)<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Slowly reacts with water and dilute acids; dissolves in concentrated hydrochloric acid<br>• Exhibits stable +4 oxidation state (most common/stable)<br>• Forms the most refractory oxide known (ThO₂), melting at 3300°C<br>• Highly resistant to corrosion in air when pure; forms a protective oxide layer<br>• Forms stable halides, nitrates, and specialized organothorium compounds<br>• Pyrophoric in finely divided powder form (can ignite in air)<br><br><b>Thorium Isotopes</b><br>• Thorium-232 (²³²Th) — the primary natural isotope (approx. 100% abundance)<br>• Thorium-232 half-life — 14 billion years (comparable to the age of the universe)<br>• Thorium-230 and Thorium-228 — naturally occurring isotopes in decay chains<br>• Over 30 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• Thorium-229 — critical for research into nuclear 'clocks' (ultra-precise timekeeping)<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in the mineral Monazite (a phosphate of rare earths)<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 6-12 ppm (as common as lead)<br>• Occurs in many common rocks like granite in trace amounts<br>• Major deposits in India, Australia, Brazil, Canada, and the United States<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from Monazite sand via leaching with hot sulfuric acid or sodium hydroxide<br>• Purified via solvent extraction and precipitation as thorium nitrate<br>• Metal produced by reduction of thorium oxide with calcium or electrolysis of fused salts<br><br><b>Applications of Thorium</b><br>• Energy: used in experimental Thorium reactors (MSFR) as a safer nuclear fuel<br>• Industry: added to tungsten to create 'thoriated' electrodes for TIG welding<br>• Optics: high-refractive index glass for high-end camera lenses (historical)<br>• Aerospace: added to magnesium alloys to increase strength and heat resistance<br>• Lighting: historical use in gas mantles (Auer mantles) for bright white light<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Potential foundation for a sustainable, carbon-free global energy future<br>• Essential for high-precision manufacturing and welding technology<br>• Critical tool for understanding the age of the Earth's oceans and sediments<br>• Fundamental for research into advanced nuclear physics and timekeeping<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Energy — sustainable nuclear fission and 'green' nuclear power research<br>• Technology — high-performance metallurgy and precision optics<br>• Geology — dating deep-sea sediments and crustal rocks<br>• Aerospace — high-strength, heat-resistant lightweight alloys",
    "system.protactinium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Pa<br>• Atomic Number — 91<br>• A dense, silvery-grey radioactive actinide metal<br>• Named after the Greek 'protos' (first) as it is the precursor to Actinium<br>• One of the rarest and most expensive naturally occurring elements<br>• Highly toxic and radioactive; requires specialized handling in nuclear facilities<br>• Exists in trace amounts in all uranium ores (approx. 1 part per million)<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 91 protons in the nucleus<br>• 91 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Protactinium-231 (T1/2 = 32,760 years)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f² 6d¹ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white luster; turns black upon exposure to air<br>• Boiling point — 4000°C (estimated)<br>• Melting point — 1568°C<br>• High density (approx. 15.37 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity<br>• Superconductive at temperatures below 1.4 Kelvin<br>• Hardness comparable to that of uranium; malleable and ductile<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: reacts with oxygen, water vapor, and inorganic acids<br>• Exhibits stable +4 and +5 oxidation states (+5 is more common/stable)<br>• Behaves chemically like a mix of Thorium and Tantalum/Niobium<br>• Forms stable halides (fluorides, chlorides) and complex oxides<br>• Highly resistant to corrosion in air when pure; forms a protective layer<br>• Forms insoluble hydroxides and carbonates in aqueous solutions<br><br><b>Protactinium Isotopes</b><br>• Protactinium has no stable isotopes; over 25 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Protactinium-231 (²³¹Pa) — most significant natural isotope (part of U-235 chain)<br>• Protactinium-234 (²³⁴Pa) — occurs in two different energy states (isomers)<br>• Protactinium-233 (²³³Pa) — critical intermediate in the thorium nuclear fuel cycle<br>• Isotope ratios used to date deep-sea sediments and geological formations<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in trace amounts in Uranium ores like Pitchblende<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 0.1 to 1.0 parts per trillion (extremely rare)<br>• Occurs in the environment only as a transient decay product of heavy elements<br>• Never found free in nature; always found in association with Uranium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Extracted from uranium ore residues (sludges) via complex chemical separation<br>• Can be produced by neutron bombardment of Thorium-230 or Thorium-232<br>• Purified via solvent extraction and ion exchange chromatography<br>• World supply of pure protactinium is estimated to be less than 150 grams<br><br><b>Applications of Protactinium</b><br>• Research: used to study the chemical behavior of the earliest actinides<br>• Geology: used as a radioactive tracer to date marine sediments and fossils<br>• Nuclear Tech: intermediate stage in producing fissile Uranium-233 from Thorium<br>• Science: used in the calibration of high-precision radiation sensors<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential link in the natural radioactive decay chains of the universe<br>• Critical for the development of alternative thorium-based nuclear energy<br>• Major concern for radiation safety in uranium mining and processing<br>• Fundamental for testing relativistic effects in heavy atom chemistry<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Geology — dating the formation of the Earth's crust and oceans<br>• Nuclear Energy — research into safe and efficient thorium fuel cycles<br>• Medicine — study of internal radiation damage from heavy actinides<br>• Physics — investigation of superconductivity and magnetic properties",
    "system.uranium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — U<br>• Atomic Number — 92<br>• A dense, silvery-white, weakly radioactive actinide metal<br>• Named after the planet 'Uranus', discovered just years before the element<br>• The heaviest naturally occurring element in significant quantities<br>• Primary fuel for global nuclear power generation and nuclear propulsion<br>• Famous for its historical and controversial role in the development of nuclear weapons<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 92 protons in the nucleus<br>• 92 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common natural isotope is Uranium-238 (99.27% abundance)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f³ 6d¹ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white luster; turns dull grey upon exposure to air<br>• Boiling point — 4131°C<br>• Melting point — 1132.2°C<br>• Exceptionally high density (approx. 19.1 g/cm³), similar to gold or tungsten<br>• Ductile, malleable, and slightly paramagnetic<br>• Poor conductor of electricity; however, it is superconductive at very low temps<br>• Displays distinct pyrophoric properties when in finely divided powder form<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: reacts with almost all non-metals and inorganic acids<br>• Exhibits stable +3, +4, +5, and +6 oxidation states (+4 and +6 are common)<br>• Reacts with water and oxygen at room temperature to form oxides<br>• Forms stable halides, nitrates, and complex uranyl salts (UO₂²⁺)<br>• Highly resistant to corrosion in concentrated sulfuric or nitric acid<br>• Uranyl compounds often display characteristic green or yellow fluorescence<br><br><b>Uranium Isotopes</b><br>• Natural uranium consists of 3 isotopes: U-238 (99.3%), U-235 (0.7%), U-234 (trace)<br>• Uranium-235 (²³⁵U) — the only naturally occurring fissile isotope in the world<br>• Uranium-238 (²³⁸U) — fertile isotope (can be converted to fissile Plutonium-239)<br>• Over 20 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• U-Pb isotope ratios are the 'gold standard' for dating the age of the Earth<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in minerals like Uraninite (Pitchblende) and Carnotite<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 2.7 ppm (more common than silver or mercury)<br>• Occurs naturally in seawater, soil, and even some common rocks like granite<br>• Major global deposits in Kazakhstan, Canada, Australia, and Namibia<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via mining (underground/open-pit) or in-situ leaching (ISL)<br>• Refined into 'yellowcake' (uranium oxide concentrate) via chemical processing<br>• Enriched (to increase U-235 content) via gas centrifugation or diffusion<br>• Pure metal produced by reduction of uranium tetrafluoride with magnesium/calcium<br><br><b>Applications of Uranium</b><br>• Energy: primary fuel for nuclear reactors providing carbon-free electricity<br>• Military: 'Depleted Uranium' (DU) used in high-density armor and penetrators<br>• History: used in the Manhattan Project to create the first atomic bombs<br>• Science: used as a target for synthesizing new transuranium elements<br>• Industry: historical use as a coloring agent in specialized glass and ceramics<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• The 'engine' of Earth's internal heat due to its ongoing radioactive decay<br>• Critical for understanding the formation and evolution of the solar system<br>• Major geopolitical and environmental priority due to its dual-use nature<br>• Fundamental for the study of high-energy physics and nuclear chemistry<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Energy — base-load power generation and nuclear safety research<br>• Geosciences — dating the Earth, Moon, and ancient geological processes<br>• Technology — high-density materials and advanced nuclear propulsion<br>• Medicine — research into actinide toxicology and radiation protection",
    "system.neptunium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Np<br>• Atomic Number — 93<br>• A dense, silvery radioactive actinide metal; the first transuranium element<br>• Named after the planet 'Neptune' (as it follows Uranium in the periodic table)<br>• Primarily produced in nuclear reactors as a byproduct of uranium irradiation<br>• Critical intermediate for the production of Plutonium-238 (space energy fuel)<br>• Highly toxic and radioactive; requires advanced shielding and remote handling<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 93 protons in the nucleus<br>• 93 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Neptunium-237 (T1/2 = 2.14 million years)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f⁴ 6d¹ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery appearance; tarnishes slowly in air at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — 3902°C (estimated)<br>• Melting point — 639°C (relatively low for a metal)<br>• High density (approx. 20.45 g/cm³), making it one of the densest known metals<br>• Exists in three allotropic forms (alpha, beta, gamma) depending on temperature<br>• Ductile and malleable in its beta and gamma phases<br>• Paramagnetic over a wide temperature range<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: reacts with oxygen, steam, and most acids<br>• Exhibits multiple oxidation states: +3, +4, +5, +6, and +7 (+5 is most stable)<br>• Forms stable halides, oxides, and complex neptunyl salts (NpO₂⁺)<br>• Chemical behavior is a bridge between Uranium and Plutonium<br>• Dissolves easily in concentrated hydrochloric acid and organic solvents<br>• Solutions of different oxidation states display distinct colors (e.g., purple, green, yellow)<br><br><b>Neptunium Isotopes</b><br>• Neptunium has no stable isotopes; over 20 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Neptunium-237 (²³⁷Np) — most significant and longest-lived isotope<br>• Neptunium-239 (²³⁹Np) — the first transuranium isotope ever discovered (1940)<br>• Part of the artificial 'Neptunium series' of radioactive decay<br>• Occurs naturally in only fleeting trace amounts in Uranium ores<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Virtually non-existent in nature: only trace amounts found in uranium ores<br>• Formed in nature via neutron capture reactions from natural uranium decay<br>• Global presence is almost entirely due to human activity (nuclear testing/waste)<br>• Never found in concentrated minerals; considered a 'synthetic' element for practical use<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced in large quantities in nuclear reactors from Uranium-235/238<br>• Extracted from spent nuclear fuel via the PUREX or specialized REDOX processes<br>• Metal produced by reduction of neptunium tetrafluoride with barium or calcium vapor<br>• Managed as long-lived radioactive waste in nuclear fuel management programs<br><br><b>Applications of Neptunium</b><br>• Energy: precursor for producing Plutonium-238 for space RTGs<br>• Research: used to study the chemical properties of heavy transuranium elements<br>• Nuclear Physics: used as a target for synthesizing heavier actinides<br>• Defense: studied for potential high-energy neutron weapon applications (theoretical)<br>• Science: used in the calibration of high-energy particle and neutron detectors<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• The first 'man-made' element beyond the boundaries of natural uranium<br>• Critical for understanding the synthesis of all heavier elements in the universe<br>• Major concern for long-term geological nuclear waste storage and safety<br>• Fundamental for testing the actinide 'bridge' in chemical periodicity<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Space Science — enabling long-term power for deep-space exploration (via Pu-238)<br>• Nuclear Waste Management — researching the long-term behavior of actinides in soil<br>• Physics — study of relativistic effects and f-orbital electron behavior<br>• Chemistry — exploring extreme oxidation states and complex ion formation",
    "system.plutonium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Pu<br>• Atomic Number — 94<br>• A dense, silvery-grey radioactive actinide metal; tarnishes quickly to a dull yellow<br>• Named after the dwarf planet 'Pluto' (following Neptunium and Uranium)<br>• The most significant transuranium element in human history and technology<br>• Critical fuel for advanced nuclear reactors and the core material for nuclear weapons<br>• Famous as a high-density energy source for space missions (RTGs)<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 94 protons in the nucleus<br>• 94 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common isotope is Plutonium-239 (fissile, used in weapons/reactors)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f⁶ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery appearance; exhibits six different allotropic forms (phases) depending on temp<br>• Boiling point — 3228°C<br>• Melting point — 639.4°C (remarkably low for such a dense metal)<br>• High density (approx. 19.82 g/cm³ in its alpha phase)<br>• Exceptionally poor conductor of heat and electricity compared to most metals<br>• Warm to the touch due to intense alpha radiation and self-heating<br>• Pyrophoric: fine particles can spontaneously ignite in air<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: reacts with oxygen, moisture, and common laboratory acids<br>• Exhibits four common oxidation states: +3, +4, +5, and +6 (+4 is most common)<br>• Forms stable halides, oxides, and complex plutonium salts<br>• Displays distinct and beautiful colors in solution (e.g., pink, tan, emerald green)<br>• Forms a wide variety of alloys with elements like aluminum, gallium, and iron<br>• Highly complex chemistry: can undergo 'disproportionation' (existing in multiple states at once)<br><br><b>Plutonium Isotopes</b><br>• Plutonium has no stable isotopes; over 20 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Plutonium-239 (²³⁹Pu) — primary fissile isotope (half-life: 24,100 years)<br>• Plutonium-238 (²³⁸Pu) — used as a heat source for space power systems (half-life: 87.7 years)<br>• Plutonium-244 (²⁴⁴Pu) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 80 million years)<br>• Trace amounts found in nature as a result of natural uranium neutron capture<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Virtually non-existent in nature: only fleeting traces found in uranium ores<br>• Global environmental presence is due to historical atmospheric nuclear testing<br>• Managed as a strictly controlled synthetic element in the nuclear industry<br>• Considered the most 'man-made' element with significant global impacts<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced in nuclear reactors via neutron irradiation of Uranium-238<br>• Separated from spent nuclear fuel using the PUREX (Plutonium Uranium Redox EXtraction) process<br>• Refined into metal via reduction of plutonium tetrafluoride with calcium<br>• Subject to intense international regulation and non-proliferation monitoring<br><br><b>Applications of Plutonium</b><br>• Energy: fuel for 'breeder' reactors and MOX (Mixed Oxide) nuclear fuels<br>• Space Tech: power source for Voyager, New Horizons, and Mars rovers (Perseverance)<br>• Military: primary fissile material for modern nuclear warheads<br>• Research: target material for synthesizing new superheavy elements<br>• History: used in 'Fat Man', the second atomic bomb ever used in warfare<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• The element that defined the 'Atomic Age' and cold war geopolitics<br>• Major health and environmental priority due to its extreme toxicity if inhaled<br>• Critical tool for deep-space exploration where solar energy is insufficient<br>• Fundamental for the study of the heaviest actinide metals and complex bonding<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Space Exploration — enabling missions beyond the outer solar system<br>• National Security — monitoring nuclear non-proliferation and safeguards<br>• Environmental Health — researching the migration of heavy metals in soil<br>• Material Science — studying exotic phase transitions and metallurgy",
    "system.americium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Am<br>• Atomic Number — 95<br>• A silvery-white radioactive actinide metal; tarnishes slowly in dry air<br>• Named after the 'Americas' (following the pattern of Europium)<br>• Most widely distributed transuranium element due to its use in smoke detectors<br>• Critical for specialized industrial gauges and neutron sources<br>• Produced primarily by the beta decay of Plutonium-241 in nuclear reactors<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 95 protons in the nucleus<br>• 95 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common isotope is Americium-241 (used in smoke detectors)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f⁷ 7s² (stable half-filled f-shell configuration)<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white luster; tarnishes to a dull grey upon exposure to moist air<br>• Boiling point — 2607°C (estimated)<br>• Melting point — 1176°C<br>• Moderate density (approx. 13.67 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity<br>• Exists in two allotropic forms: alpha (hexagonal) and beta (cubic)<br>• More malleable and ductile than uranium or neptunium<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: reacts with oxygen, steam, and most inorganic acids<br>• Exhibits multiple oxidation states: +2, +3, +4, +5, and +6 (+3 is most stable)<br>• Forms stable halides, oxides, and complex americyl salts (AmO₂⁺)<br>• Solutions of different oxidation states display distinct colors (e.g., pink, yellow, rose)<br>• Chemical behavior is very similar to the lanthanide element Europium<br>• Forms stable complexes with various organic ligands in nuclear processing<br><br><b>Americium Isotopes</b><br>• Americium has no stable isotopes; over 15 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Americium-241 (²⁴¹Am) — most significant and widely used isotope (half-life: 432 years)<br>• Americium-243 (²⁴³Am) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 7,370 years)<br>• Part of the artificial 'Neptunium series' of radioactive decay (via Np-237)<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Present in the environment only as a result of past nuclear testing and accidents<br>• Managed as a strictly controlled radioisotope in industry and research<br>• Considered a 'byproduct' actinide of the global nuclear fuel cycle<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced in nuclear reactors via successive neutron capture by Plutonium-239<br>• Extracted from spent nuclear fuel or aged plutonium stockpiles<br>• Purified via ion exchange and solvent extraction processes (e.g., DIAMEX)<br>• Metal produced by reduction of americium oxide with lanthanum or thorium<br><br><b>Applications of Americium</b><br>• Safety: Am-241 used in ionization-type smoke detectors (found in millions of homes)<br>• Industry: used in specialized gauges for measuring thickness and density of materials<br>• Research: mixed with beryllium to create portable neutron sources for oil well logging<br>• Space Tech: potential fuel for next-generation radioisotope thermoelectric generators<br>• Science: used as a target for synthesizing heavier transuranium elements (e.g., Moscovium)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• The most familiar 'synthetic' element to the general public due to home safety<br>• Critical tool for non-destructive industrial testing and geological exploration<br>• Major factor in long-term radioactive waste management (minor actinide)<br>• Fundamental for testing the stability of the half-filled 5f electron shell<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Public Safety — fire prevention and smoke detection technology<br>• Industry — precision manufacturing and quality control via gauges<br>• Energy — research into transmutation of minor actinides in nuclear waste<br>• Physics — study of alpha-particle interaction with gases and matter",
    "system.curium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Cm<br>• Atomic Number — 96<br>• A hard, dense, silvery-white radioactive actinide metal<br>• Named after Marie and Pierre Curie, pioneers in radioactivity research<br>• Glows with a distinct purple light in the dark due to extreme radioactivity<br>• Critical high-power energy source for specialized space missions<br>• Produced primarily by neutron bombardment of Plutonium in nuclear reactors<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 96 protons in the nucleus<br>• 96 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common isotope is Curium-244 (heat source for space RTGs)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f⁷ 6d¹ 7s² (stable half-filled f-shell configuration)<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery appearance; tarnishes rapidly in air to form an oxide layer<br>• Boiling point — 3110°C (estimated)<br>• Melting point — 1345°C (relatively high for a heavy actinide)<br>• High density (approx. 13.51 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity<br>• Exists in two allotropic forms: alpha (hexagonal) and beta (cubic)<br>• Harder than most of its neighboring actinides; brittle at room temperature<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: reacts with oxygen and water vapor instantly<br>• Exhibits stable +3 and +4 oxidation states (+3 is much more common/stable)<br>• Behaves chemically like a heavier version of Gadolinium (its lanthanide analog)<br>• Forms stable halides, oxides (Cm₂O₃, CmO₂), and complex curyl salts<br>• Solutions of Curium(III) display a characteristic pale yellow or colorless appearance<br>• Forms highly stable complexes with organic chelating agents (e.g., DTPA)<br><br><b>Curium Isotopes</b><br>• Curium has no stable isotopes; over 20 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Curium-244 (²⁴⁴Cm) — used in Alpha Particle X-ray Spectrometers (APXS)<br>• Curium-247 (²⁴⁷Cm) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 15.6 million years)<br>• Curium-242 (²⁴²Cm) — used in early space missions as a heat source<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized laboratories and waste<br>• Managed as a high-level radioactive byproduct of the nuclear fuel cycle<br>• Found in trace amounts in the vicinity of nuclear accident sites (e.g., Chernobyl)<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced in high-flux nuclear reactors via neutron irradiation of Plutonium-239<br>• Extracted from spent fuel or irradiated targets via complex chemical separation<br>• Purified via ion exchange and solvent extraction processes (e.g., TALSPEAK)<br>• Metal produced by reduction of curium fluoride with barium or lithium vapor<br><br><b>Applications of Curium</b><br>• Space Tech: Alpha Particle X-ray Spectrometer (APXS) used on Mars rovers<br>• Energy: potential fuel for next-generation, high-density RTGs for deep space<br>• Research: target material for synthesizing heavier actinides and transactinides<br>• Nuclear Physics: used to study the spontaneous fission of heavy nuclei<br>• Science: used as a source of neutrons when mixed with beryllium<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Essential for non-destructive chemical analysis of planetary surfaces (Mars/Moon)<br>• Critical tool for testing the 'actinide hypothesis' of chemical periodicity<br>• Major factor in long-term high-level nuclear waste management and safety<br>• Fundamental for the study of the stability of the half-filled 5f electron shell<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Planetary Science — determining the chemical composition of other worlds<br>• Nuclear Waste Management — researching the long-term behavior of heavy actinides<br>• Aerospace — power sources and analytical instruments for space probes<br>• Physics — study of spontaneous fission and heavy-ion reactions",
    "system.berkelium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Bk<br>• Atomic Number — 97<br>• A soft, silvery-white radioactive transuranium actinide metal<br>• Named after the city of 'Berkeley' (University of California), where it was discovered<br>• Extremely rare: produced in milligram quantities in high-flux nuclear reactors<br>• Critical target material for synthesizing new superheavy elements (e.g., Tennessine)<br>• Highly radioactive; all isotopes have relatively short half-lives<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 97 protons in the nucleus<br>• 97 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common isotope is Berkelium-249 (used for element synthesis)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f⁹ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery appearance; exists in two allotropic forms: alpha (hexagonal) and beta (cubic)<br>• Boiling point — 2627°C (estimated)<br>• Melting point — 986°C (relatively low for a heavy actinide)<br>• Moderate density (approx. 14.78 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity<br>• Soft metal with a crystal structure similar to curium<br>• Volatilizes easily at high temperatures; samples self-heat significantly<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: reacts with oxygen and moisture to form Berkelium(III/IV) oxides<br>• Exhibits stable +3 and +4 oxidation states (+3 is more common/stable)<br>• Behaves chemically like a mix of Curium and Terbium (its lanthanide analog)<br>• Forms stable halides, hydroxides, and complex berkelyl salts<br>• Solutions of Berkelium(III) display a characteristic yellow or orange-red color<br>• First actinide to display a stable +4 state in aqueous solutions under normal conditions<br><br><b>Berkelium Isotopes</b><br>• Berkelium has no stable isotopes; over 10 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Berkelium-249 (²⁴⁹Bk) — most significant isotope for scientific research (half-life: 330 days)<br>• Berkelium-247 (²⁴⁷Bk) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 1,380 years)<br>• Berkelium-245 (²⁴⁵Bk) — used in specialized nuclear physics experiments<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized research centers (e.g., ORNL)<br>• Managed as a strictly controlled, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Never found in the general environment or as a byproduct of standard nuclear fuel<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced in high-flux nuclear reactors via neutron bombardment of Curium-244 or Americium-241<br>• Requires years of irradiation followed by complex chemical separation (e.g., Cation Exchange)<br>• Purified via specialized ion exchange and solvent extraction processes<br>• Metal produced by reduction of berkelium fluoride with lithium or barium vapor<br><br><b>Applications of Berkelium</b><br>• Science: primary target for synthesizing Element 117 (Tennessine)<br>• Research: used to study the chemical trends of the late actinide series<br>• Nuclear Chemistry: investigation of heavy element decay and nuclear stability<br>• Specialized tracing: study of high-valent actinide behavior in chemical systems<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Essential 'building block' for expanding the periodic table into the 7th row<br>• Critical for understanding the transition from +3 to +4 oxidation states in actinides<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced quantum chemical models of heavy atoms<br>• Represents the limit of macroscopic quantities for synthetic elements<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Nuclear Physics — discovering new superheavy elements at the 'Island of Stability'<br>• Material Science — researching the bonding of 5f electrons in complex systems<br>• Theoretical Chemistry — testing relativistic and electron correlation effects",
    "system.californium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Cf<br>• Atomic Number — 98<br>• A dense, silvery-white radioactive transuranium metal<br>• Named after 'California' (University of California, Berkeley), where it was discovered<br>• Famous as a powerful and portable source of neutrons (via spontaneous fission)<br>• Used in critical life-saving medical treatments and high-stakes industrial sensing<br>• One of the most expensive and specialized elements produced by humanity<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 98 protons in the nucleus<br>• 98 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common isotope is Californium-252 (extraordinary neutron emitter)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁰ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery appearance; soft and malleable (can be cut with a razor)<br>• Boiling point — 1472°C (relatively low for a metal)<br>• Melting point — 900°C<br>• Moderate density (approx. 15.1 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity<br>• Exists in two allotropic forms: alpha (hexagonal) and beta (cubic)<br>• Glows with an eerie blue-white light due to intense self-irradiation<br>• Highly volatile: vaporizes easily even at moderate temperatures<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: reacts with moisture and oxygen to form Californium(III) oxide (Cf₂O₃)<br>• Exhibits multiple oxidation states: +2, +3, and +4 (+3 is the most stable)<br>• Behaves chemically like its lanthanide analog, Dysprosium<br>• Forms stable halides, hydroxides, and complex californyl salts<br>• Solutions of Californium(III) display a characteristic green or yellow-green color<br>• First element in the series to show a stable +2 oxidation state in specialized conditions<br><br><b>Californium Isotopes</b><br>• Californium has no stable isotopes; over 20 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Californium-252 (²⁵²Cf) — most significant industrial isotope (half-life: 2.645 years)<br>• Californium-251 (²⁵¹At) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: approx. 900 years)<br>• Californium-249 (²⁴⁹Cf) — used for specialized chemical and spectroscopic research<br>• Californium-252 is unique for its high rate of 'spontaneous fission' (releasing neutrons)<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized high-flux reactors<br>• Managed as a strictly controlled, high-value radioisotope for industry and medicine<br>• Trace amounts produced in supernovas but decay long before reaching Earth<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced in high-flux nuclear reactors via successive neutron capture by Curium or Plutonium<br>• Requires years of irradiation followed by complex chemical separation (e.g., Cation Exchange)<br>• Purified via specialized ion exchange and solvent extraction processes<br>• Metal produced by reduction of californium oxide with lanthanum or thorium vapor<br><br><b>Applications of Californium</b><br>• Medicine: Californium-252 used for targeted brachytherapy for cervical and brain cancer<br>• Energy: portable neutron source for starting up nuclear reactors on demand<br>• Industry: neutron gauges for detecting oil and water in underground wells<br>• Security: portable neutron scanners for detecting explosives and drugs at borders<br>• Research: target material for synthesizing heaviest elements (e.g., Oganesson)<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Enabling material for life-saving cancer treatments where other methods fail<br>• Critical tool for non-destructive testing of aircraft parts and space components<br>• Essential for discovering the heaviest element in the periodic table (Oganesson)<br>• Fundamental for the study of the transition to late actinide behavior<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — advanced oncology and targeted neutron therapy<br>• Security — advanced sensing and non-destructive detection technology<br>• Energy — nuclear reactor safety and startup procedures<br>• Planetary Science — mapping the chemical composition of planetary surfaces",
    "system.einsteinium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Es<br>• Atomic Number — 99<br>• A soft, silvery-white radioactive transuranium metal; first discovered in H-bomb debris<br>• Named after the legendary physicist Albert Einstein<br>• Produced in minute, microgram quantities in specialized high-flux nuclear reactors<br>• Extremely radioactive; all isotopes have relatively short half-lives<br>• Primarily of fundamental scientific interest due to its extreme scarcity<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 99 protons in the nucleus<br>• 99 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common isotope is Einsteinium-253 (half-life: 20 days)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹¹ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery appearance; glows with an intense blue light due to extreme radioactivity<br>• Boiling point — 996°C (estimated)<br>• Melting point — 860°C (relatively low for a metal)<br>• Moderate density (approx. 8.84 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity<br>• Soft and malleable; crystal structure is face-centered cubic (FCC)<br>• Volatilizes rapidly: samples can vaporize themselves due to radioactive heating<br>• Paramagnetic at room temperature<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: reacts with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits stable +2 and +3 oxidation states (+3 is more common/stable)<br>• Behaves chemically like its lanthanide analog, Holmium<br>• Forms stable halides, oxides, and complex salts in specialized conditions<br>• Solutions of Einsteinium(III) display a characteristic pale pink or yellow color<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its chemical bonding and spectra<br><br><b>Einsteinium Isotopes</b><br>• Einsteinium has no stable isotopes; over 15 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Einsteinium-253 (²⁵³Es) — used for most chemical and physics research<br>• Einsteinium-254 (²⁵⁴Es) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 471.7 days)<br>• Originally discovered in the fallout of the 'Ivy Mike' hydrogen bomb test (1952)<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Found only in highly specialized nuclear research facilities (e.g., ORNL in USA)<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental physics<br>• Global supply at any moment is measured in micrograms (millionths of a gram)<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced in high-flux nuclear reactors via successive neutron capture by Curium or Californium<br>• Requires years of irradiation followed by extremely complex chemical separation<br>• Purified via specialized ion exchange and solvent extraction processes<br>• Metal produced by reduction of einsteinium fluoride with lithium or barium vapor<br><br><b>Applications of Einsteinium</b><br>• Science: primary target for synthesizing Element 101 (Mendelevium)<br>• Research: used to study the chemical trends of the heaviest actinides<br>• Nuclear Physics: investigation of heavy element decay and nuclear structure<br>• Spectroscopy: used to study the relativistic effects on the atomic electron shells<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Essential 'building block' for reaching the trans-actinide elements<br>• Critical for understanding the limits of the periodic table and atomic stability<br>• Powerful tool for testing the most advanced quantum mechanical models<br>• Represents the extreme limit of elements that can be produced in visible quantities<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — testing the extreme limits of the Standard Model<br>• Nuclear Chemistry — exploring the chemistry of short-lived, heavy atoms<br>• History — its discovery marked the beginning of the 'Transuranium Age'<br>• High-Energy Physics — study of nuclear structure under extreme conditions",
    "system.fermium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Fm<br>• Atomic Number — 100<br>• A highly radioactive transuranium element; the heaviest element producible by neutron bombardment<br>• Named after the Nobel laureate Enrico Fermi, pioneer of nuclear reactors<br>• Produced in vanishingly small quantities (nanograms) in specialized reactors<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to a few atoms at a time<br>• Represents the absolute limit of the 'neutron capture' method of element synthesis<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 100 protons in the nucleus<br>• 100 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Fermium-257 (half-life: 100.5 days)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹² 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a silvery metal at room temperature (never seen in bulk form)<br>• Boiling point — unknown (estimated to be relatively low)<br>• Melting point — 1527°C (estimated)<br>• Density and conductivity are currently unknown but predicted to be metallic<br>• Predicted to have a face-centered cubic (FCC) crystal structure<br>• Studies are conducted on individual atoms or minute tracer amounts<br>• Vaporizes easily under even mild radioactive self-heating<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits stable +2 and +3 oxidation states (+3 is more common/stable)<br>• Behaves chemically like its lanthanide analog, Erbium<br>• Forms stable halides and complex ions in aqueous solutions (observed in tracers)<br>• Solutions of Fermium(III) are predicted to be pale pink or colorless<br>• Displays extreme relativistic effects in its electronic and chemical properties<br><br><b>Fermium Isotopes</b><br>• Fermium has no stable isotopes; over 20 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Fermium-257 (²⁵⁷Fm) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 100.5 days)<br>• Fermium-255 (²⁵⁵Fm) — originally discovered in H-bomb debris (half-life: 20 hours)<br>• Fermium-258 — famous for its extremely fast spontaneous fission rate<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized high-flux reactors<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Atomic Number 100 marks the end of elements that occur even transiently in reactors<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced in high-flux nuclear reactors via massive neutron capture by Plutonium or Curium<br>• Requires years of irradiation followed by extremely complex chemical separation<br>• Purified via specialized ion exchange and micro-chromatography processes<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk quantities due to short half-lives<br><br><b>Applications of Fermium</b><br>• Science: used as a tracer to study the properties of the heaviest actinides<br>• Research: investigation of the 'spontaneous fission' barrier in heavy nuclei<br>• Nuclear Physics: used to probe the limits of the periodic table<br>• Theoretical Research: testing relativistic effects on atomic structure<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Represents the 'finish line' for neutron-based element synthesis<br>• Critical for understanding the rapid decay pathways of the heaviest nuclei<br>• Powerful tool for testing the ultimate limits of chemical periodicity<br>• Fundamental for the study of the transition to the lawrencium/nobelium series<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability<br>• High-Energy Chemistry — studying the chemistry of individual atoms<br>• Nuclear History — discovery in the first hydrogen bomb explosion fallout<br>• Mathematical Physics — modeling relativistic electron shells in heavy atoms",
    "system.mendelevium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Md<br>• Atomic Number — 101<br>• A highly radioactive transuranium actinide metal; the first element to be produced atom-by-atom<br>• Named after Dmitri Mendeleev, the father of the periodic table<br>• Produced in minute quantities in particle accelerators (typically by bombarding Einsteinium)<br>• Extremely rare and short-lived; primarily used for fundamental scientific research<br>• Represents a significant milestone in the synthesis of the heaviest elements<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 101 protons in the nucleus<br>• 101 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Mendelevium-258 (half-life: approx. 51 days)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹³ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a silvery-white or grey metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — unknown (estimated to be low)<br>• Melting point — 827°C (estimated)<br>• Density and conductivity are currently unknown but predicted to be metallic<br>• Study is limited to tracer amounts due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a face-centered cubic (FCC) crystal structure<br>• Volatilizes easily at moderate temperatures<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits stable +2 and +3 oxidation states (+3 is more stable in solution)<br>• Behaves chemically like its lanthanide analog, Thulium<br>• Forms stable halides and complex ions in aqueous solutions (observed in tracers)<br>• Solutions of Mendelevium(III) display properties similar to other heavy actinides<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its electronic and chemical properties<br><br><b>Mendelevium Isotopes</b><br>• Mendelevium has no stable isotopes; over 15 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Mendelevium-258 (²⁵⁸Md) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 51.5 days)<br>• Mendelevium-256 (²⁵⁶Md) — the isotope originally discovered in 1955<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of rare targets like Einsteinium-253<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of lighter actinides in cyclotrons<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Einsteinium-253 with alpha particles<br>• Purified via specialized ion exchange and micro-chromatography processes<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme scarcity<br><br><b>Applications of Mendelevium</b><br>• Science: used as a tracer to study the chemistry of individual heavy atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the electronic structure of the heaviest actinides<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the limits of atomic stability<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic and correlation effects in heavy atoms<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• The first element to be synthesized one atom at a time (historic achievement)<br>• Critical for verifying the completion of the actinide series (pre-103)<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced quantum chemical models of heavy nuclei<br>• Named in honor of the architect of the periodic system itself<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability<br>• History of Science — symbol of international cooperation in element discovery<br>• Mathematical Physics — modeling relativistic electron shells in heavy atoms",
    "system.nobelium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — No<br>• Atomic Number — 102<br>• A highly radioactive transuranium actinide metal; produced only in minute quantities<br>• Named after Alfred Nobel, the inventor of dynamite and founder of the Nobel Prizes<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding lighter elements with heavy ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to a few atoms at a time<br>• One of the last members of the actinide series, displaying unique chemical behavior<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 102 protons in the nucleus<br>• 102 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Nobelium-259 (half-life: approx. 58 minutes)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 7s² (completely filled f-shell configuration)<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (actinide series) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a silvery-white or grey metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — unknown (predicted to be relatively low)<br>• Melting point — 827°C (estimated)<br>• Density and conductivity are unknown but predicted to be metallic<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity<br>• Predicted to have a face-centered cubic (FCC) crystal structure<br>• Volatility is higher than that of the earlier actinides<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Unique among actinides for its very stable +2 oxidation state in solution<br>• Behaves chemically like its lanthanide analog, Ytterbium (stable +2 state)<br>• Forms stable halides and complex ions (observed in tracer studies)<br>• Solutions of Nobelium(II) display properties distinct from most other actinides<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its electronic and chemical properties<br><br><b>Nobelium Isotopes</b><br>• Nobelium has no stable isotopes; over 10 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Nobelium-259 (²⁵⁹No) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 58 minutes)<br>• Nobelium-255 (²⁵⁵No) — commonly used in nuclear and chemical research<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of specialized targets like Curium or Californium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of actinides in cyclotrons or linear accelerators<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Curium-244 or -248 with Carbon or Neon ions<br>• Purified via specialized ion exchange and gas-phase chromatography processes<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Nobelium</b><br>• Science: used as a tracer to study the chemical properties of heavy atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 'filling' of the 5f electron shell<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the barrier to spontaneous fission<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on atomic orbitals<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the transition from +3 to +2 stable oxidation states<br>• Powerful tool for testing the 'actinide hypothesis' at its final stages<br>• Represents a challenge in element discovery due to historic priority disputes<br>• Named in honor of the philanthropist who promoted global scientific excellence<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability<br>• International Science — focus of cooperation between USA, Russia, and Europe<br>• Mathematical Physics — modeling the behavior of fully-filled f-shells",
    "system.lawrencium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Lr<br>• Atomic Number — 103<br>• A highly radioactive transuranium metal; the final member of the actinide series<br>• Named after Ernest Lawrence, inventor of the cyclotron (particle accelerator)<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding lighter elements with heavy ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to a few atoms at a time<br>• Represents the 'finish line' of the actinides, marking the transition to transactinides<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 103 protons in the nucleus<br>• 103 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Lawrencium-266 (half-life: approx. 11 hours)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 7s² 7p¹ (unique p-orbital electron addition)<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 3 (final actinide) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a silvery-white or grey metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — unknown (predicted to be relatively high)<br>• Melting point — 1627°C (estimated)<br>• Density and conductivity are unknown but predicted to be metallic<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity<br>• Predicted to have a face-centered cubic (FCC) or hexagonal structure<br>• Displaying significant thermal instability during experimental handling<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits a very stable +3 oxidation state in aqueous solution<br>• Behaves chemically like its lanthanide analog, Lutetium (stable +3 state)<br>• Forms stable halides and complex ions (observed in gas-phase chemistry)<br>• First element predicted to have a stable p-orbital valence electron in its ground state<br>• Displays extreme relativistic effects in its electronic and chemical properties<br><br><b>Lawrencium Isotopes</b><br>• Lawrencium has no stable isotopes; over 10 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Lawrencium-266 (²⁶⁶Lr) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 11 hours)<br>• Lawrencium-262 (²⁶²Lr) — commonly used in nuclear physics research<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or electron capture<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of specialized targets like Americium or Berkelium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of actinides in cyclotrons<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Californium-249 with Boron ions<br>• Purified via specialized ion exchange and gas-phase chromatography processes<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme scarcity<br><br><b>Applications of Lawrencium</b><br>• Science: used as a tracer to study the properties of the heaviest atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the end-of-series electronic shell behavior<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the transition to transactinide elements<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on p-orbital electrons<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Marks the successful completion of the actinide series (f-shell filling)<br>• Critical for understanding the transition to Group 4 transition metals<br>• Powerful tool for testing the most advanced relativistic quantum models<br>• Named in honor of the man whose invention made its discovery possible<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of the periodic table<br>• Particle Accelerator Physics — pushing the limits of heavy-ion fusion<br>• Mathematical Chemistry — modeling the behavior of 7p valence electrons",
    "system.rutherfordium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Rf<br>• Atomic Number — 104<br>• A highly radioactive transuranium transition metal; the first transactinide element<br>• Named after Lord Ernest Rutherford, the father of nuclear physics<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy elements with lighter ones<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Represents the first member of the 6d transition metal series (Group 4)<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 104 protons in the nucleus<br>• 104 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Rutherfordium-265 (half-life: approx. 13 hours)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d² 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 4 (transition metals) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, silvery metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — unknown (estimated to be very high)<br>• Melting point — 2100°C (estimated)<br>• High density (approx. 23 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a hexagonal close-packed (HCP) crystal structure<br>• Displaying significant relativistic contractions in its atomic radius<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits a stable +4 oxidation state, similar to Hafnium and Zirconium<br>• Behaves chemically like its lighter Group 4 homologs (Zirconium, Hafnium)<br>• Forms stable halides (e.g., RfCl₄) and complex ions in acidic solutions<br>• First transactinide element to have its chemistry confirmed via gas-phase studies<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its electronic and bonding properties<br><br><b>Rutherfordium Isotopes</b><br>• Rutherfordium has no stable isotopes; over 15 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Rutherfordium-265 (²⁶⁵Rf) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 13 hours)<br>• Rutherfordium-263 (²⁶³Rf) — commonly used in chemical research<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Plutonium or Californium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of actinides in cyclotrons<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Plutonium-242 with Neon ions<br>• Purified via specialized fast chemical separation and gas-phase chromatography<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme scarcity<br><br><b>Applications of Rutherfordium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of superheavy atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 6d electron shell behavior<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the 'island of stability' vicinity<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on transition metal bonding<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Marks the first entry into the transactinide (superheavy transition metal) region<br>• Critical for verifying the periodic law beyond the actinide series<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum mechanical models<br>• Named in honor of the scientist who discovered the atomic nucleus<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the stability of extremely heavy nuclei<br>• Particle Accelerator Physics — pushing the limits of heavy-ion fusion reactions",
    "system.dubnium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Db<br>• Atomic Number — 105<br>• A highly radioactive transuranium transition metal; part of the transactinide series<br>• Named after 'Dubna', Russia, the site of the Joint Institute for Nuclear Research (JINR)<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy elements with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 5, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Tantalum<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 105 protons in the nucleus<br>• 105 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Dubnium-268 (half-life: approx. 16–32 hours)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d³ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 5 (transition metals) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, silvery-white metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — unknown (estimated to be extremely high)<br>• Melting point — unknown (predicted to be high)<br>• High density (approx. 29 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a body-centered cubic (BCC) crystal structure<br>• Displaying significant relativistic effects on its physical properties<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits a stable +5 oxidation state, similar to Tantalum and Niobium<br>• Behaves chemically like its lighter Group 5 homologs (Niobium, Tantalum)<br>• Forms stable halides (e.g., DbCl₅) and complex anions in acidic solutions<br>• Chemistry studied via automated gas-phase and liquid chromatography systems<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Dubnium Isotopes</b><br>• Dubnium has no stable isotopes; over 10 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Dubnium-268 (²⁶⁸Db) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: approx. 16–32 hours)<br>• Dubnium-262 (²⁶²Db) — commonly used in nuclear physics and chemistry research<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Americium or Berkelium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of actinides in cyclotrons<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Americium-243 with Neon ions<br>• Purified via specialized automated chemical separation and gas-phase systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Dubnium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of transactinide atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 6d transition metal chemistry<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying nuclear shell effects in heavy nuclei<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on heavy transition metals<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the chemical trends in Group 5 beyond Tantalum<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• Represents a historic era of competition and eventual cooperation in discovery<br>• Named in honor of the major research center in the field of superheavy elements<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability<br>• International Science — symbol of scientific collaboration between nations",
    "system.seaborgium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Sg<br>• Atomic Number — 106<br>• A highly radioactive transuranium transition metal; part of the transactinide series<br>• Named after Glenn T. Seaborg, the first living person to have an element named after him<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy elements with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 6, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Tungsten<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 106 protons in the nucleus<br>• 106 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Seaborgium-271 (half-life: approx. 1.9 minutes)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d⁴ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 6 (transition metals) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, silvery-white metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — unknown (estimated to be extremely high)<br>• Melting point — unknown (predicted to be high)<br>• High density (approx. 35 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a body-centered cubic (BCC) crystal structure<br>• Displaying significant relativistic effects on its physical properties<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits a stable +6 oxidation state, similar to Tungsten and Molybdenum<br>• Behaves chemically like its lighter Group 6 homologs (Molybdenum, Tungsten)<br>• Forms stable oxychlorides (e.g., SgO₂Cl₂) and complex anions in acidic solutions<br>• Chemistry studied via automated gas-phase chromatography systems<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Seaborgium Isotopes</b><br>• Seaborgium has no stable isotopes; over 10 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Seaborgium-271 (²⁷¹Sg) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: approx. 1.9 minutes)<br>• Seaborgium-265 (²⁶⁵Sg) — commonly used in nuclear physics research<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Californium or Curium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of actinides in cyclotrons<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Californium-249 with Neon ions<br>• Purified via specialized automated chemical separation and gas-phase systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Seaborgium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of transactinide atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 6d transition metal chemistry<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying nuclear shell effects in heavy nuclei<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on heavy transition metals<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the chemical trends in Group 6 beyond Tungsten<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• First element to be named after a person who was still alive at the time<br>• Named in honor of the major contributor to the actinide concept<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability<br>• Nuclear Chemistry — exploring the chemistry of individual atoms",
    "system.bohrium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Bh<br>• Atomic Number — 107<br>• A highly radioactive transactinide metal; part of the transition metal series<br>• Named after Niels Bohr, pioneer of atomic structure and quantum mechanics<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy targets with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 7, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Rhenium<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 107 protons in the nucleus<br>• 107 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Bohrium-270 (half-life: approx. 2.4 minutes)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d⁵ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 7 (transition metals) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, silvery-white metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — unknown (estimated to be extremely high)<br>• Melting point — unknown (predicted to be high)<br>• High density (approx. 37 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a hexagonal close-packed (HCP) crystal structure<br>• Displaying significant relativistic effects on its physical properties<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits a stable +7 oxidation state, similar to Rhenium and Manganese<br>• Behaves chemically like its lighter Group 7 homologs (Manganese, Rhenium)<br>• Forms stable oxycompounds (e.g., BhO₃Cl) and complex anions in acidic solutions<br>• Chemistry studied via automated gas-phase chromatography systems<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Bohrium Isotopes</b><br>• Bohrium has no stable isotopes; over 10 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Bohrium-270 (²⁷⁰Bh) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: approx. 2.4 minutes)<br>• Bohrium-262 (²⁶²Bh) — commonly used in nuclear physics research<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Berkelium or Californium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of actinides in cyclotrons<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Berkelium-249 with Neon ions<br>• Purified via specialized automated chemical separation and gas-phase systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Bohrium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of transactinide atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 6d transition metal chemistry<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying nuclear shell effects in heavy nuclei<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on heavy transition metals<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the chemical trends in Group 7 beyond Rhenium<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• Named in honor of one of the most influential physicists of the 20th century<br>• Key element for testing the validity of the Periodic Law at its extreme end<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability<br>• Quantum Mechanics — testing the Bohr model at extreme atomic numbers",
    "system.hassium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Hs<br>• Atomic Number — 108<br>• A highly radioactive transactinide metal; part of the transition metal series<br>• Named after 'Hassia', the Latin name for the German state of Hesse<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy targets with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 8, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Osmium<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 108 protons in the nucleus<br>• 108 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Hassium-276 (half-life: approx. 1.1 hours)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d⁶ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 8 (transition metals) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, silvery-white metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — unknown (estimated to be high)<br>• Melting point — unknown (predicted to be high)<br>• High density (approx. 41 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a hexagonal close-packed (HCP) crystal structure<br>• Displaying significant relativistic effects on its physical properties<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits a stable +8 oxidation state, similar to Osmium and Ruthenium<br>• Behaves chemically like its lighter Group 8 homologs (Ruthenium, Osmium)<br>• Forms stable tetroxides (e.g., HsO₄), which are volatile like OsO₄<br>• First transactinide to have its chemistry confirmed via gas-phase studies of its oxide<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Hassium Isotopes</b><br>• Hassium has no stable isotopes; over 10 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Hassium-276 (²⁷⁶Hs) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: approx. 1.1 hours)<br>• Hassium-270 (²⁷⁰Hs) — a 'doubly magic' nucleus, providing extreme stability info<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Curium or Lead<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of targets in cyclotrons or linear accelerators<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Curium-248 with Magnesium ions<br>• Purified via specialized automated chemical separation and gas-phase systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Hassium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of transactinide atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 6d transition metal chemistry<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the 'Island of Stability' vicinity<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on heavy transition metals<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the chemical trends in Group 8 beyond Osmium<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• Doubly magic isotope Hs-270 is a landmark for nuclear structure theory<br>• Key element for testing the volatility of heavy metal oxides<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability<br>• Material Science — researching the bonding of 6d electrons in oxides",
    "system.meitnerium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Mt<br>• Atomic Number — 109<br>• A highly radioactive transactinide metal; part of the transition metal series<br>• Named after Lise Meitner, a pioneer in nuclear fission and physics<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy targets with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 9, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Iridium<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 109 protons in the nucleus<br>• 109 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Meitnerium-278 (half-life: approx. 8 seconds)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d⁷ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 9 (transition metals) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, silvery-white metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — unknown (estimated to be high)<br>• Melting point — unknown (predicted to be high)<br>• High density (approx. 35 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a face-centered cubic (FCC) crystal structure<br>• Displaying significant relativistic effects on its physical properties<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits stable +3, +4, and +6 oxidation states (predicted based on trends)<br>• Behaves chemically like its lighter Group 9 homologs (Cobalt, Rhodium, Iridium)<br>• Forms stable halides and complex ions (predicted but not yet confirmed)<br>• Chemistry is exceptionally difficult to study due to very short half-lives<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Meitnerium Isotopes</b><br>• Meitnerium has no stable isotopes; over 10 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Meitnerium-278 (²⁷⁸Mt) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: approx. 8 seconds)<br>• Meitnerium-266 (²⁶⁶Mt) — originally discovered in 1982<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Bismuth or Lead bombarded with Iron<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of targets in linear accelerators<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Bismuth-209 with Iron ions<br>• Purified via specialized fast automated chemical separation systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Meitnerium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of transactinide atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 6d transition metal chemistry<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the barrier to spontaneous fission<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on heavy transition metals<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the chemical trends in Group 9 beyond Iridium<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• Named in honor of the physicist who provided the first theoretical explanation of fission<br>• Key element for testing the limits of the periodic table structure<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability",
    "system.darmstadtium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ds<br>• Atomic Number — 110<br>• A highly radioactive transactinide metal; part of the transition metal series<br>• Named after 'Darmstadt', Germany, the home of the GSI research center<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy targets with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 10, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Platinum<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 110 protons in the nucleus<br>• 110 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Darmstadtium-281 (half-life: approx. 11 seconds)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d⁸ 7s²<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 10 (transition metals) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, silvery-white metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — unknown (estimated to be high)<br>• Melting point — unknown (predicted to be high)<br>• High density (approx. 34.8 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a body-centered cubic (BCC) crystal structure<br>• Displaying significant relativistic effects on its physical properties<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits stable +2, +4, and +6 oxidation states (predicted based on trends)<br>• Behaves chemically like its lighter Group 10 homologs (Nickel, Palladium, Platinum)<br>• Forms stable halides and complex ions (predicted but not yet confirmed)<br>• Chemistry is exceptionally difficult to study due to very short half-lives<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Darmstadtium Isotopes</b><br>• Darmstadtium has no stable isotopes; over 10 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Darmstadtium-281 (²⁸¹Ds) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: approx. 11 seconds)<br>• Darmstadtium-267 (²⁶⁷Ds) — originally discovered in 1994<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Lead bombarded with Nickel<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of targets in linear accelerators<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Lead-208 with Nickel ions<br>• Purified via specialized fast automated chemical separation systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Darmstadtium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of transactinide atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 6d transition metal chemistry<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the barrier to spontaneous fission<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on heavy transition metals<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the chemical trends in Group 10 beyond Platinum<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• Named in honor of the city where the GSI Helmholtz Centre for Heavy Ion Research is located<br>• Key element for testing the limits of the periodic table structure<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability",
    "system.roentgenium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Rg<br>• Atomic Number — 111<br>• A highly radioactive transactinide metal; part of the transition metal series<br>• Named after Wilhelm Roentgen, the discoverer of X-rays<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy targets with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 11, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Gold<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 111 protons in the nucleus<br>• 111 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Roentgenium-282 (half-life: approx. 100 seconds)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d⁹ 7s² (predicted)<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 11 (transition metals) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, silvery or golden metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — unknown (estimated to be high)<br>• Melting point — unknown (predicted to be high)<br>• High density (approx. 28.7 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a body-centered cubic (BCC) crystal structure<br>• Displaying significant relativistic contractions in its atomic structure<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits stable +3 oxidation state, similar to Gold (predicted)<br>• Behaves chemically like its lighter Group 11 homologs (Copper, Silver, Gold)<br>• Predicted to be a noble metal with low chemical reactivity in bulk<br>• Chemistry is exceptionally difficult to study due to very short half-lives<br>• Displays extreme relativistic effects in its valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Roentgenium Isotopes</b><br>• Roentgenium has no stable isotopes; over 7 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Roentgenium-282 (²⁸²Rg) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 100 seconds)<br>• Roentgenium-272 (²⁷²Rg) — originally discovered in 1994<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Bismuth bombarded with Nickel<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of targets in linear accelerators<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Bismuth-209 with Nickel-64 ions<br>• Purified via specialized fast automated chemical separation systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Roentgenium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of transactinide atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 6d transition metal chemistry<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the barrier to spontaneous fission<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on heavy transition metals<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the chemical trends in Group 11 beyond Gold<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• Named in honor of the physicist who revolutionized medical diagnosis with X-rays<br>• Key element for testing the limits of the periodic table structure<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability",
    "system.copernicium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Cn<br>• Atomic Number — 112<br>• A highly radioactive transactinide metal; predicted to be a volatile liquid<br>• Named after Nicolaus Copernicus, the astronomer who proposed the heliocentric model<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy targets with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 12, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Mercury<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 112 protons in the nucleus<br>• 112 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Copernicium-285 (half-life: approx. 29 seconds)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d¹⁰ 7s² (fully filled shells)<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 12 (transition metals) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a volatile metal, potentially liquid at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — approx. 67°C (exceptionally low for a metal)<br>• Melting point — approx. 10°C (predicted to be liquid near room temp)<br>• Moderate density (approx. 14 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms using gas-phase chromatography<br>• Predicted to behave like a very heavy noble gas in some physical aspects<br>• Displaying extreme relativistic contractions in its electronic shells<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly volatile: behaves more like a noble gas than its neighbor Mercury<br>• Exhibits stable +2 oxidation state (predicted based on trends)<br>• Behaves chemically like a very noble version of Mercury<br>• Forms stable alloys (amalgams) with Gold (observed in tracer studies)<br>• Chemistry studied via automated gas-phase chromatography on gold surfaces<br>• Displays the most extreme relativistic effects in Group 12<br><br><b>Copernicium Isotopes</b><br>• Copernicium has no stable isotopes; over 5 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Copernicium-285 (²⁸⁵Cn) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 29 seconds)<br>• Copernicium-277 (²⁷⁷Cn) — originally discovered in 1996<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Lead bombarded with Zinc<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of targets in linear accelerators<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Lead-208 with Zinc-70 ions<br>• Purified via specialized automated gas-phase chromatography systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Copernicium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of transactinide atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 6d shell closure and noble behavior<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the 'Island of Stability' vicinity<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing the limits of the periodic law<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the transition from metallic to noble behavior<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• Named in honor of the scientist who changed our view of the universe<br>• Key element for testing the validity of the periodic table in the superheavy region<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability",
    "system.nihonium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Nh<br>• Atomic Number — 113<br>• A highly radioactive transactinide metal; the first element discovered in Asia<br>• Named after 'Nihon', the Japanese name for Japan<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy targets with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 13, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Thallium<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 113 protons in the nucleus<br>• 113 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Nihonium-286 (half-life: approx. 20 seconds)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d¹⁰ 7s² 7p¹ (predicted)<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 13 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, silvery-white metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — approx. 1100°C (estimated)<br>• Melting point — approx. 430°C (estimated)<br>• High density (approx. 16 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a hexagonal close-packed (HCP) crystal structure<br>• Displaying significant relativistic effects on its atomic radius<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits stable +1 and +3 oxidation states (+1 is predicted to be more stable)<br>• Behaves chemically like its lighter Group 13 homologs (Indium, Thallium)<br>• Forms stable halides and complex ions (predicted based on trends)<br>• Chemistry is exceptionally difficult to study due to very short half-lives<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Nihonium Isotopes</b><br>• Nihonium has no stable isotopes; over 8 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Nihonium-286 (²⁸⁶Nh) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 20 seconds)<br>• Nihonium-278 (²⁷⁸Nh) — originally discovered at RIKEN, Japan (2004)<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Bismuth or Americium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of targets in linear accelerators<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Bismuth-209 with Zinc-70 ions (at RIKEN)<br>• Purified via specialized fast automated chemical separation systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Nihonium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of superheavy atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 7p electron shell behavior<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the limits of atomic stability<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on heavy group 13 elements<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Historic achievement for Asian science (first element discovered in Japan)<br>• Critical for understanding the chemical trends in Group 13 beyond Thallium<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• Key element for testing the stability of the 7th row of the periodic table<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability",
    "system.flerovium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Fl<br>• Atomic Number — 114<br>• A highly radioactive transactinide metal; predicted to have noble-like properties<br>• Named after the Flerov Laboratory of Nuclear Reactions in Dubna, Russia<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy targets with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 14, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Lead<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 114 protons in the nucleus<br>• 114 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Flerovium-289 (half-life: approx. 2.6 seconds)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d¹⁰ 7s² 7p² (predicted)<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 14 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, volatile metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — approx. 150°C (exceptionally low for a Group 14 metal)<br>• Melting point — approx. 70°C (predicted to have a low melting point)<br>• High density (approx. 14 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms using gas-phase chromatography<br>• Predicted to behave like a noble metal or even a noble gas in some aspects<br>• Displaying extreme relativistic effects on its electronic structure<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly volatile: predicted to be less reactive than its neighbor Lead<br>• Exhibits stable +2 and +4 oxidation states (+2 is predicted to be more stable)<br>• Behaves chemically like a very noble version of Lead<br>• Forms stable halides and complex ions (observed in tracer studies)<br>• Chemistry studied via automated gas-phase chromatography on gold surfaces<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Flerovium Isotopes</b><br>• Flerovium has no stable isotopes; over 5 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Flerovium-289 (²⁸⁹Fl) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 2.6 seconds)<br>• Flerovium-285 (²⁸⁵Fl) — originally discovered in 1998<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Plutonium bombarded with Calcium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of targets in linear accelerators<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Plutonium-244 with Calcium-48 ions<br>• Purified via specialized automated gas-phase chromatography systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Flerovium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of superheavy atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the shell closure at Z=114 (predicted magic number)<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the 'Island of Stability' core<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing the limits of the periodic law<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the stability of the 'Island of Stability' vicinity<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• Named in honor of Georgy Flerov, a giant of Soviet nuclear physics<br>• Key element for testing the transition from metallic to noble-like behavior<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability",
    "system.moscovium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Mc<br>• Atomic Number — 115<br>• A highly radioactive transactinide metal; part of the p-block series<br>• Named after the Moscow region, where it was first synthesized<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy targets with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 15, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Bismuth<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 115 protons in the nucleus<br>• 115 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Moscovium-290 (half-life: approx. 0.65 seconds)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d¹⁰ 7s² 7p³ (predicted)<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 15 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, silvery-white metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — unknown (estimated to be high)<br>• Melting point — approx. 400°C (estimated)<br>• High density (approx. 13.5 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a body-centered cubic (BCC) crystal structure<br>• Displaying significant relativistic effects on its atomic radius<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits stable +1 and +3 oxidation states (+1 is predicted to be more stable)<br>• Behaves chemically like its lighter Group 15 homologs (Antimony, Bismuth)<br>• Forms stable halides and complex ions (predicted based on trends)<br>• Chemistry is exceptionally difficult to study due to sub-second half-lives<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Moscovium Isotopes</b><br>• Moscovium has no stable isotopes; over 4 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Moscovium-290 (²⁹⁰Mc) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 0.65 seconds)<br>• Moscovium-287 (²⁸⁷Mc) — originally discovered in 2003<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Americium bombarded with Calcium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of targets in linear accelerators<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Americium-243 with Calcium-48 ions<br>• Purified via specialized fast automated chemical separation systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Moscovium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of superheavy atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 7p electron shell behavior<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the limits of atomic stability<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on heavy p-block elements<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the chemical trends in Group 15 beyond Bismuth<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• Named in honor of the geographic region of its primary discovery center (JINR)<br>• Key element for testing the stability of the 7th row of the periodic table<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability",
    "system.livermorium.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Lv<br>• Atomic Number — 116<br>• A highly radioactive transactinide metal; part of the chalcogen series<br>• Named after the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in California, USA<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy targets with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 16, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Polonium<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 116 protons in the nucleus<br>• 116 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Livermorium-293 (half-life: approx. 60 milliseconds)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d¹⁰ 7s² 7p⁴ (predicted)<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 16 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, silvery metal at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — approx. 800°C (estimated)<br>• Melting point — approx. 450°C (estimated)<br>• High density (approx. 12.9 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a body-centered cubic (BCC) crystal structure<br>• Displaying significant relativistic effects on its physical properties<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits stable +2 and +4 oxidation states (+2 is predicted to be more stable)<br>• Behaves chemically like its lighter Group 16 homologs (Tellurium, Polonium)<br>• Forms stable halides and oxides (predicted based on trends)<br>• Chemistry is exceptionally difficult to study due to millisecond half-lives<br>• Displays significant relativistic effects in its valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Livermorium Isotopes</b><br>• Livermorium has no stable isotopes; over 4 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Livermorium-293 (²⁹³Lv) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 60 milliseconds)<br>• Livermorium-290 (²⁹⁰Lv) — originally discovered in 2000<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Curium bombarded with Calcium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of targets in linear accelerators<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Curium-248 with Calcium-48 ions<br>• Purified via specialized fast automated chemical separation systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Livermorium</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of superheavy atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 7p electron shell behavior<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the limits of atomic stability<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on heavy chalcogens<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the chemical trends in Group 16 beyond Polonium<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• Named in honor of the laboratory that co-discovered several superheavy elements<br>• Key element for testing the stability of the 7th row of the periodic table<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability",
    "system.tennessine.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Ts<br>• Atomic Number — 117<br>• A highly radioactive transactinide; predicted to be a metallic halogen<br>• Named after the state of Tennessee, USA, home to several discovery institutions<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy targets with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 17, predicted to be a heavier homolog of Astatine<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 117 protons in the nucleus<br>• 117 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most stable isotope is Tennessine-294 (half-life: approx. 80 milliseconds)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d¹⁰ 7s² 7p⁵ (predicted)<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 17 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a dense, metallic solid at room temperature<br>• Boiling point — approx. 550°C (estimated)<br>• Melting point — approx. 400°C (estimated)<br>• High density (approx. 7.2 g/cm³) and metallic conductivity predicted<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a body-centered cubic (BCC) crystal structure<br>• Displaying extreme relativistic effects on its physical properties<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to react with oxygen and moisture instantly<br>• Exhibits multiple oxidation states: -1, +1, +3, and +5 (+1 and +3 are predicted)<br>• Behaves chemically more like a metal than its lighter Group 17 homologs (Iodine, Astatine)<br>• Predicted to form stable halides and complex ions (based on trends)<br>• Chemistry is exceptionally difficult to study due to millisecond half-lives<br>• Displays extreme relativistic effects in its valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Tennessine Isotopes</b><br>• Tennessine has no stable isotopes; only 2 known radioisotopes exist<br>• Tennessine-294 (²⁹⁴Ts) — longest-lived isotope (half-life: 80 milliseconds)<br>• Tennessine-293 (²⁹³Ts) — originally discovered in 2010<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Berkelium bombarded with Calcium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of targets in linear accelerators<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Berkelium-249 with Calcium-48 ions<br>• Purified via specialized fast automated chemical separation systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Tennessine</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the properties of superheavy atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the 7p electron shell behavior near the end of row 7<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the limits of atomic stability<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing relativistic effects on heavy halogens<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Critical for understanding the chemical trends in Group 17 beyond Astatine<br>• Powerful tool for testing advanced relativistic quantum models of heavy atoms<br>• Named in honor of the US state that is a global center for nuclear research<br>• Key element for testing the stability of the 7th row of the periodic table<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of nuclear stability",
    "system.oganesson.details": "<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Og<br>• Atomic Number — 118<br>• A highly radioactive transactinide; the final element in the periodic table<br>• Named after Yuri Oganessian, a giant of superheavy element discovery<br>• Produced in particle accelerators by bombarding heavy targets with light ions<br>• Extremely short-lived; study is limited to specialized experimental setups<br>• Member of Group 18, predicted to be a reactive solid, not a noble gas<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 118 protons in the nucleus<br>• 118 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Only characterizable isotope is Oganesson-294 (half-life: approx. 0.9 milliseconds)<br>• Electron configuration — [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d¹⁰ 7s² 7p⁶ (predicted shell closure)<br>• Located in the 7th period and group 18 (final element) of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Predicted to be a reactive solid or liquid at room temperature, not a gas<br>• Boiling point — approx. 80°C (exceptionally high for a Group 18 element)<br>• Melting point — approx. 52°C (predicted to be solid near room temp)<br>• Density and conductivity are unknown but predicted to be metallic-like<br>• Study is conducted on individual atoms due to extreme radioactivity and scarcity<br>• Predicted to have a face-centered cubic (FCC) crystal structure<br>• Displaying the most extreme relativistic effects in the entire periodic table<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Highly reactive: predicted to be the most reactive element in Group 18<br>• Exhibits stable +2 and +4 oxidation states (predicted based on trends)<br>• Behaves chemically more like a metal or a reactive solid than a noble gas<br>• Predicted to form stable halides (e.g., OgF₄) and complex ions<br>• Chemistry is exceptionally difficult to study due to sub-millisecond half-lives<br>• Displays the ultimate relativistic effects in valence electron behavior<br><br><b>Oganesson Isotopes</b><br>• Oganesson has no stable isotopes; only 1 known radioisotope exists<br>• Oganesson-294 (²⁹⁴Og) — only characterizable isotope (half-life: 0.9 ms)<br>• Originally discovered in 2002 via bombardment of Californium with Calcium<br>• Decays primarily through alpha emission or spontaneous fission<br>• All isotopes are strictly synthetic; not found in nature in detectable amounts<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Non-existent in nature: exclusively produced by human nuclear activity<br>• Global presence is virtually zero outside of specialized particle accelerators<br>• Managed as a fleeting, high-value radioisotope for fundamental science<br>• Synthesis requires the use of heavy targets like Californium bombarded with Calcium<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Produced via heavy-ion bombardment of targets in linear accelerators<br>• Typical reaction: bombardment of Californium-249 with Calcium-48 ions<br>• Purified via specialized fast automated chemical separation systems<br>• Metal form has never been produced in bulk due to extreme instability<br><br><b>Applications of Oganesson</b><br>• Science: used as a probe to study the ultimate properties of atoms<br>• Research: investigation of the total 7p shell closure and relativistic effects<br>• Nuclear Physics: probe for studying the very end of the periodic table<br>• Theoretical Chemistry: testing the limits of atomic and chemical theory<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Tech</b><br>• Represents the 'finish line' of the current periodic table (Element 118)<br>• Powerful tool for testing the most advanced relativistic quantum models<br>• Named in honor of the living scientist who co-discovered many superheavy elements<br>• Key element for testing the validity of the Periodic Law at its ultimate boundary<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Theoretical Physics — exploring the boundaries of the known universe",
